1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:18,051
A makeover project
for your most unhinged leftovers.

2
00:00:18,118 --> 00:00:21,788
The best chefs in Korea
will turn your fridge inside out.

3
00:00:21,855 --> 00:00:23,823
The classy cooking show has returned.

4
00:00:23,890 --> 00:00:26,960
-<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>!
-<i>My Fridge</i>!

5
00:00:28,695 --> 00:00:31,498
AS ALWAYS, THE TRUSTWORTHY CHEFS ARE HERE

6
00:00:31,564 --> 00:00:35,635
We're about to meet the guests
who brought their fridges today,

7
00:00:35,702 --> 00:00:38,371
two people with great vibes
that radiate charisma

8
00:00:38,438 --> 00:00:40,440
just by their sheer presence.

9
00:00:40,507 --> 00:00:43,043
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

10
00:00:43,109 --> 00:00:44,477
Come on out!

11
00:00:46,513 --> 00:00:47,714
Wow.

12
00:00:47,781 --> 00:00:49,082
GENUINELY IMPRESSED

13
00:00:49,916 --> 00:00:51,384
The two wonderful guests,

14
00:00:51,451 --> 00:00:55,321
actors Go Soo and Lee Jong-hyuk!
Come on out!

15
00:00:55,388 --> 00:00:57,190
GO SOO & LEE JONG-HYUK

16
00:00:57,257 --> 00:00:59,993
-Please say hello.
-They haven't aged a day.

17
00:01:00,060 --> 00:01:01,194
NODDING

18
00:01:01,261 --> 00:01:03,430
-Hello.
-Goodness, hello.

19
00:01:03,930 --> 00:01:04,864
OOZING CHARISMA

20
00:01:04,931 --> 00:01:06,499
QUIET…

21
00:01:06,566 --> 00:01:07,600
CRACK

22
00:01:08,435 --> 00:01:09,803
You crack one open
as soon as you get here?

23
00:01:10,370 --> 00:01:11,271
You must've been thirsty.

24
00:01:11,337 --> 00:01:12,505
I'm nervous.

25
00:01:13,073 --> 00:01:14,874
Allow me to introduce this man.

26
00:01:14,941 --> 00:01:15,942
The definition of handsomeness.

27
00:01:16,443 --> 00:01:18,344
A LIVING, BREATHING SCULPTURE

28
00:01:18,411 --> 00:01:20,080
IRREFUTABLY GOOD-LOOKING

29
00:01:20,146 --> 00:01:22,015
The charming actor, Go Soo!

30
00:01:22,082 --> 00:01:23,683
BOWING

31
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:26,319
WELCOME TO THE SHOW

32
00:01:26,386 --> 00:01:27,954
Please say hello to the viewers.

33
00:01:28,788 --> 00:01:30,356
-Where do I look?
-Over there.

34
00:01:30,423 --> 00:01:32,425
I see. Yes, hello.

35
00:01:32,492 --> 00:01:35,128
-The cameras are all hidden.
-They're hiding.

36
00:01:35,195 --> 00:01:36,796
Hello, it's great to be here.

37
00:01:36,863 --> 00:01:38,598
-I'm Go Soo.
-Yes, okay.

38
00:01:39,799 --> 00:01:41,267
Look at Eun-yeong's face.

39
00:01:41,334 --> 00:01:42,569
You're still the same.

40
00:01:42,635 --> 00:01:44,971
…CAN'T HIDE HER SMILE

41
00:01:45,038 --> 00:01:47,073
-Look at Chef Eun-yeong.
-Yes?

42
00:01:47,140 --> 00:01:49,375
-She's out of it. So mesmerized.
-It's not that.

43
00:01:49,442 --> 00:01:51,711
How does a person look that good?

44
00:01:52,212 --> 00:01:53,847
THANK YOU

45
00:01:54,414 --> 00:01:55,582
SLURP…
(NOTICING HIM)

46
00:01:55,648 --> 00:01:58,618
-Let me introduce the soda-drinking guy.
-Yes, the next man.

47
00:01:58,685 --> 00:02:00,286
This is Min-gook's dad,

48
00:02:00,353 --> 00:02:02,322
I'm Ri-hwan's dad,

49
00:02:02,388 --> 00:02:04,224
and he's Joon-su's dad.

50
00:02:04,290 --> 00:02:07,861
-The charismatic actor, Lee Jong-hyuk!
-Lee Jong-hyuk!

51
00:02:07,927 --> 00:02:09,496
IT'S GREAT TO SEE YOU

52
00:02:09,562 --> 00:02:11,798
It's great to be here. I'm Lee Jong-hyuk.

53
00:02:13,466 --> 00:02:17,303
Soo, you aren't someone
we often see on variety shows,

54
00:02:17,370 --> 00:02:18,838
but have you watched our show?

55
00:02:18,905 --> 00:02:19,873
Yes, of course.

56
00:02:19,939 --> 00:02:23,209
I've been watching this
since the early days.

57
00:02:23,276 --> 00:02:25,178
The tagline is "Since 2014,"

58
00:02:25,245 --> 00:02:26,412
-so since then?
-Of course.

59
00:02:26,980 --> 00:02:28,214
REALLY?

60
00:02:28,281 --> 00:02:29,782
Compared to then, the show has become

61
00:02:29,849 --> 00:02:30,950
rather fancy.

62
00:02:31,017 --> 00:02:32,285
How so?

63
00:02:32,352 --> 00:02:34,420
How can I put this?
Back then, it was simple.

64
00:02:34,487 --> 00:02:36,122
-Simple and homey?
-It was much smaller.

65
00:02:36,189 --> 00:02:37,557
<i>That's how the show felt.</i>

66
00:02:37,624 --> 00:02:41,060
But as time went by,
it became much more dynamic

67
00:02:41,127 --> 00:02:43,429
-and fancier.
-I see.

68
00:02:43,496 --> 00:02:45,999
-You must be familiar with the chefs.
-Of course.

69
00:02:46,065 --> 00:02:48,968
It's such an honor to be invited here.

70
00:02:49,035 --> 00:02:51,371
I'm not sure
if I can say something like this,

71
00:02:52,272 --> 00:02:53,773
but it feels like a dream.

72
00:02:53,840 --> 00:02:54,874
TOUCHED

73
00:02:54,941 --> 00:02:56,376
-Are we that big?
-Like a dream.

74
00:02:56,442 --> 00:02:57,944
WE ARE THAT BIG, NAM-NO

75
00:02:58,011 --> 00:03:00,113
You'll see later

76
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:02,115
that my fridge is quite humble.

77
00:03:03,082 --> 00:03:05,418
But despite that,

78
00:03:05,485 --> 00:03:07,820
-why am I so excited?
-He's excited.

79
00:03:07,887 --> 00:03:09,756
HE HAS A QUIRKY SIDE!

80
00:03:09,822 --> 00:03:12,458
He's rarely on variety shows,
so I can tell how genuine he is.

81
00:03:12,959 --> 00:03:15,328
UNBELIEVABLE MUKBANG

82
00:03:15,395 --> 00:03:16,596
THE MASTER MUKBANGER

83
00:03:16,663 --> 00:03:17,597
So? What does it taste like?

84
00:03:18,198 --> 00:03:19,199
Do you want to know?

85
00:03:19,265 --> 00:03:20,500
Of course, we do.

86
00:03:20,567 --> 00:03:21,768
AN UNPREDICTABLE REVIEW

87
00:03:21,834 --> 00:03:23,169
You must be dying to know.

88
00:03:23,236 --> 00:03:24,304
Yes, we are.

89
00:03:24,370 --> 00:03:26,172
You've probably never had
anything like this.

90
00:03:26,239 --> 00:03:27,340
Of course not.

91
00:03:27,907 --> 00:03:30,376
STAY TUNED TO WITNESS
A COMPLETELY NEW STYLE OF FOOD REVIEWS

92
00:03:30,443 --> 00:03:32,212
He's so good at teasing us.

93
00:03:32,278 --> 00:03:34,447
If he brought that up already,
he must honestly mean he has nothing.

94
00:03:34,514 --> 00:03:36,082
He seems to be telling the truth.

95
00:03:36,149 --> 00:03:37,750
What's the relationship here?

96
00:03:37,817 --> 00:03:39,586
-Jong-hyuk, you're older, right?
-Yes.

97
00:03:39,652 --> 00:03:40,687
Who debuted earlier?

98
00:03:40,753 --> 00:03:42,055
He must've debuted much earlier.

99
00:03:42,121 --> 00:03:45,725
It must've been 20 years ago or so

100
00:03:45,792 --> 00:03:48,795
-when we were in the same TV series.
-The same show? 20 years ago?

101
00:03:48,861 --> 00:03:51,264
It was called <i>Green Rose</i>.

102
00:03:51,331 --> 00:03:53,600
It's our first time reuniting
after that show's wrap party.

103
00:03:53,666 --> 00:03:55,468
Wow, it's been ages.

104
00:03:55,535 --> 00:03:57,337
-Has it been 20 years?
-Yes.

105
00:03:57,403 --> 00:04:00,173
I see. Ever since <i>Green Rose</i>?

106
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:03,509
I felt my heart race to see him up close.

107
00:04:03,576 --> 00:04:04,811
It's nice to see him again.

108
00:04:04,877 --> 00:04:08,381
They're seeing each other after 20 years,
thanks to <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

109
00:04:08,448 --> 00:04:11,050
I hear they came here
to promote something.

110
00:04:11,117 --> 00:04:13,019
-Really?
-I hear that's the reason.

111
00:04:13,086 --> 00:04:14,754
In my case, it's a stage production

112
00:04:14,821 --> 00:04:16,990
-called <i>Beginning</i>.
-<i>Beginning</i>?

113
00:04:17,056 --> 00:04:18,825
Something that begins.

114
00:04:18,891 --> 00:04:21,327
It's about a man who lives alone
after getting divorced.

115
00:04:21,394 --> 00:04:25,031
<i>He gets to spend the late night</i>
<i>with a very attractive woman.</i>

116
00:04:26,466 --> 00:04:29,569
So the man and the woman
spend the late night alone…

117
00:04:29,636 --> 00:04:30,770
-Alone?
-…talking to each other.

118
00:04:30,837 --> 00:04:33,306
It's an intense and honest story.

119
00:04:33,373 --> 00:04:35,241
-Late in the night?
-That's the beginning?

120
00:04:35,308 --> 00:04:37,243
We never step off the stage.

121
00:04:38,177 --> 00:04:39,746
-Yes, we're up there the whole time.
-A two-person play?

122
00:04:40,313 --> 00:04:42,215
Almost to a point that we're burnt out.

123
00:04:42,282 --> 00:04:43,416
Do you two only talk?

124
00:04:44,817 --> 00:04:46,886
We talk and do other stuff too.

125
00:04:47,920 --> 00:04:50,556
-I wanted to know if they just talked.
-Then what?

126
00:04:50,623 --> 00:04:52,992
It's a play, so we act.

127
00:04:53,059 --> 00:04:54,661
THEY MUST DO A BUNCH OF STUFF…

128
00:04:54,727 --> 00:04:57,497
Soo, if you have anything to promote,
this is your chance.

129
00:04:57,563 --> 00:05:00,933
Last year, I filmed a series
called <i>Reverse</i>.

130
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,368
Rivers?

131
00:05:02,935 --> 00:05:03,936
No.

132
00:05:05,471 --> 00:05:07,006
SORRY

133
00:05:07,073 --> 00:05:08,408
PULLS A DAD JOKE…

134
00:05:08,975 --> 00:05:10,510
LOVES IT
HEHEHE…

135
00:05:11,077 --> 00:05:12,779
IT'S REVERSE

136
00:05:12,845 --> 00:05:15,915
I hear that my fiancée gets
into an accident.

137
00:05:16,282 --> 00:05:17,817
HIS FIANCÉE
GETS INTO A MYSTERIOUS ACCIDENT

138
00:05:17,884 --> 00:05:19,952
<i>I run over to the hospital,</i>

139
00:05:20,520 --> 00:05:23,056
-but she doesn't recognize me.
-Oh, no.

140
00:05:23,122 --> 00:05:25,158
That's how the story begins.

141
00:05:25,224 --> 00:05:26,626
A MYSTERY THRILLER
UNCOVERING HIDDEN TRUTHS

142
00:05:26,693 --> 00:05:28,027
So that's how it begins.

143
00:05:28,094 --> 00:05:29,095
SHOW LOTS OF INTEREST IN REVERSE

144
00:05:29,162 --> 00:05:32,231
Soo is nicknamed GoVid,

145
00:05:32,298 --> 00:05:36,469
who outshines Michelangelo's David,
which he probably gets all the time.

146
00:05:36,536 --> 00:05:38,438
You might be sick of hearing it.

147
00:05:38,504 --> 00:05:42,275
Now, we have a transcript
of something he said in the green room.

148
00:05:42,342 --> 00:05:44,711
-What?
-We're even tapping guests now?

149
00:05:45,345 --> 00:05:46,646
CHEF & MY FRIDGE WIRETAPS EVERYONE

150
00:05:46,713 --> 00:05:48,981
It's the first time
we tapped the guest green room.

151
00:05:49,048 --> 00:05:50,650
We make use of everything entertaining.

152
00:05:50,717 --> 00:05:52,852
Soo said something like this.

153
00:05:52,919 --> 00:05:55,455
<i>"People tell me that I'm good-looking,</i>

154
00:05:55,521 --> 00:05:57,990
<i>but isn't it something they say</i>
<i>out of common courtesy?"</i>

155
00:05:58,057 --> 00:05:59,892
<i>"Are they really saying that</i>
<i>because I'm good-looking?"</i>

156
00:05:59,959 --> 00:06:02,395
I heard you were suspicious
of people's intentions.

157
00:06:02,462 --> 00:06:04,797
When we greet others, we say things like,

158
00:06:04,864 --> 00:06:06,399
"Looking good" or "You look healthy."

159
00:06:06,466 --> 00:06:09,102
We do that out of courtesy, don't we?

160
00:06:09,168 --> 00:06:10,636
I don't think it's any different.

161
00:06:10,703 --> 00:06:11,938
No one has been courteous to me.

162
00:06:12,004 --> 00:06:13,139
I've never heard it, either.

163
00:06:13,206 --> 00:06:15,308
You do not think you're all that handsome?

164
00:06:15,375 --> 00:06:17,310
That's something I really want to hear.

165
00:06:18,077 --> 00:06:19,245
You think so, don't you?

166
00:06:19,312 --> 00:06:21,180
If you don't, it just means

167
00:06:21,247 --> 00:06:22,782
-you have zero self-awareness.
-These days,

168
00:06:22,849 --> 00:06:26,252
there are way too many cool
and good-looking people, so not me.

169
00:06:26,319 --> 00:06:27,787
When you look in the mirror,

170
00:06:27,854 --> 00:06:30,056
don't you go,
"Hey, I'm looking pretty good today"?

171
00:06:30,123 --> 00:06:32,191
You do that, right?
After washing your face.

172
00:06:32,258 --> 00:06:34,527
Do you actually do that?

173
00:06:34,594 --> 00:06:35,728
All men do that.

174
00:06:35,795 --> 00:06:37,029
-I did it today.
-Right?

175
00:06:37,096 --> 00:06:38,598
-Everyone does it.
-I did it today.

176
00:06:38,664 --> 00:06:39,665
-Don't.
-I look okay today.

177
00:06:39,732 --> 00:06:41,667
That's just egotistical. Don't do it.

178
00:06:41,734 --> 00:06:43,503
-I even took a selfie.
-A selfie?

179
00:06:43,569 --> 00:06:45,004
See? He takes selfies.

180
00:06:45,071 --> 00:06:46,506
-When your hair's all wet, right?
-I like good.

181
00:06:46,572 --> 00:06:48,474
THE WET IMAGE OF ME…
SAVED TO MY PHONE

182
00:06:48,541 --> 00:06:51,411
This is really wonderful. I spoke up

183
00:06:51,477 --> 00:06:54,614
and got to hear from the chefs.

184
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:56,149
I'm really glad.

185
00:06:56,215 --> 00:06:57,517
Thank you. I mean it.

186
00:06:58,184 --> 00:07:00,920
Soo, do you not take selfies often?

187
00:07:00,987 --> 00:07:04,090
-I used to, but I've given up.
-Why?

188
00:07:04,157 --> 00:07:06,325
-I only get one good shot after 500 takes.
-Just one?

189
00:07:06,392 --> 00:07:08,461
RELATABLE NEWS
EVEN GOVID MUST TAKE 500 SELFIES

190
00:07:09,028 --> 00:07:11,097
Any shot would look great.

191
00:07:11,164 --> 00:07:13,933
We heard Soo had spent
his entire life looking gorgeous,

192
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:17,403
-so we got our hands on some pictures.
-Pictures?

193
00:07:17,470 --> 00:07:19,305
Why don't we take a look?

194
00:07:19,372 --> 00:07:21,340
These are all Soo's pictures.

195
00:07:22,341 --> 00:07:23,376
My gosh.

196
00:07:23,443 --> 00:07:24,844
Look at that baby.

197
00:07:24,911 --> 00:07:27,480
-Wait, that baby…
-It's hard for a baby to look handsome.

198
00:07:27,547 --> 00:07:29,749
-How is that baby so handsome?
-He has huge eyes!

199
00:07:30,450 --> 00:07:32,685
TA-DA

200
00:07:33,853 --> 00:07:36,155
Can you tell us when those were?

201
00:07:36,222 --> 00:07:39,225
-On the left, probably about 100 days old.
-About 100 days old.

202
00:07:39,292 --> 00:07:43,362
In the middle is a yearbook picture
I took as a senior in high school.

203
00:07:43,429 --> 00:07:46,098
-He was in high school.
-He still looks the same.

204
00:07:46,165 --> 00:07:47,934
The right is my college graduation photo.

205
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:51,771
I was ill that day, but I remember going
and taking the picture.

206
00:07:51,838 --> 00:07:53,105
He's handsome even when he's ill.

207
00:07:53,673 --> 00:07:55,074
HIS APPEARANCE IS IN TOP HEALTH

208
00:07:55,141 --> 00:07:56,576
What if you hadn't been ill?

209
00:07:56,642 --> 00:07:58,478
This may be an odd question,

210
00:07:58,544 --> 00:08:00,713
but as you look around,

211
00:08:00,780 --> 00:08:04,584
have you found any chefs
you thought were good-looking?

212
00:08:05,151 --> 00:08:07,186
REARRANGING HIS SHORT LIMBS

213
00:08:07,253 --> 00:08:09,956
Someone worthy of the nickname
David of the show?

214
00:08:10,022 --> 00:08:11,924
Stop looking at me and making me laugh.

215
00:08:11,991 --> 00:08:14,126
Pick one to be the cover model
for <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

216
00:08:14,193 --> 00:08:16,329
Well, instead of that…

217
00:08:16,395 --> 00:08:18,464
He's dodging the question.

218
00:08:18,531 --> 00:08:21,100
…the one I want to visit…

219
00:08:21,167 --> 00:08:24,170
-The cover model of the show.
-The one I want to visit and dine at is--

220
00:08:24,237 --> 00:08:27,006
Sure. Let's say we're shooting a poster.

221
00:08:27,073 --> 00:08:30,076
Whose picture
should go in the dead center?

222
00:08:30,142 --> 00:08:32,645
-Give us your answer.
-In that case,

223
00:08:32,712 --> 00:08:34,780
let me share it with you right now.

224
00:08:36,015 --> 00:08:37,617
Chef Sam.

225
00:08:37,683 --> 00:08:39,418
-Me?
-He said it. It's Chef Sam!

226
00:08:40,152 --> 00:08:42,321
-If we're to do a poster shoot…
-He seems to be

227
00:08:42,388 --> 00:08:45,558
-on the calm side, just like me.
-His personality?

228
00:08:45,625 --> 00:08:47,360
He has changed lately.

229
00:08:47,426 --> 00:08:49,562
He destroys people with his canines.

230
00:08:49,629 --> 00:08:51,731
Just now, Sam had been… Jeez.

231
00:08:51,797 --> 00:08:53,099
He has a potty mouth too.

232
00:08:53,165 --> 00:08:55,735
-He got mad last time for losing.
-Yes, that he lost.

233
00:08:55,801 --> 00:08:57,136
How do you feel?

234
00:08:57,203 --> 00:08:59,338
I forgot all about the previous episode.

235
00:08:59,906 --> 00:09:01,240
SUDDENLY IN HIS BEST CONDITION

236
00:09:01,307 --> 00:09:03,042
Don't you suddenly feel great?

237
00:09:03,109 --> 00:09:05,311
-Yes, I'm feeling wonderful.
-That's great.

238
00:09:05,378 --> 00:09:09,015
Chef Eun-yeong is the only woman here,
so who's the best looking among the chefs?

239
00:09:09,081 --> 00:09:12,351
You know,
I don't even have to think about it.

240
00:09:12,418 --> 00:09:14,620
-The show's David would be
-David.

241
00:09:14,687 --> 00:09:15,821
Chef Jong-won.

242
00:09:15,888 --> 00:09:16,923
NO SURPRISE

243
00:09:18,524 --> 00:09:19,959
-She's so boring.
-Everyone looks down.

244
00:09:20,526 --> 00:09:21,661
SULKING

245
00:09:21,727 --> 00:09:23,596
-This is a variety show.
-It's so obvious.

246
00:09:23,663 --> 00:09:26,032
-I can't even lie about that.
-What if we exclude him?

247
00:09:26,098 --> 00:09:27,600
-The second good-looking one.
-Exclude him?

248
00:09:27,667 --> 00:09:28,834
The second?

249
00:09:28,901 --> 00:09:30,102
That's really hard.

250
00:09:30,169 --> 00:09:32,738
THE TOUGHEST DILEMMA OF HER LIFE

251
00:09:33,306 --> 00:09:34,540
WE GET THAT YOU DON'T WANT TO PICK

252
00:09:34,607 --> 00:09:35,975
It's that hard?

253
00:09:36,042 --> 00:09:37,643
It's way too hard.

254
00:09:37,710 --> 00:09:40,079
-I don't even want to know anyway.
-Chef Eun-yeong seemed…

255
00:09:40,146 --> 00:09:42,281
-I'm starting to feel down.
-…appalled by the question.

256
00:09:42,348 --> 00:09:43,883
-My gosh.
-She's unbelievable.

257
00:09:43,950 --> 00:09:45,851
Wait, Nam-no has a different thought.

258
00:09:45,918 --> 00:09:48,621
-What?
-He's an avid fan of Jong-won's,

259
00:09:48,688 --> 00:09:50,256
but the show's David is someone else?

260
00:09:50,323 --> 00:09:51,857
-Who is it?
-Not you, right?

261
00:09:51,924 --> 00:09:53,926
-Come on.
-You'd better be fair.

262
00:09:53,993 --> 00:09:54,961
I think

263
00:09:55,027 --> 00:09:57,096
-it's Chef Hyun-suk.
-I see.

264
00:09:57,163 --> 00:09:58,864
It's his dark seductiveness.

265
00:09:58,931 --> 00:10:00,399
-Dark and seductive?
-Dark?

266
00:10:00,466 --> 00:10:03,336
-Dark?
-On the days when he hasn't slept,

267
00:10:03,402 --> 00:10:05,204
his eyes look a little bloated,

268
00:10:05,271 --> 00:10:07,840
reminding me of Ju Ji-hoon.

269
00:10:07,907 --> 00:10:09,442
-What?
-Or Lee Dong-wook.

270
00:10:09,508 --> 00:10:11,210
Lee Dong-wook? He looks like them?

271
00:10:11,277 --> 00:10:12,411
I'm sorry.

272
00:10:13,145 --> 00:10:14,146
Just kill me now.

273
00:10:14,714 --> 00:10:16,315
Do you know what Ju Ji-hoon looks like?

274
00:10:17,116 --> 00:10:18,250
YOU…

275
00:10:18,317 --> 00:10:19,986
-You've never met Dong-wook, right?
-No.

276
00:10:20,052 --> 00:10:21,287
I've never met him.

277
00:10:23,055 --> 00:10:26,125
You're making a huge mistake.
We have actors here today.

278
00:10:26,192 --> 00:10:28,794
I've worked with Dong-wook, and…

279
00:10:28,861 --> 00:10:31,130
HAS A LOT TO SAY BUT WON'T…

280
00:10:31,731 --> 00:10:33,032
Is this how the show operates?

281
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,101
IT'S ALWAYS LIKE THIS

282
00:10:35,167 --> 00:10:37,737
Yes, we like to encourage one another.

283
00:10:37,803 --> 00:10:40,506
I see you say rude things
to people you haven't even met.

284
00:10:41,073 --> 00:10:42,908
EITHER DISCOURTEOUS OR DOWNRIGHT RUDE

285
00:10:42,975 --> 00:10:44,410
But they all cook well.

286
00:10:44,477 --> 00:10:46,979
-Yes, of course.
-Anyway, that was fun.

287
00:10:47,046 --> 00:10:50,216
Wait a second.
I just found out about this today.

288
00:10:50,282 --> 00:10:52,885
Go Soo is his real birth name.

289
00:10:52,952 --> 00:10:54,253
EVEN HIS NAME IS COOL

290
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:57,590
-That's so cool.
-My grandmother named me.

291
00:10:57,657 --> 00:10:59,725
-It suits him so well.
-Is it in Chinese characters?

292
00:10:59,792 --> 00:11:01,761
-Yes, Soo means waterside.
-Waterside.

293
00:11:01,827 --> 00:11:03,562
HIGH "GO", WATERSIDE "SOO"

294
00:11:03,629 --> 00:11:06,666
People historically lived
along the waters, right?

295
00:11:06,732 --> 00:11:08,567
So she wanted my life
to be full of people.

296
00:11:08,634 --> 00:11:10,603
-I see.
-That's a nice meaning.

297
00:11:10,670 --> 00:11:12,371
Ever have any misunderstandings
with your name?

298
00:11:12,438 --> 00:11:15,174
-I have so many stories around my name.
-I'm sure.

299
00:11:15,241 --> 00:11:17,376
These days, many restaurants

300
00:11:18,077 --> 00:11:19,979
put up a picture of me.

301
00:11:20,046 --> 00:11:21,847
-Restaurants?
-Yes.

302
00:11:21,914 --> 00:11:23,382
-Because of his name.
-I've seen it.

303
00:11:23,449 --> 00:11:25,618
-Additional <i>gosu</i>, as in cilantro.
-<i>Gosu</i>.

304
00:11:25,685 --> 00:11:27,153
They use his picture instead?

305
00:11:27,219 --> 00:11:28,220
An actual picture of him?

306
00:11:28,287 --> 00:11:31,724
-Yes, and it says, "Extra <i>gosu</i>."
-For those who want extra cilantro.

307
00:11:31,791 --> 00:11:33,526
-I saw it on a kiosk.
-His face is on it.

308
00:11:33,592 --> 00:11:36,228
He said this in an interview once
regarding his name.

309
00:11:36,295 --> 00:11:38,631
"I'm grateful for <i>gosu</i>, the herb."

310
00:11:38,698 --> 00:11:41,033
"Even when I'm on hiatus,

311
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:43,836
<i>gosu</i> the herb
makes sure that I'm never forgotten."

312
00:11:43,903 --> 00:11:46,872
-That's true.
-Thanks to the pictures at restaurants.

313
00:11:46,939 --> 00:11:49,175
In that case, I can probably ask you this.

314
00:11:49,241 --> 00:11:50,509
Do you like <i>gosu</i>, cilantro?

315
00:11:52,311 --> 00:11:55,347
-It's either a hit or miss.
-I'm curious.

316
00:11:55,414 --> 00:11:58,017
-May I be honest?
-Yes, honestly.

317
00:11:58,084 --> 00:11:59,418
Many people must want to know.

318
00:11:59,485 --> 00:12:01,854
Does Go Soo the actor like <i>gosu</i> the herb?

319
00:12:01,921 --> 00:12:03,155
I'm curious.

320
00:12:03,222 --> 00:12:07,827
Back in 2010, I went to Southeast Asia
to shoot something.

321
00:12:07,893 --> 00:12:09,695
There was nothing I could eat

322
00:12:09,762 --> 00:12:12,798
-unless I could handle cilantro.
-Right.

323
00:12:12,865 --> 00:12:14,967
So I began to eat it.

324
00:12:15,034 --> 00:12:16,869
Since then,

325
00:12:16,936 --> 00:12:19,138
I learned that
there were so many delicious dishes.

326
00:12:19,205 --> 00:12:21,107
-Yes, once you get over the hurdle.
-Yes.

327
00:12:21,173 --> 00:12:23,275
I got addicted to it after that,

328
00:12:23,342 --> 00:12:26,679
-and I still enjoy it very much.
-That's the case.

329
00:12:26,746 --> 00:12:29,648
Go Soo is addicted to <i>gosu</i>.

330
00:12:29,715 --> 00:12:31,751
That's the conclusion.

331
00:12:31,817 --> 00:12:32,818
Go Soo

332
00:12:32,885 --> 00:12:34,120
does not ghost <i>gosu</i>.

333
00:12:34,186 --> 00:12:35,454
Isn't that funnier?

334
00:12:35,521 --> 00:12:37,490
-I'm sorry.
-That guy.

335
00:12:37,556 --> 00:12:39,158
We'll use my line instead.

336
00:12:39,725 --> 00:12:41,494
I THOUGHT IT WAS FUNNY…

337
00:12:41,560 --> 00:12:43,562
-We're here with the best guest.
-Yes.

338
00:12:43,629 --> 00:12:45,064
His name sounds like an herb.

339
00:12:45,131 --> 00:12:46,932
We have a food ingredient as a guest.

340
00:12:46,999 --> 00:12:49,135
-Yes, our guest is a food ingredient.
-I'm sorry.

341
00:12:49,201 --> 00:12:50,503
LET'S LOOK FOR GOSU IN GO SOO'S FRIDGE

342
00:12:50,569 --> 00:12:53,939
We're about to go through Soo's fridge.

343
00:12:54,006 --> 00:12:57,309
We hear you're using that fridge alone.

344
00:12:58,477 --> 00:13:01,180
My family fridge has too many ingredients.

345
00:13:01,247 --> 00:13:03,516
-Yes.
-I thought the abundance of ingredients

346
00:13:03,582 --> 00:13:05,184
would make it too easy for all of you.

347
00:13:05,251 --> 00:13:06,452
That's right.

348
00:13:06,519 --> 00:13:08,387
-His fridge is going to whip us.
-It's funnier

349
00:13:08,454 --> 00:13:10,556
-when it's lacking.
-It was about time we got whipped.

350
00:13:10,623 --> 00:13:12,057
I watched the episodes

351
00:13:12,124 --> 00:13:14,093
and saw that people had
amazing ingredients.

352
00:13:14,160 --> 00:13:15,461
HE KNOWS THE SHOW WELL

353
00:13:15,528 --> 00:13:16,595
With that many ingredients,

354
00:13:16,662 --> 00:13:17,696
even I could do it.

355
00:13:17,763 --> 00:13:20,533
GO SOO'S PROVOCATION

356
00:13:20,599 --> 00:13:22,301
You just drove it home!

357
00:13:22,368 --> 00:13:25,037
Just stir-fry some stuff
and throw in salt.

358
00:13:25,104 --> 00:13:26,839
-Even I could do that.
-Anyone could.

359
00:13:26,906 --> 00:13:29,008
He's been monitoring our show.

360
00:13:29,074 --> 00:13:32,044
-He knows how to make the show fun.
-That's why he's an expert.

361
00:13:32,111 --> 00:13:34,613
So you use this one alone?

362
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:38,717
Yes, my kids get irked
and close it right away after opening it.

363
00:13:40,152 --> 00:13:42,788
But when I open the family fridge,

364
00:13:42,855 --> 00:13:44,156
I end up craving everything.

365
00:13:45,191 --> 00:13:46,525
-You're on a diet.
-To keep in shape.

366
00:13:46,592 --> 00:13:49,595
That's why my fridge is humble.

367
00:13:50,329 --> 00:13:53,632
His family has another fridge,
so this is his personal one

368
00:13:53,699 --> 00:13:55,467
-to stay in shape.
-That's right.

369
00:13:55,534 --> 00:13:58,003
Also, we'll check it out to see
if he has <i>gosu</i>, cilantro.

370
00:13:58,571 --> 00:14:00,406
DOES GO SOO KEEP GOSU IN HIS FRIDGE?

371
00:14:00,472 --> 00:14:02,474
Does Go Soo have <i>gosu</i> in his fridge?

372
00:14:02,541 --> 00:14:05,344
-Does he enjoy cilantro at home?
-That's important.

373
00:14:05,411 --> 00:14:07,680
Let's find out what his diet is like.

374
00:14:07,746 --> 00:14:09,782
-We present Soo's fridge!
-Fridge!

375
00:14:10,482 --> 00:14:11,383
-Fridge!
-Fridge!

376
00:14:12,251 --> 00:14:14,486
EVERYONE GROANS

377
00:14:15,054 --> 00:14:17,323
PRESENTING GO SOO'S FRIDGE

378
00:14:18,324 --> 00:14:19,792
He only keeps essentials.

379
00:14:19,859 --> 00:14:21,393
He has some stuff.

380
00:14:21,460 --> 00:14:24,964
I can already see
things like chicken breast.

381
00:14:25,030 --> 00:14:27,600
Salad greens and boiled eggs too.

382
00:14:27,666 --> 00:14:29,101
Do you usually eat like this?

383
00:14:29,168 --> 00:14:31,704
-Those are sprouts, actually.
-Yes.

384
00:14:31,770 --> 00:14:35,207
I usually eat sprouts
and one piece of chicken breast

385
00:14:35,274 --> 00:14:36,909
for breakfast and dinner.

386
00:14:37,576 --> 00:14:38,611
It's so good.

387
00:14:38,677 --> 00:14:39,778
-What?
-It's good?

388
00:14:39,845 --> 00:14:41,747
But your face said something else.

389
00:14:41,814 --> 00:14:44,283
THE FACE OF SOMEONE
WHO FINDS IT DELICIOUS?

390
00:14:44,350 --> 00:14:46,652
-For both breakfast and dinner?
-Breakfast and dinner.

391
00:14:46,852 --> 00:14:47,920
GASP

392
00:14:47,987 --> 00:14:49,922
-What about lunch?
-Lunch?

393
00:14:49,989 --> 00:14:51,657
I add some protein to the meal.

394
00:14:51,724 --> 00:14:53,158
ABOVE THEIR COMPREHENSION

395
00:14:53,225 --> 00:14:56,128
I usually don't stay on a strict diet,
but I have to do that for now.

396
00:14:56,195 --> 00:14:59,665
What about today? Can you eat
if our chefs make you something?

397
00:14:59,732 --> 00:15:02,234
I starved for three days to eat here.

398
00:15:02,301 --> 00:15:04,904
-It's his cheat day.
-But we need to find ingredients.

399
00:15:04,970 --> 00:15:06,972
-These are…
-This is his daily diet.

400
00:15:07,039 --> 00:15:08,807
-He has something.
-Something's here.

401
00:15:09,408 --> 00:15:11,644
-What is this?
-Nuts? Oatmeal?

402
00:15:11,710 --> 00:15:13,879
It's a mix of a few different things.

403
00:15:13,946 --> 00:15:18,484
Oatmeal, oats, and salad topping seeds.

404
00:15:18,550 --> 00:15:19,718
…salad topping seeds.

405
00:15:19,785 --> 00:15:21,153
DROP

406
00:15:21,720 --> 00:15:22,821
-Goodness.
-Hey.

407
00:15:22,888 --> 00:15:24,857
What if these begin to grow here?

408
00:15:24,924 --> 00:15:27,092
You just wasted one meal's worth!

409
00:15:27,159 --> 00:15:29,795
-He'll have to skip a meal!
-It wasn't that much.

410
00:15:29,862 --> 00:15:30,696
That was his lunch!

411
00:15:30,763 --> 00:15:32,932
AS ALWAYS,
THINGS ARE PEACEFUL HERE IN THE STUDIO

412
00:15:32,998 --> 00:15:34,466
I like to cycle,

413
00:15:34,533 --> 00:15:36,535
so in the morning… Man, this is a secret.

414
00:15:36,602 --> 00:15:39,605
I can't have my rivals
find out about this.

415
00:15:39,672 --> 00:15:40,673
It's a secret.

416
00:15:40,739 --> 00:15:42,441
-Is this your trade secret?
-Yes.

417
00:15:42,508 --> 00:15:44,944
I mix that with milk
and eat it before I ride,

418
00:15:45,010 --> 00:15:47,279
and it keeps me going well over 60 km.

419
00:15:47,346 --> 00:15:48,681
-Really?
-Yes.

420
00:15:48,747 --> 00:15:50,416
-On just cereal?
-On just cereal?

421
00:15:50,482 --> 00:15:51,383
I don't fall behind.

422
00:15:51,450 --> 00:15:53,452
-Without falling behind.
-I don't.

423
00:15:53,519 --> 00:15:54,920
And I don't experience a bonk.

424
00:15:54,987 --> 00:15:56,622
-A bonk?
-A bonk is a symptom

425
00:15:56,689 --> 00:15:58,223
when you get exhausted while cycling,

426
00:15:58,290 --> 00:16:00,859
and you can no longer continue to pedal.

427
00:16:00,926 --> 00:16:02,194
-That's called a bonk?
-Yes.

428
00:16:02,261 --> 00:16:04,296
-I see. Bonking.
-You call it bonking.

429
00:16:04,363 --> 00:16:06,598
I eat that once before I begin,

430
00:16:06,665 --> 00:16:09,101
and have another portion
during the session at about 50 km

431
00:16:09,168 --> 00:16:10,903
to easily get up to 100 km.

432
00:16:10,970 --> 00:16:11,971
You ride up to 100 km?

433
00:16:12,037 --> 00:16:14,907
-How far is 100 km from here?
-From Seoul to Cheonan.

434
00:16:14,974 --> 00:16:17,409
100 KM IS ABOUT THE DISTANCE
BETWEEN SEOUL AND CHEONAN

435
00:16:17,476 --> 00:16:20,112
-Without a break?
-It's a long ride even by car.

436
00:16:20,179 --> 00:16:22,481
I once went out to cycle in the summer

437
00:16:22,548 --> 00:16:24,616
and saw someone enjoying beer.
It looked so good.

438
00:16:24,683 --> 00:16:26,518
So I had some too, then called a cab

439
00:16:26,585 --> 00:16:28,053
and loaded the bicycle in the taxi.

440
00:16:28,120 --> 00:16:29,121
RETURNED HOME IN A TAXI

441
00:16:29,188 --> 00:16:31,156
-I'm saying that he's amazing.
-He is.

442
00:16:31,223 --> 00:16:32,624
He has great self-discipline.

443
00:16:32,691 --> 00:16:35,027
This is… Are these raw fish fillets?

444
00:16:35,094 --> 00:16:36,795
These look like leftovers.

445
00:16:36,862 --> 00:16:38,030
Halibut and snapper.

446
00:16:38,097 --> 00:16:40,466
No one finishes
the entire thing at once, right?

447
00:16:40,532 --> 00:16:41,800
The same for <i>jokbal</i>, pig's feet.

448
00:16:41,867 --> 00:16:43,335
-I'm not sure.
-Why not?

449
00:16:43,402 --> 00:16:46,872
-I kept an ice pack underneath.
-It's down here.

450
00:16:46,939 --> 00:16:49,675
You're right. There's an ice pack here.

451
00:16:49,742 --> 00:16:52,978
Anyway, I don't see any side dishes,
so I'm feeling a bit let down.

452
00:16:53,045 --> 00:16:56,482
We were also curious to have a taste
of something your wife made.

453
00:16:56,548 --> 00:16:58,784
Is she a good cook?

454
00:16:58,851 --> 00:17:00,886
She likes to cook.

455
00:17:00,953 --> 00:17:01,787
For example,

456
00:17:01,854 --> 00:17:06,358
some restaurants make Korean food,
Chinese food, and even Italian food.

457
00:17:06,425 --> 00:17:08,794
They make everything, right?

458
00:17:08,861 --> 00:17:09,895
My house is like that.

459
00:17:09,962 --> 00:17:12,698
-It's not easy to be good at all three.
-From time to time,

460
00:17:12,765 --> 00:17:16,235
I'd say to my wife
that we should get hamburgers.

461
00:17:16,301 --> 00:17:18,504
-"Let's have some hamburgers." Then?
-Yes. Then,

462
00:17:18,570 --> 00:17:20,406
she has it ready in a few hours.

463
00:17:20,472 --> 00:17:23,008
-She makes it?
-She must be good.

464
00:17:23,075 --> 00:17:26,211
One day, I was with my kids, and I said,

465
00:17:26,278 --> 00:17:27,780
-"Don't you want some pizza?"
-Pizza?

466
00:17:27,846 --> 00:17:29,248
ME?

467
00:17:29,314 --> 00:17:31,850
Then a moment later,
we see a pizza on the table.

468
00:17:31,917 --> 00:17:33,886
-Wow.
-She has it ready?

469
00:17:33,952 --> 00:17:36,255
But my kids and I

470
00:17:36,321 --> 00:17:40,059
-want to eat out at times.
-You also want to eat out.

471
00:17:40,125 --> 00:17:42,061
-There's fun in eating out.
-Right.

472
00:17:42,628 --> 00:17:44,530
-We want to eat out too.
-Of course.

473
00:17:44,596 --> 00:17:47,032
-It's a different mood.
-Definitely.

474
00:17:47,099 --> 00:17:51,270
But my wife can make everything at home,

475
00:17:51,336 --> 00:17:53,672
so we keep postponing eating out.

476
00:17:53,739 --> 00:17:55,207
A HAPPY CONCERN

477
00:17:55,274 --> 00:17:58,477
Look at this.
He's into ready-to-cook products.

478
00:17:58,544 --> 00:18:01,013
I found a pack of udon.

479
00:18:01,080 --> 00:18:02,181
Do you enjoy noodle dishes?

480
00:18:02,247 --> 00:18:04,483
Yes, I do like noodle dishes.

481
00:18:04,550 --> 00:18:06,118
I see more noodles here.

482
00:18:06,185 --> 00:18:08,387
-There they are.
-Thin noodles. He has thin noodles.

483
00:18:08,454 --> 00:18:10,889
-And pasta.
-And pasta.

484
00:18:10,956 --> 00:18:12,791
I guess you eat <i>ramyeon </i>too.

485
00:18:12,858 --> 00:18:13,959
Of course.

486
00:18:14,026 --> 00:18:15,828
I eat three bags at a time.

487
00:18:15,894 --> 00:18:16,728
-For one meal?
-Yes.

488
00:18:16,795 --> 00:18:18,597
-You eat a lot when you do.
-You eat a lot.

489
00:18:18,664 --> 00:18:21,667
It used to be much easier to lose weight.

490
00:18:21,733 --> 00:18:23,969
-Losing weight?
-Yes, dropping weight.

491
00:18:24,036 --> 00:18:26,505
It took me about 3 weeks to drop 5 kg.

492
00:18:27,172 --> 00:18:28,640
-That's quick.
-Wait, 5 kg in 3 weeks?

493
00:18:28,707 --> 00:18:30,008
He dropped 5 kg in 3 weeks?

494
00:18:30,075 --> 00:18:31,477
I'm jealous.

495
00:18:31,543 --> 00:18:33,345
Instead of cycling 100 km,

496
00:18:33,412 --> 00:18:35,614
you should cut it down to 50 km.

497
00:18:35,681 --> 00:18:38,383
After I cycle 100 km,

498
00:18:38,450 --> 00:18:40,152
there's something I always crave.

499
00:18:40,219 --> 00:18:41,120
What is it?

500
00:18:41,186 --> 00:18:42,921
<i>Naengmyeon</i>, cold noodles.

501
00:18:42,988 --> 00:18:46,792
-From Y <i>naengmyeon </i>restaurant.
-That place.

502
00:18:46,859 --> 00:18:48,827
-That place is good.
-It's insane.

503
00:18:48,894 --> 00:18:51,597
I pretty much cycle 100 km to eat that.

504
00:18:52,164 --> 00:18:54,166
SMACKING LIPS
THAT SOUNDS GOOD…

505
00:18:54,733 --> 00:18:56,368
Down here.

506
00:18:56,435 --> 00:18:57,870
-Konjac.
-He has konjac.

507
00:18:57,936 --> 00:18:59,104
-Pumpkin juice.
-Pumpkin juice.

508
00:18:59,171 --> 00:19:00,873
-Goodness.
-What's up?

509
00:19:01,473 --> 00:19:04,276
The expiry date was April 2023.

510
00:19:04,343 --> 00:19:06,712
-That's 3 years ago.
-April 10th.

511
00:19:06,778 --> 00:19:09,748
This expired on March 20, 2025.

512
00:19:09,815 --> 00:19:11,083
You can consume some things

513
00:19:11,150 --> 00:19:13,118
even after the expiration date.

514
00:19:13,185 --> 00:19:14,853
What do you mean? Such as?

515
00:19:14,920 --> 00:19:18,524
The expiry date is just a recommendation.

516
00:19:19,191 --> 00:19:20,993
But three years is a bit…

517
00:19:21,059 --> 00:19:23,595
-It's a recommendation.
-It's different from the use-by date, but…

518
00:19:23,662 --> 00:19:25,931
-Right
-But it's been three years.

519
00:19:25,998 --> 00:19:29,034
-All right. Feel free to have it.
-"Feel free to have it."

520
00:19:29,101 --> 00:19:30,969
-Now, we finally found veggies.
-Vegetables.

521
00:19:31,036 --> 00:19:33,372
We'll have to see
if he has cilantro or not.

522
00:19:33,438 --> 00:19:34,373
The crisper drawer.

523
00:19:34,439 --> 00:19:35,440
Bell peppers.

524
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:37,442
CURIOUS

525
00:19:37,509 --> 00:19:38,677
-What's this?
-Broccoli.

526
00:19:38,744 --> 00:19:39,711
-Cilantro?
-Broccoli.

527
00:19:39,778 --> 00:19:41,680
-Gosh. What else?
-It wasn't cilantro.

528
00:19:41,747 --> 00:19:44,116
-Cherry tomatoes. Is this cilantro?
-Cilantro?

529
00:19:44,683 --> 00:19:47,052
WILL GO SOO'S FRIDGE HAVE GOSU?

530
00:19:48,353 --> 00:19:49,655
Salad mix.

531
00:19:50,222 --> 00:19:51,423
DISAPPOINTED

532
00:19:51,490 --> 00:19:52,724
Does this contain cilantro?

533
00:19:52,791 --> 00:19:54,993
-I doubt it.
-It's usually not mixed in.

534
00:19:55,060 --> 00:19:56,428
-So no cilantro.
-What a shame.

535
00:19:56,495 --> 00:19:59,531
Go Soo's fridge did not contain <i>gosu</i>!

536
00:19:59,598 --> 00:20:01,099
WHAT A SHAME?

537
00:20:01,166 --> 00:20:05,137
I don't keep it.
I've never even bought it, actually.

538
00:20:05,204 --> 00:20:06,738
I see liquor here too.

539
00:20:06,805 --> 00:20:08,140
What's this bottle?

540
00:20:08,207 --> 00:20:10,108
That's <i>omija</i>.

541
00:20:10,175 --> 00:20:11,476
<i>Omija</i>?

542
00:20:11,543 --> 00:20:12,711
This is <i>omija</i>?

543
00:20:12,778 --> 00:20:15,314
-But the bottle…
-The bottle doesn't say that.

544
00:20:15,380 --> 00:20:18,750
That used to be… Do you see
that bottle of liquid to the right?

545
00:20:18,817 --> 00:20:21,420
-This one?
-That used to be the <i>omija</i> bottle.

546
00:20:21,486 --> 00:20:24,089
-I had to move it.
-You moved it.

547
00:20:24,156 --> 00:20:26,725
Here's the story.

548
00:20:26,792 --> 00:20:29,962
I made eggplant tea
and didn't have a jar to put it in,

549
00:20:30,028 --> 00:20:32,364
then my eyes landed
on the <i>omija</i> extract bottle.

550
00:20:32,431 --> 00:20:34,166
So I decided to put the tea there,

551
00:20:34,233 --> 00:20:35,767
but now I had nowhere to put the <i>omija</i> in.

552
00:20:35,834 --> 00:20:38,637
HIS LIFE IS LIKE A SITCOM

553
00:20:38,704 --> 00:20:41,673
That bottle seemed the most suitable
for <i>omija </i>among the ones I had.

554
00:20:41,740 --> 00:20:42,975
LAUGHING OUT LOUD

555
00:20:43,041 --> 00:20:44,176
What about the whiskey?

556
00:20:44,243 --> 00:20:45,344
I had it.

557
00:20:45,410 --> 00:20:47,179
-Did you drink it for this?
-You drank this.

558
00:20:47,246 --> 00:20:49,147
-I had to drink it.
-To get the bottle?

559
00:20:49,214 --> 00:20:53,118
So that means
you basically like whiskey too.

560
00:20:53,185 --> 00:20:54,886
I have a glass at times.

561
00:20:54,953 --> 00:20:56,255
But recently,

562
00:20:56,321 --> 00:20:59,858
Han Ji-min mentioned me
when she was on TV.

563
00:20:59,925 --> 00:21:01,927
She said that I went down in 15 minutes.

564
00:21:01,994 --> 00:21:04,329
-What do you mean?
-I guess you haven't heard.

565
00:21:04,396 --> 00:21:06,498
We had an agency-wide dinner,

566
00:21:06,565 --> 00:21:08,767
and I got there at about 9:00 p.m.

567
00:21:08,834 --> 00:21:10,035
Then Ji-min said,

568
00:21:10,102 --> 00:21:11,937
"Soo, you have to chug down
three glasses now."

569
00:21:12,004 --> 00:21:15,140
-For arriving late?
-As a penalty?

570
00:21:15,207 --> 00:21:17,209
-"You have to chug three glasses."
-For coming late.

571
00:21:17,276 --> 00:21:19,678
-So how can I not have it?
-That's true.

572
00:21:19,745 --> 00:21:21,446
You had to drink.

573
00:21:21,513 --> 00:21:23,015
So I downed one.

574
00:21:23,081 --> 00:21:25,117
-Two.
-Drinking quickly makes you drunk fast.

575
00:21:25,183 --> 00:21:26,718
Yes, and I had the third one.

576
00:21:26,785 --> 00:21:28,287
That's all I remember.

577
00:21:28,353 --> 00:21:30,289
ALL MEMORIES WERE DELETED AFTER THAT

578
00:21:30,355 --> 00:21:32,090
-And then…
-He blacked out.

579
00:21:32,157 --> 00:21:34,760
…I got home, came to my senses,

580
00:21:34,826 --> 00:21:36,094
and realized it was ten o'clock.

581
00:21:36,161 --> 00:21:37,529
HAPPENED IN 1 HOUR

582
00:21:37,596 --> 00:21:40,132
But you got there at 9:00 p.m.?

583
00:21:40,198 --> 00:21:41,900
He was there for 20 minutes.

584
00:21:41,967 --> 00:21:44,236
He probably spent five minutes saying hi,

585
00:21:44,303 --> 00:21:46,672
five minutes for each drink,

586
00:21:46,738 --> 00:21:49,975
and then 30 to 40 minutes getting home.

587
00:21:50,042 --> 00:21:53,512
-You probably stayed there for 15 minutes.
-Yes, just 15 minutes.

588
00:21:53,578 --> 00:21:55,580
Fifteen minutes sounds like
you're meant to be here.

589
00:21:56,148 --> 00:21:57,916
A PERFECT GUEST FOR THE SHOW

590
00:21:57,983 --> 00:21:59,584
-He's meant to be.
-It's fate.

591
00:21:59,651 --> 00:22:01,119
Next, the freezer.

592
00:22:01,186 --> 00:22:03,822
-What is this?
-What is it?

593
00:22:03,889 --> 00:22:04,990
Dried filefish fillets?

594
00:22:05,057 --> 00:22:07,059
-Why do you have so many?
-Dried filefish fillets.

595
00:22:07,125 --> 00:22:09,294
-These are a lot.
-Gosh, I love those.

596
00:22:09,361 --> 00:22:10,962
He barely had any.

597
00:22:11,029 --> 00:22:13,765
I got it as a present,

598
00:22:13,832 --> 00:22:17,035
but it was too hard to chew.

599
00:22:17,102 --> 00:22:18,837
You can soak it in water,
then deep-fry it.

600
00:22:18,904 --> 00:22:19,971
Deep-fried filefish fillet.

601
00:22:20,038 --> 00:22:22,074
-First, soak them, then deep-fry.
-Isn't it tough?

602
00:22:22,140 --> 00:22:23,442
-It's okay.
-It gets soft.

603
00:22:23,508 --> 00:22:26,845
Chefs, please share any secrets you know.

604
00:22:26,912 --> 00:22:29,281
-Wouldn't it be nice?
-That'd be wonderful.

605
00:22:29,348 --> 00:22:31,183
Next, some meat.

606
00:22:31,249 --> 00:22:33,719
This looks like Korean beef.
How do you eat your meat?

607
00:22:33,785 --> 00:22:37,055
-I grill 100 to 150 g of meat per meal.
-Only 100 g?

608
00:22:37,122 --> 00:22:39,825
-Right.
-My kid eats 100 g of meat.

609
00:22:39,891 --> 00:22:43,095
Eating this much or that much
is all the same, isn't it?

610
00:22:43,161 --> 00:22:45,864
What are you talking about?

611
00:22:45,931 --> 00:22:47,966
-Isn't it better to eat a lot?
-I mean, how much gets absorbed.

612
00:22:48,033 --> 00:22:49,401
You should eat this much.

613
00:22:49,468 --> 00:22:52,571
-I don't even begin if I must eat little.
-Yes, it feels like a tease.

614
00:22:52,637 --> 00:22:54,973
-The amount…
-I mean the absorption.

615
00:22:55,040 --> 00:22:57,309
You mean
whatever that doesn't get absorbed

616
00:22:57,376 --> 00:22:59,111
-is unnecessary, right?
-Yes, the absorption.

617
00:22:59,177 --> 00:23:00,545
He's not a glutton.

618
00:23:00,612 --> 00:23:02,581
-He doesn't obsess over food.
-No.

619
00:23:02,647 --> 00:23:04,049
What's this?

620
00:23:04,116 --> 00:23:05,450
-What's that? Ice cream?
-Ice cream.

621
00:23:05,517 --> 00:23:07,185
Ice cream? Yes, it's ice cream.

622
00:23:07,252 --> 00:23:10,689
-Yogurt ice cream.
-Yogurt ice cream with milk fat.

623
00:23:10,756 --> 00:23:12,791
-It's big. A gallon?
-This is a lot.

624
00:23:12,858 --> 00:23:14,092
He's clapping.

625
00:23:14,159 --> 00:23:15,560
He's clapping.

626
00:23:15,627 --> 00:23:17,963
A FULL TUB

627
00:23:18,029 --> 00:23:19,398
You have a lot of yogurt ice cream.

628
00:23:19,464 --> 00:23:21,433
-I love ice cream.
-You buy in bulk?

629
00:23:21,500 --> 00:23:23,502
-I always eat a portion a day.
-This?

630
00:23:23,568 --> 00:23:25,470
I either eat this or one of those.

631
00:23:26,271 --> 00:23:28,039
Goodness. He has a whole bucket of these.

632
00:23:28,106 --> 00:23:30,142
-My gosh!
-This is shocking.

633
00:23:30,208 --> 00:23:32,544
That tangerine popsicle is my favorite.

634
00:23:32,611 --> 00:23:33,612
This is a good one.

635
00:23:33,678 --> 00:23:37,482
It only has 50 calories… Maybe 70?
Around 50 to 70.

636
00:23:37,549 --> 00:23:38,750
He knows what it's called.

637
00:23:38,817 --> 00:23:40,285
The S brand.

638
00:23:40,352 --> 00:23:41,853
-S popsicle has 50 calories.
-I eat it

639
00:23:41,920 --> 00:23:43,688
when I crave something refreshing.

640
00:23:43,755 --> 00:23:46,158
-I see.
-One of those always hits the spot.

641
00:23:46,224 --> 00:23:48,493
Is there a reason
you specifically love ice cream cones?

642
00:23:48,560 --> 00:23:50,128
Because it's sweet. Yes.

643
00:23:50,195 --> 00:23:51,430
I love chocolate.

644
00:23:51,496 --> 00:23:53,799
-The bottom is always chocolate.
-The bottom part.

645
00:23:54,433 --> 00:23:55,801
He has chocolate snacks here.

646
00:23:55,867 --> 00:23:57,369
Wait a second.

647
00:23:57,436 --> 00:23:59,504
You seem to have a sweet tooth.

648
00:23:59,571 --> 00:24:01,173
-These are a lot.
-Soo.

649
00:24:01,239 --> 00:24:03,675
-I do love sweet things.
-You do.

650
00:24:03,742 --> 00:24:06,144
-That was a twist.
-It was a big surprise.

651
00:24:06,211 --> 00:24:09,481
-But you don't eat what you should eat…
-Right?

652
00:24:09,548 --> 00:24:11,283
…but a lot of what you shouldn't.

653
00:24:11,349 --> 00:24:13,318
Why doesn't he think these are too much?

654
00:24:13,385 --> 00:24:15,220
Don't things like ice cream and snacks

655
00:24:15,287 --> 00:24:17,122
fly off your body instantly?

656
00:24:17,189 --> 00:24:19,391
What flies? Fly off to where?

657
00:24:19,458 --> 00:24:21,827
THIS IS GO SOO'S PERSONAL OPINION

658
00:24:21,893 --> 00:24:23,962
It flies off after a run
or a cycling session.

659
00:24:24,029 --> 00:24:26,031
I suddenly feel relatable.

660
00:24:26,097 --> 00:24:28,500
At first, I thought to myself,

661
00:24:28,567 --> 00:24:31,736
"I'm so bad with my diet compared to Soo."

662
00:24:31,803 --> 00:24:34,105
-But now I'm suddenly seeing hope.
-Right?

663
00:24:34,172 --> 00:24:35,040
That's true.

664
00:24:35,106 --> 00:24:37,108
And that was it
for the master of self-discipline,

665
00:24:37,175 --> 00:24:39,744
Go Soo's fridge!

666
00:24:39,811 --> 00:24:42,514
FINISHED CHECKING OUT SOO'S FRIDGE

667
00:24:42,581 --> 00:24:46,685
Now, let's find out
what he wants to eat today.

668
00:24:46,751 --> 00:24:48,620
These are his orders.

669
00:24:48,687 --> 00:24:49,688
Show us!

670
00:24:50,655 --> 00:24:52,324
-Go Soo's Bite Master.
-Go Soo's Bite Master.

671
00:24:52,390 --> 00:24:54,359
-Go Soo's Noodle Master.
-Go Soo's Noodle Master.

672
00:24:54,426 --> 00:24:56,161
Both orders are revealed at once.

673
00:24:56,228 --> 00:24:58,563
What are you looking for
when you say Go Soo's Bite Master?

674
00:24:58,630 --> 00:25:00,699
I want to eat everything in one bite.

675
00:25:02,501 --> 00:25:04,769
I want something nutritional and tasty,

676
00:25:04,836 --> 00:25:06,771
but I want to have everything in one bite.

677
00:25:06,838 --> 00:25:09,241
-Like that chocolate bar you have?
-Yes!

678
00:25:09,307 --> 00:25:11,176
We must condense everything into one bite.

679
00:25:11,243 --> 00:25:12,477
But why have just one bite?

680
00:25:12,544 --> 00:25:13,979
Next, Go Soo's Noodle Master.

681
00:25:14,546 --> 00:25:16,848
Noodles. I love all noodles,

682
00:25:16,915 --> 00:25:20,185
including pasta, <i>ramyeon</i>,
udon, buckwheat noodles,

683
00:25:20,252 --> 00:25:21,853
and everything else.

684
00:25:21,920 --> 00:25:25,957
-Please make me a delicious noodle dish.
-A noodle dish.

685
00:25:27,125 --> 00:25:30,262
-He said he eats three bags of <i>ramyeon</i>.
-Exactly.

686
00:25:30,328 --> 00:25:31,496
All right.

687
00:25:31,563 --> 00:25:33,798
Go Soo's Bite Master
and Go Soo's Noodle Master.

688
00:25:33,865 --> 00:25:35,700
-I'll go.
-Chef Hyun-suk? I knew it.

689
00:25:35,767 --> 00:25:39,337
-As the master of the show…
-Yes, the <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> master.

690
00:25:39,404 --> 00:25:41,206
Smells like a master.

691
00:25:41,273 --> 00:25:43,475
-He has mastered his age too.
-So I should go first.

692
00:25:43,542 --> 00:25:45,277
-Go Soo's Bite Master.
-Go Soo's Bite Master.

693
00:25:45,343 --> 00:25:48,713
All right. Chef Hyun-suk takes
Go Soo's Bite Master.

694
00:25:48,780 --> 00:25:50,482
Waiting for the next master.

695
00:25:50,549 --> 00:25:54,219
Sam, why don't you join today?
Soo picked you as the face of our show.

696
00:25:54,286 --> 00:25:55,787
-You're right.
-Yes.

697
00:25:55,854 --> 00:25:57,622
-The David of the show.
-Our David.

698
00:25:58,290 --> 00:26:00,625
I like noodle dishes, so…

699
00:26:00,692 --> 00:26:01,960
Yes, of course.

700
00:26:02,027 --> 00:26:04,029
-I'll make noodles.
-A noodle dish.

701
00:26:04,095 --> 00:26:05,430
-He'll make pasta.
-Noodles.

702
00:26:05,497 --> 00:26:07,265
Hyun-suk and Sam join different rounds.

703
00:26:07,332 --> 00:26:09,234
HMM…

704
00:26:09,301 --> 00:26:10,936
-I'll join.
-Sung-jun?

705
00:26:11,002 --> 00:26:13,505
-Wait. Noodles?
-Noodles?

706
00:26:13,572 --> 00:26:16,107
Actually, I was in Italy until last week.

707
00:26:16,174 --> 00:26:17,542
Really?

708
00:26:17,609 --> 00:26:19,911
After that, I'm hyped up right now,

709
00:26:19,978 --> 00:26:24,015
-so I want to fight against someone tough.
-It's time.

710
00:26:24,082 --> 00:26:26,718
I'll choose Hyun-suk's round,

711
00:26:26,785 --> 00:26:28,853
-Go Soo's Bite Master.
-Go Soo's Bite Master.

712
00:26:28,920 --> 00:26:31,356
-I'm going for the big fish.
-Chef Hyun-suk.

713
00:26:31,423 --> 00:26:33,959
Then it's Hyun-suk versus Sung-jun.

714
00:26:34,025 --> 00:26:35,160
The noodles round.

715
00:26:35,226 --> 00:26:36,661
I'll jump in.

716
00:26:36,728 --> 00:26:37,929
-Nam-no?
-Yes.

717
00:26:37,996 --> 00:26:40,865
I'm nicknamed both Noodle Nam-no
and Yoon Nam-Noodles.

718
00:26:40,932 --> 00:26:43,468
I've had a fair share of noodles,

719
00:26:43,535 --> 00:26:46,304
-so I'll go after Chef Sam.
-All right.

720
00:26:46,371 --> 00:26:47,205
It won't be easy.

721
00:26:47,272 --> 00:26:48,640
All right, then.

722
00:26:48,707 --> 00:26:52,177
Let us begin the 15-minute cook-off
between Hyun-suk and Sung-jun!

723
00:26:52,744 --> 00:26:55,447
THE COOK-OFF BEGINS NOW

724
00:26:55,513 --> 00:26:59,551
<i>This is the first cook-off</i>
<i>played with ingredients from Soo's fridge.</i>

725
00:26:59,618 --> 00:27:02,087
The master show-off, Chef Choi Hyun-suk,

726
00:27:03,121 --> 00:27:05,924
versus the master of switching masters,

727
00:27:05,991 --> 00:27:08,827
-Chef Kwon Sung-jun.
-The master of switching masters.

728
00:27:08,893 --> 00:27:11,129
-I have a question.
-Yes?

729
00:27:11,196 --> 00:27:14,265
When Chef Hyun-suk doesn't cook,

730
00:27:14,332 --> 00:27:17,102
does he always keep his arms crossed?

731
00:27:17,168 --> 00:27:18,203
HUMBLE

732
00:27:18,269 --> 00:27:20,639
-He's always like this.
-He was born like this.

733
00:27:20,705 --> 00:27:22,407
He was like, "Wah!"

734
00:27:22,474 --> 00:27:24,009
The fridge owner attacked you.

735
00:27:24,075 --> 00:27:25,744
THE FIRST FRIDGE OWNER TO ATTACK A CHEF

736
00:27:25,810 --> 00:27:28,213
Don't take it the wrong way. It wasn't us.

737
00:27:28,279 --> 00:27:30,982
-It was him.
-I was genuinely curious.

738
00:27:31,049 --> 00:27:33,084
Here's your history.

739
00:27:33,151 --> 00:27:37,222
Last year, Chef Sung-jun fought him twice
and lost twice,

740
00:27:37,288 --> 00:27:39,324
and this year,
he fought him once and lost that.

741
00:27:39,391 --> 00:27:40,492
SUNG-JUN LOST ALL 3 ROUNDS

742
00:27:40,558 --> 00:27:43,528
-Three consecutive losses.
-He lost all three times against Hyun-suk.

743
00:27:43,595 --> 00:27:45,363
So no one gets kicked out when they lose?

744
00:27:45,430 --> 00:27:48,066
It looks like we'll need a new rule.

745
00:27:48,133 --> 00:27:50,201
That's a wonderful idea.

746
00:27:50,268 --> 00:27:53,505
-How did he win <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>?
-I lost in the beginning of the year,

747
00:27:53,571 --> 00:27:57,609
but elderly men count their days
with a lunar calendar.

748
00:27:57,676 --> 00:28:00,879
So in the lunar calendar,
it's finally the year 2026,

749
00:28:00,945 --> 00:28:01,913
so I'm starting over.

750
00:28:01,980 --> 00:28:03,415
THIS IS THE REAL FIRST ROUND OF 2026

751
00:28:03,481 --> 00:28:05,750
The previous one was done
with a solar calendar.

752
00:28:05,817 --> 00:28:06,751
A RIDICULOUS RESET

753
00:28:06,818 --> 00:28:09,587
The world of culinary arts
is rotting again.

754
00:28:09,654 --> 00:28:11,156
It's infected.

755
00:28:11,222 --> 00:28:12,390
-It is.
-It's festering.

756
00:28:12,457 --> 00:28:14,859
Sung-jun continuously challenges him,

757
00:28:14,926 --> 00:28:19,064
but Chef Hyun-suk says this year,
Sung-jun is starting to grow on him.

758
00:28:19,130 --> 00:28:20,231
-What?
-Really?

759
00:28:20,298 --> 00:28:22,100
To be honest, Chef Sung-jun

760
00:28:22,167 --> 00:28:24,736
-isn't easily likable.
-What?

761
00:28:24,803 --> 00:28:25,737
FIERCE SLANDER

762
00:28:25,804 --> 00:28:27,605
-To his face?
-Whenever he had a chance,

763
00:28:27,672 --> 00:28:29,240
he was busy switching masters

764
00:28:29,307 --> 00:28:33,344
-and attacking me by calling me elderly.
-He's holding a grudge.

765
00:28:33,411 --> 00:28:35,947
But I find his enthusiasm endearing.

766
00:28:36,014 --> 00:28:37,649
Hence, I kept copying his catchphrases

767
00:28:37,716 --> 00:28:40,218
and decided to show him my support.

768
00:28:40,285 --> 00:28:42,320
"It's an emergency,"
and "It looks delicious."

769
00:28:42,387 --> 00:28:46,124
Have you noticed that Chef Hyun-suk
had been supporting your catchphrases?

770
00:28:46,191 --> 00:28:47,459
Yes, I've seen it often.

771
00:28:47,525 --> 00:28:49,027
BLAND REACTION

772
00:28:49,094 --> 00:28:50,829
-He looks indifferent.
-"I've seen it often."

773
00:28:50,895 --> 00:28:54,799
He used to keep a notebook
full of Hyun-suk's quotes. Remember?

774
00:28:54,866 --> 00:28:57,802
-He kept a notebook.
-Where is it?

775
00:28:57,869 --> 00:28:58,870
That thing?

776
00:28:58,937 --> 00:29:02,440
-I lost it.
-You lost it? Are you serious?

777
00:29:02,507 --> 00:29:04,309
-We have a new transcript.
-Yes?

778
00:29:04,375 --> 00:29:05,610
It's from Chef Hyun-suk.

779
00:29:05,677 --> 00:29:08,713
He said this round will be
an emergency for Sung-jun.

780
00:29:08,780 --> 00:29:10,248
I see.

781
00:29:10,315 --> 00:29:11,883
I run the kind of a restaurant

782
00:29:11,950 --> 00:29:13,985
<i>that often makes finger food</i>

783
00:29:14,052 --> 00:29:16,054
<i>and even gets requests</i>
<i>for quite a lot of catering gigs.</i>

784
00:29:16,821 --> 00:29:18,523
So it's an emergency for Chef Sung-jun,

785
00:29:18,590 --> 00:29:21,559
and an emerging flight for Chef Hyun-suk.

786
00:29:22,127 --> 00:29:24,195
DROP THE MIC

787
00:29:24,262 --> 00:29:25,897
He killed it with the rhyme.

788
00:29:25,964 --> 00:29:28,199
-It's an emergency.
-That was like a rap battle.

789
00:29:29,134 --> 00:29:30,902
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
STRIP LOIN, DRIED FILEFISH FILLET

790
00:29:30,969 --> 00:29:33,204
RAW HALIBUT AND SNAPPER, BREAD, RYE BREAD,
FROZEN LOBSTER FRIED RICE, AND MORE

791
00:29:33,271 --> 00:29:35,373
The name of the dish I'll make is

792
00:29:35,440 --> 00:29:37,208
Napoli MatPro.

793
00:29:37,275 --> 00:29:38,743
-I see.
-Napoli MatPro.

794
00:29:38,810 --> 00:29:42,380
-Napoli MatPro.
-You've named it Naples.

795
00:29:42,447 --> 00:29:45,350
-Is it something Italian?
-I returned to Korea four days ago.

796
00:29:45,416 --> 00:29:49,154
The food I ate in Naples
is still in my system.

797
00:29:49,220 --> 00:29:51,022
-I'll add the taste…
-Something must be wrong.

798
00:29:51,089 --> 00:29:52,490
-That's indigestion.
-His fart must smell.

799
00:29:52,557 --> 00:29:53,892
He must be sick.

800
00:29:53,958 --> 00:29:55,660
-Have a digestive drink.
-I'll bring out its flavor.

801
00:29:55,727 --> 00:29:58,229
There are a few dishes
that can represent Naples.

802
00:29:58,296 --> 00:30:00,064
First, <i>polpette</i>,

803
00:30:00,131 --> 00:30:02,700
which is meatballs in tomato sauce.

804
00:30:02,767 --> 00:30:05,003
Another dish is called parmigiana,

805
00:30:05,069 --> 00:30:08,006
a kind of deep-fried eggplant lasagna.

806
00:30:08,072 --> 00:30:09,374
So I'll prepare that too.

807
00:30:09,440 --> 00:30:11,276
I'm thinking of using
the filefish fillets too.

808
00:30:11,342 --> 00:30:13,311
-Really?
-In Italy,

809
00:30:13,378 --> 00:30:16,714
there are some seafood restaurants
that make dessert with seafood.

810
00:30:16,781 --> 00:30:19,217
-I see.
-Filefish fillet dessert?

811
00:30:19,284 --> 00:30:21,820
I'll make famous street food from Naples

812
00:30:21,886 --> 00:30:23,388
and serve it to you.

813
00:30:23,454 --> 00:30:25,557
It'll be like taking a walk in Naples.

814
00:30:25,623 --> 00:30:27,192
A WALK IN NAPLES THROUGH HIS DISH!

815
00:30:28,026 --> 00:30:29,994
CHEF HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS:
STRIP LOIN, SHRIMP, RAW HALIBUT

816
00:30:30,061 --> 00:30:32,197
BREAD, RYE BREAD, CHESTNUT JAM,
BROCCOLI, SPROUTS, APPLE, AND MORE

817
00:30:32,263 --> 00:30:34,899
Chef Hyun-suk is up against Sung-jun.

818
00:30:34,966 --> 00:30:36,734
-What are you making?
-It's something big.

819
00:30:37,502 --> 00:30:39,804
Sung-jun's Miss,

820
00:30:40,505 --> 00:30:42,607
Nice for Hyun-suk.

821
00:30:43,875 --> 00:30:45,476
-Sung-jun's Miss.
-Sung-jun's Miss.

822
00:30:45,543 --> 00:30:47,145
-Nice for Hyun-suk.
-Nice for Hyun-suk.

823
00:30:47,212 --> 00:30:48,847
-"Miss."
-I see.

824
00:30:48,913 --> 00:30:51,549
I'm going to make three different kinds

825
00:30:51,616 --> 00:30:52,984
-of small bites.
-Which are?

826
00:30:53,051 --> 00:30:56,187
First, beef tartare turned into a canapé.

827
00:30:56,254 --> 00:30:58,857
Next, a sushi tart.

828
00:30:58,923 --> 00:31:01,426
A tart filled with fish tartare.

829
00:31:01,492 --> 00:31:04,262
Lastly, I'll use shrimp and vegetables

830
00:31:04,329 --> 00:31:06,831
and make a thin shrimp sandwich.

831
00:31:07,398 --> 00:31:08,466
HE'LL ALSO MAKE 3 BITES!

832
00:31:08,533 --> 00:31:10,368
-Using bread?
-Yes.

833
00:31:10,435 --> 00:31:13,471
Sung-jun said he'd make him
take a stroll around Naples,

834
00:31:13,538 --> 00:31:15,640
so which region will you take him to?

835
00:31:15,707 --> 00:31:17,108
-I'll take him…
-Cheongdam.

836
00:31:17,175 --> 00:31:20,245
-…to Paldang.
-Paldang?

837
00:31:20,311 --> 00:31:21,913
That area has good Pyongyang <i>naengmyeon</i>.

838
00:31:21,980 --> 00:31:24,382
-You'll take him to Paldang?
-Just like he wanted,

839
00:31:24,449 --> 00:31:26,985
I'll condense the calories, nutrients,

840
00:31:27,051 --> 00:31:28,753
and other aspects of a dish into a bite

841
00:31:28,820 --> 00:31:30,288
to prevent him from bonking.

842
00:31:30,355 --> 00:31:32,757
-I'll do that.
-All right.

843
00:31:32,824 --> 00:31:36,895
Let's begin Go Soo's Bite Master
for Go Soo.

844
00:31:36,961 --> 00:31:39,364
Give us the timer for 15 minutes.

845
00:31:39,430 --> 00:31:41,266
The huge mountain of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,

846
00:31:41,332 --> 00:31:43,067
the big fish of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,

847
00:31:43,134 --> 00:31:44,802
Chef Choi Hyun-suk.

848
00:31:44,869 --> 00:31:47,038
Here to gnaw mercilessly on that big fish,

849
00:31:47,105 --> 00:31:49,340
the doctor fish of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,

850
00:31:49,407 --> 00:31:51,776
-Chef Kwon Sung-jun.
-The doctor fish?

851
00:31:51,843 --> 00:31:53,344
That thing feeds on dead skin cells.

852
00:31:54,679 --> 00:31:56,147
He thought he was an angler,

853
00:31:56,214 --> 00:31:57,415
but he was a doctor fish.

854
00:31:57,482 --> 00:31:58,483
That was random.

855
00:31:58,549 --> 00:32:00,518
-I was thrown off.
-It eats dead skin cells.

856
00:32:00,585 --> 00:32:03,688
Which one of them
will capture Soo's heart?

857
00:32:03,755 --> 00:32:06,724
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

858
00:32:06,791 --> 00:32:08,259
THE 15-MINUTE COOK-OFF BEGINS

859
00:32:08,326 --> 00:32:09,394
Whoo!

860
00:32:10,795 --> 00:32:12,430
THE YOUNG MAN VS. THE OLD MAN

861
00:32:13,932 --> 00:32:14,933
Where's the club?

862
00:32:15,500 --> 00:32:17,101
What are you looking for, Hyun-suk?

863
00:32:17,168 --> 00:32:18,770
-Where's the club?
-A club?

864
00:32:18,836 --> 00:32:20,338
-The rolling pin's right there.
-Right.

865
00:32:20,405 --> 00:32:23,207
IT WAS RIGHT IN FRONT OF HIM

866
00:32:23,274 --> 00:32:24,208
Stop that.

867
00:32:24,776 --> 00:32:26,644
HE CAN'T BELIEVE HIMSELF EITHER

868
00:32:27,312 --> 00:32:28,613
He's cutting the bread.

869
00:32:29,180 --> 00:32:30,848
FLATTENING WITH A ROLLING PIN

870
00:32:30,915 --> 00:32:32,951
He's much slower than he used to be.

871
00:32:33,017 --> 00:32:34,819
I'm taking my time on purpose.

872
00:32:35,386 --> 00:32:36,621
1. CUT OUT CIRCLES FROM FLATTENED BREAD

873
00:32:36,688 --> 00:32:38,156
He flattened bread

874
00:32:38,222 --> 00:32:41,092
and is now cutting it out into circles.

875
00:32:41,159 --> 00:32:42,293
Is that oil?

876
00:32:42,360 --> 00:32:43,328
BUTTER

877
00:32:45,196 --> 00:32:47,665
Is he making tart shells?

878
00:32:48,633 --> 00:32:50,335
RYE BREAD FOR CANAPÉ
ALSO BECOMES BITE-SIZED

879
00:32:50,401 --> 00:32:55,740
Hyun-suk has to make
a canapé, a tart, and a sandwich.

880
00:32:55,807 --> 00:32:56,674
TIMER ON

881
00:32:58,242 --> 00:33:00,011
He's grinding bread right away.

882
00:33:00,611 --> 00:33:01,612
1. GRIND RYE BREAD INTO BREADCRUMBS

883
00:33:01,679 --> 00:33:03,181
They're both using bread.

884
00:33:03,514 --> 00:33:04,582
DRIED FILEFISH FILLETS

885
00:33:06,751 --> 00:33:10,989
Hyun-suk has had an overwhelming lead
against Sung-jun to this day.

886
00:33:12,690 --> 00:33:14,325
BEGINS TO CHOP!

887
00:33:14,392 --> 00:33:16,461
That's so fast.

888
00:33:16,527 --> 00:33:18,096
Whoa.

889
00:33:18,529 --> 00:33:21,299
INCREDIBLE SPEED

890
00:33:23,534 --> 00:33:24,369
CRUSHED GARLIC

891
00:33:25,670 --> 00:33:26,704
OLIVE OIL

892
00:33:27,271 --> 00:33:28,906
He's really quick with his hands.

893
00:33:28,973 --> 00:33:31,843
He has everything planned out.

894
00:33:32,410 --> 00:33:33,444
MAKING TOMATO SAUCE

895
00:33:33,511 --> 00:33:36,114
He said he'd make
meatballs in tomato sauce.

896
00:33:37,015 --> 00:33:39,283
He's cooking the tomatoes right away.

897
00:33:39,350 --> 00:33:41,652
Stir-fried onion and sugar.

898
00:33:43,621 --> 00:33:44,622
LOOK AT THAT GUY

899
00:33:45,556 --> 00:33:46,958
A TAUNT USING SALT!

900
00:33:48,026 --> 00:33:49,927
Sung-jun taunts Hyun-suk.

901
00:33:49,994 --> 00:33:50,928
He stole his thing.

902
00:33:50,995 --> 00:33:52,230
Wasn't his arm too short?

903
00:33:52,296 --> 00:33:53,765
SHORT AND TUBBY

904
00:33:53,831 --> 00:33:56,000
It probably landed on his head.

905
00:33:56,067 --> 00:33:57,902
<i>I thought he aimed for his head.</i>

906
00:33:58,603 --> 00:34:00,271
I think I did get some on my head.

907
00:34:00,338 --> 00:34:02,006
That's hilarious.

908
00:34:02,073 --> 00:34:04,475
He's facing many handicaps

909
00:34:04,542 --> 00:34:06,511
whenever he faces these younger chefs.

910
00:34:06,577 --> 00:34:07,512
Look at him go!

911
00:34:07,578 --> 00:34:08,880
I'M THE ORIGINAL!

912
00:34:08,946 --> 00:34:10,548
That's what I'm talking about!

913
00:34:11,215 --> 00:34:12,316
THIS IS!

914
00:34:14,419 --> 00:34:15,920
HOW IT'S SUPPOSED TO LOOK!

915
00:34:16,487 --> 00:34:17,855
EXHILARATING

916
00:34:17,922 --> 00:34:20,024
<i>There's a difference in arm lengths.</i>

917
00:34:20,091 --> 00:34:21,993
SLANDER AGAINST THE TUBBY YOUNG MAN

918
00:34:22,560 --> 00:34:23,895
MEANWHILE, HE GATHERS THE SALT

919
00:34:23,961 --> 00:34:26,297
In the old days, salt was like gold.

920
00:34:26,364 --> 00:34:27,598
GATHERING GOLD

921
00:34:27,665 --> 00:34:30,635
Chef Hyun-suk makes circles
with the rye bread.

922
00:34:30,701 --> 00:34:34,439
He's making finger food, so it's important
to make the bites pretty.

923
00:34:34,505 --> 00:34:37,208
He needs to eat it in a bite,
and that's what's important.

924
00:34:37,275 --> 00:34:38,609
It shouldn't be too big.

925
00:34:38,676 --> 00:34:40,244
Soo won't like that.

926
00:34:40,978 --> 00:34:43,114
SUNG-JUN PREPARES MEATBALL MIXTURE

927
00:34:44,182 --> 00:34:45,416
STRIP LOIN

928
00:34:45,483 --> 00:34:47,318
-What's that?
-What?

929
00:34:47,385 --> 00:34:49,620
That one. Is that bread soaked in milk?

930
00:34:50,221 --> 00:34:51,055
Milk.

931
00:34:51,122 --> 00:34:53,057
I see. You soaked bread in milk.

932
00:34:53,124 --> 00:34:55,460
He's grinding strip loin
with bread soaked in milk.

933
00:34:56,294 --> 00:35:00,264
In Naples, they always add old bread
after soaking it in water or milk.

934
00:35:00,331 --> 00:35:01,532
OH

935
00:35:01,599 --> 00:35:03,935
Hyun-suk is doing his best.

936
00:35:04,001 --> 00:35:05,503
He's also using meat.

937
00:35:05,570 --> 00:35:07,038
-Is that strip loin too?
-Yes.

938
00:35:07,105 --> 00:35:09,774
-He said he'd make tartare, right?
-Yes.

939
00:35:12,410 --> 00:35:14,112
He's grinding beef, and…

940
00:35:14,679 --> 00:35:16,214
I'M A SPRAY…

941
00:35:16,280 --> 00:35:17,915
He couldn't find the stick blender,

942
00:35:17,982 --> 00:35:19,717
and he almost stuck the spray bottle on.

943
00:35:20,485 --> 00:35:22,053
WHY ARE YOU DOING THIS, REALLY?

944
00:35:22,687 --> 00:35:23,788
CHUCKLE

945
00:35:23,855 --> 00:35:26,691
He almost took this and stuck it on top.

946
00:35:28,126 --> 00:35:29,660
Oh, no.

947
00:35:29,727 --> 00:35:32,263
EVERYONE WAILS

948
00:35:32,330 --> 00:35:33,898
What's he going to do?

949
00:35:33,965 --> 00:35:36,534
He's supposed to be asleep by now.

950
00:35:36,601 --> 00:35:38,236
Better be careful.

951
00:35:38,302 --> 00:35:40,271
Ho-young, you be careful too.

952
00:35:40,338 --> 00:35:41,873
You be careful too, Ho-young.

953
00:35:41,939 --> 00:35:44,242
-That's heartbreaking.
-Yes.

954
00:35:44,942 --> 00:35:45,776
CHESTNUT JAM

955
00:35:46,410 --> 00:35:48,946
He's mixing chestnut jam with lemon juice.

956
00:35:49,013 --> 00:35:51,115
Chestnut jam with lemon juice?
Will that work?

957
00:35:51,682 --> 00:35:52,650
It sounds weird.

958
00:35:53,417 --> 00:35:54,986
SALTING HIM AWAY!

959
00:35:55,052 --> 00:35:56,420
When he sprinkles the salt,

960
00:35:56,487 --> 00:35:57,955
does it land where he wants it to?

961
00:35:58,022 --> 00:35:59,991
It's kind of like a ritual now.

962
00:36:00,558 --> 00:36:01,626
SALT RITUAL

963
00:36:01,692 --> 00:36:03,661
-To keep bad luck away?
-To keep bad luck away.

964
00:36:05,196 --> 00:36:06,330
That goes into the tartare?

965
00:36:06,397 --> 00:36:07,565
4. MIX BEEF AND LEMON CHESTNUT JAM

966
00:36:07,632 --> 00:36:09,033
HE SUDDENLY SPRINTS?!

967
00:36:09,100 --> 00:36:10,368
No, Chef Hyun-suk!

968
00:36:10,935 --> 00:36:12,136
No, Chef Hyun-suk!

969
00:36:12,770 --> 00:36:14,739
It looks like he's adding olive oil.

970
00:36:15,573 --> 00:36:18,442
He's facing many handicaps

971
00:36:18,509 --> 00:36:20,478
whenever he faces these younger chefs.

972
00:36:21,646 --> 00:36:22,480
PLAIN CHEESE

973
00:36:25,349 --> 00:36:27,318
ADD PLAIN CHEESE INTO A RECTANGULAR MOLD

974
00:36:27,385 --> 00:36:28,653
Is he facing a crisis?

975
00:36:28,719 --> 00:36:29,687
TOP WITH BEEF TARTARE

976
00:36:29,754 --> 00:36:31,088
Hyun-suk is doing his best.

977
00:36:31,689 --> 00:36:35,092
This is a wonderful opportunity
for Sung-jun to take Hyun-suk down.

978
00:36:35,893 --> 00:36:36,727
BUTTER

979
00:36:37,295 --> 00:36:39,530
CROUTONS FOR DESSERT, INTO THE OVEN

980
00:36:40,031 --> 00:36:42,200
WALKS OVER TO PULL OUT
DEEP-FRIED FILEFISH FILLETS

981
00:36:42,266 --> 00:36:44,202
-What is that?
-It's burnt!

982
00:36:44,268 --> 00:36:46,003
The eggplant is burnt!

983
00:36:46,070 --> 00:36:47,438
-Is that eggplant?
-What is it? Eggplant?

984
00:36:47,505 --> 00:36:50,541
No, that's filefish fillet.

985
00:36:50,608 --> 00:36:52,343
-Filefish fillet.
-His mistake!

986
00:36:52,410 --> 00:36:54,312
FILEFISH FILLET, MISS!

987
00:36:54,845 --> 00:36:56,681
-The filefish fillets got burnt.
-Another try.

988
00:36:56,747 --> 00:36:59,217
He just used up the precious fillets.

989
00:36:59,283 --> 00:37:01,452
-He lost two pieces.
-I lost two pieces.

990
00:37:01,519 --> 00:37:03,554
Did you soak it in water?

991
00:37:03,621 --> 00:37:04,455
No, he threw them in.

992
00:37:04,522 --> 00:37:05,790
THE BURNT FILLETS LOOK GOOD!

993
00:37:05,856 --> 00:37:07,592
-They look good!
-No, they don't!

994
00:37:07,658 --> 00:37:08,593
WAR IN THE COMMENT SECTION

995
00:37:08,659 --> 00:37:09,694
Nine minutes left.

996
00:37:10,828 --> 00:37:12,463
ROLLING THE MEATBALL MIXTURE

997
00:37:13,197 --> 00:37:15,099
AND THROWING IT INTO THE OIL

998
00:37:15,166 --> 00:37:16,834
I think that'll burn too. It's a dry mix.

999
00:37:17,501 --> 00:37:18,703
Why is this so hot?

1000
00:37:19,570 --> 00:37:22,139
-Why are you asking me?
-It's boiling hard.

1001
00:37:22,206 --> 00:37:23,874
Ask the stove.

1002
00:37:24,875 --> 00:37:26,444
-Add more oil.
-Add more oil.

1003
00:37:26,510 --> 00:37:28,446
-Wait.
-It's too hot.

1004
00:37:28,512 --> 00:37:29,580
-The oil is too hot.
-Turn it off!

1005
00:37:29,647 --> 00:37:30,481
-I did.
-He did.

1006
00:37:30,548 --> 00:37:32,516
-The oil is way too hot.
-The oil is too hot.

1007
00:37:32,583 --> 00:37:34,652
-Again?
-That'll only burn the outside.

1008
00:37:34,719 --> 00:37:35,620
You should add more oil.

1009
00:37:35,686 --> 00:37:37,521
-Hey, it's too burnt!
-It's burnt!

1010
00:37:38,956 --> 00:37:40,024
QUICKLY SAVING THE FILEFISH

1011
00:37:40,091 --> 00:37:41,859
-It's burnt again!
-The filefish fillet!

1012
00:37:41,926 --> 00:37:43,761
-It's not burnt.
-It's not.

1013
00:37:43,828 --> 00:37:46,063
-It's not burnt.
-I guess he'll just use it.

1014
00:37:46,130 --> 00:37:47,632
-That's…
-The oil is way too hot.

1015
00:37:47,698 --> 00:37:48,666
Why is it so hot?

1016
00:37:48,733 --> 00:37:51,636
-You did that. Add more oil.
-Pour more oil inside.

1017
00:37:51,702 --> 00:37:53,237
Add more oil.

1018
00:37:53,304 --> 00:37:55,539
-It's an emergency.
-It's an emergency.

1019
00:37:55,606 --> 00:37:56,974
That looks good.

1020
00:37:57,041 --> 00:37:58,676
-That looks good.
-It's Sung-jun's emergency.

1021
00:37:58,743 --> 00:37:59,810
MORE COMMENTERS HAVE JOINED

1022
00:38:00,578 --> 00:38:03,147
-Things look very hectic for Hyun-suk.
-It does.

1023
00:38:03,214 --> 00:38:04,048
YUJA CHEONG

1024
00:38:04,882 --> 00:38:06,284
YUJA CHEONG, ORIENTAL DRESSING

1025
00:38:06,917 --> 00:38:08,619
FINELY CHOP RAW HALIBUT

1026
00:38:08,686 --> 00:38:11,088
He's seasoning raw halibut
with <i>yuja cheong</i>

1027
00:38:11,155 --> 00:38:13,858
-and oriental dressing.
-I see.

1028
00:38:14,425 --> 00:38:15,559
WHAT'S NEXT?

1029
00:38:15,626 --> 00:38:17,528
Chef Hyun-suk makes flour batter.

1030
00:38:17,595 --> 00:38:19,497
I guess he'll deep-fry something.

1031
00:38:19,563 --> 00:38:22,466
He's making fried batter bits.

1032
00:38:22,533 --> 00:38:24,902
-I see.
-Also known as <i>tenkatsu</i>.

1033
00:38:24,969 --> 00:38:26,070
<i>Tenkatsu</i>.

1034
00:38:26,137 --> 00:38:27,338
Strainer.

1035
00:38:27,405 --> 00:38:28,439
GETS A STRAINER

1036
00:38:28,506 --> 00:38:31,609
-It must be hectic to make three dishes.
-Of course.

1037
00:38:31,676 --> 00:38:34,945
Hyun-suk has to make a canapé, a tart,

1038
00:38:35,012 --> 00:38:37,081
and a sandwich.

1039
00:38:37,148 --> 00:38:38,649
-Shrimp sandwich.
-Yes.

1040
00:38:38,716 --> 00:38:41,719
Cooked shrimp and broccoli.

1041
00:38:42,753 --> 00:38:45,589
You must make a light dish
that looks pretty, tastes good,

1042
00:38:45,656 --> 00:38:46,590
and is nutritious!

1043
00:38:46,657 --> 00:38:47,758
6. STIR-FRY WITH THREE CHEESES

1044
00:38:47,825 --> 00:38:49,393
BEEP

1045
00:38:49,860 --> 00:38:51,128
The timer went off.

1046
00:38:51,195 --> 00:38:55,132
He's checking the tart shells
he made with bread.

1047
00:38:57,668 --> 00:38:59,570
TAKES THE CANAPÉ BREAD OUT FIRST

1048
00:39:00,137 --> 00:39:01,272
My breadcrumbs!

1049
00:39:01,339 --> 00:39:03,107
-Breadcrumbs.
-You don't have a lot of time.

1050
00:39:03,174 --> 00:39:04,675
What's the time? Seven minutes!

1051
00:39:04,742 --> 00:39:07,044
Time is flying by especially faster today.

1052
00:39:07,111 --> 00:39:08,846
Why don't I have enough time?

1053
00:39:08,913 --> 00:39:10,281
Wait a minute.

1054
00:39:10,348 --> 00:39:13,851
He coated fried filefish with flour,
which means he'll double-fry those.

1055
00:39:13,918 --> 00:39:15,319
These aren't filefish fillets.

1056
00:39:15,386 --> 00:39:17,922
-These are eggplant pieces.
-Eggplants!

1057
00:39:18,489 --> 00:39:19,890
SANDWICH EMMENTALER BETWEEN EGGPLANT

1058
00:39:20,658 --> 00:39:21,926
Are you deep-frying those?

1059
00:39:21,992 --> 00:39:24,328
-I think so.
-Yes, Naples has many fried dishes.

1060
00:39:24,395 --> 00:39:27,064
-So you'll coat them and refry them?
-That's right.

1061
00:39:27,131 --> 00:39:29,567
The oil still seems too hot.

1062
00:39:29,633 --> 00:39:31,335
Breadcrumbs will burn instantly.

1063
00:39:31,402 --> 00:39:33,437
Soo wouldn't like anything that's burnt.

1064
00:39:33,504 --> 00:39:36,407
-No.
-He's not checking on the temperature.

1065
00:39:36,474 --> 00:39:37,742
It's good enough.

1066
00:39:37,808 --> 00:39:39,677
-Is it?
-It looks good.

1067
00:39:39,744 --> 00:39:41,812
-He's reciting the chant again.
-It looks amazing.

1068
00:39:41,879 --> 00:39:42,947
This is spectacular.

1069
00:39:43,013 --> 00:39:44,415
He does that when he gets anxious.

1070
00:39:44,482 --> 00:39:45,950
Yes, that means he's nervous.

1071
00:39:46,016 --> 00:39:47,952
-I'm fine.
-"It looks delicious."

1072
00:39:48,018 --> 00:39:50,020
-I'm okay.
-That means he's nervous.

1073
00:39:50,087 --> 00:39:51,689
I AM OKAY

1074
00:39:51,756 --> 00:39:54,125
What's that? What's he kneading now?

1075
00:39:54,191 --> 00:39:56,494
-These? Arancini.
-Arancini?

1076
00:39:56,560 --> 00:39:58,262
Is that rice?

1077
00:39:58,329 --> 00:40:00,631
-Frozen fried rice.
-Microwavable fried rice.

1078
00:40:00,698 --> 00:40:03,267
Sung-ju! Can you report from the kitchen?

1079
00:40:03,334 --> 00:40:05,836
-Five minutes left.
-I'll report from the kitchen.

1080
00:40:05,903 --> 00:40:10,341
Sung-jun's oil temperature
still looks too high.

1081
00:40:10,408 --> 00:40:12,009
The filefish is quite burnt, isn't it?

1082
00:40:12,076 --> 00:40:14,178
Let me show you the ruined ones.

1083
00:40:15,713 --> 00:40:17,181
That's filefish?

1084
00:40:17,248 --> 00:40:18,282
This is awful.

1085
00:40:18,349 --> 00:40:19,550
Is that a block of ink?

1086
00:40:20,317 --> 00:40:21,585
You can do calligraphy with it.

1087
00:40:21,652 --> 00:40:23,687
What's this?

1088
00:40:23,754 --> 00:40:25,222
-Tomato sauce. I'll blend it.
-Tomato sauce.

1089
00:40:25,289 --> 00:40:27,191
-Let me try the tomato sauce.
-Sure.

1090
00:40:27,258 --> 00:40:30,027
Does it taste like
you're strolling in Naples?

1091
00:40:30,594 --> 00:40:33,597
IS IT THE FLAVOR OF A STROLL IN NAPLES?

1092
00:40:34,598 --> 00:40:35,733
It's not done yet.

1093
00:40:35,800 --> 00:40:37,001
It's a little bland.

1094
00:40:37,067 --> 00:40:38,636
-It's not done yet.
-I see.

1095
00:40:38,702 --> 00:40:41,071
It's not Naples, but Napo-ri, Korea.

1096
00:40:41,138 --> 00:40:43,040
Napo-ri?

1097
00:40:43,107 --> 00:40:45,009
The stroll is a bit of a bore.

1098
00:40:45,075 --> 00:40:46,877
It needs more umami.

1099
00:40:46,944 --> 00:40:48,379
-Umami.
-I'll blend it and season it.

1100
00:40:48,446 --> 00:40:50,080
-You have to season it, right?
-Very well.

1101
00:40:50,147 --> 00:40:52,149
-Three and a half minutes.
-Huh? Three and a half?

1102
00:40:52,216 --> 00:40:53,918
-Three and a half minutes.
-Three and a half?

1103
00:40:53,984 --> 00:40:55,753
You're rushing today, Sung-jun.

1104
00:40:56,220 --> 00:41:00,090
3. BLEND TOMATO SAUCE FINELY,
SEASON WITH SALT, AND REHEAT

1105
00:41:00,691 --> 00:41:01,692
WHAT'S NEXT?

1106
00:41:01,759 --> 00:41:03,294
A minute and a half left.

1107
00:41:03,360 --> 00:41:05,863
A minute and a half.
You have to start finishing up.

1108
00:41:05,930 --> 00:41:08,165
-Are these burnt? Are they okay?
-They aren't burnt.

1109
00:41:08,232 --> 00:41:11,035
These aren't burnt.

1110
00:41:11,101 --> 00:41:13,671
Stay strong, <i>polpette</i>! I got this!

1111
00:41:13,737 --> 00:41:15,673
You have a chance at defeating Hyun-suk.

1112
00:41:16,240 --> 00:41:17,875
MEANWHILE

1113
00:41:18,442 --> 00:41:19,710
TA-DA

1114
00:41:19,777 --> 00:41:21,245
The piece shouldn't be too big.

1115
00:41:21,812 --> 00:41:24,882
Hyun-suk puts lots of work into it.

1116
00:41:24,949 --> 00:41:27,051
What's the white thing in the middle?

1117
00:41:27,117 --> 00:41:28,052
Cream cheese?

1118
00:41:28,118 --> 00:41:29,553
What's in this, Ho-young?

1119
00:41:29,620 --> 00:41:31,789
Chestnut jam and lemon juice.

1120
00:41:31,856 --> 00:41:34,658
Does chestnut jam
go well with lemon juice?

1121
00:41:34,725 --> 00:41:36,660
-I'll try the strip loin.
-Is that all right?

1122
00:41:36,727 --> 00:41:39,430
Does it taste nice? Or was it a miss?

1123
00:41:42,533 --> 00:41:43,400
Nice!

1124
00:41:43,467 --> 00:41:45,202
VERY NICE, HYUN-SUK!

1125
00:41:46,537 --> 00:41:48,138
A NICE SMILE

1126
00:41:48,205 --> 00:41:49,573
It's refreshing and sweet.

1127
00:41:49,640 --> 00:41:51,075
-Really?
-Refreshing and sweet.

1128
00:41:51,141 --> 00:41:54,011
-Soo likes his food sweet.
-He does.

1129
00:41:54,078 --> 00:41:56,146
You have 2 minutes and 15 seconds.

1130
00:41:56,213 --> 00:41:58,282
And the leftover raw fish.

1131
00:41:58,349 --> 00:41:59,483
What's that for?

1132
00:41:59,550 --> 00:42:02,920
-It's for the tartar sauce for arancini.
-On top of the arancini.

1133
00:42:05,823 --> 00:42:07,024
GREEK YOGURT

1134
00:42:09,727 --> 00:42:12,096
-Olive oil!
-Right here.

1135
00:42:12,496 --> 00:42:13,330
OLIVE OIL

1136
00:42:14,632 --> 00:42:15,499
SPROUTS

1137
00:42:15,566 --> 00:42:18,769
And a drop of lemon juice.

1138
00:42:18,836 --> 00:42:20,337
Things are busy here.

1139
00:42:20,404 --> 00:42:21,872
That must be for the sandwich.

1140
00:42:21,939 --> 00:42:25,075
It's a mix of broccoli,
shrimp, and cheese.

1141
00:42:25,976 --> 00:42:26,810
SWOOSH

1142
00:42:27,378 --> 00:42:28,712
BREAD ON THE PAN, OUT

1143
00:42:30,514 --> 00:42:33,050
CUT IN HALF

1144
00:42:33,117 --> 00:42:34,618
AND FILL IT UP

1145
00:42:35,452 --> 00:42:37,054
PUT IT TOGETHER TO MAKE A SANDWICH

1146
00:42:37,121 --> 00:42:38,722
He turned bread into a taco shell.

1147
00:42:39,857 --> 00:42:41,125
-By flattening it?
-Let me see.

1148
00:42:41,792 --> 00:42:44,161
EVERYONE IS AMAZED BY THE PRESENTATION

1149
00:42:44,228 --> 00:42:46,463
-As expected from a seasoned chef.
-Right.

1150
00:42:46,530 --> 00:42:47,831
You can't take him for granted.

1151
00:42:47,898 --> 00:42:50,401
He's pulling something out of the oven.

1152
00:42:50,467 --> 00:42:52,469
Look at that.

1153
00:42:52,536 --> 00:42:55,039
-He worked hard for this single shell.
-Pretty.

1154
00:42:55,105 --> 00:42:56,707
-Is that ripped?
-It obviously is.

1155
00:42:56,774 --> 00:42:57,608
-It is, right?
-Yes.

1156
00:42:57,675 --> 00:42:59,243
SHH!

1157
00:42:59,310 --> 00:43:00,978
Don't worry about it.

1158
00:43:01,045 --> 00:43:03,380
But it'll be fine

1159
00:43:03,447 --> 00:43:06,317
as long as it doesn't leak.

1160
00:43:06,383 --> 00:43:08,018
-He'll put batter bits inside.
-Batter bits.

1161
00:43:08,085 --> 00:43:09,787
-Butter.
-Butter.

1162
00:43:10,654 --> 00:43:11,989
This one looks good too.

1163
00:43:12,056 --> 00:43:15,125
-That goes on top. It's bite-sized.
-That will taste so good with yogurt.

1164
00:43:15,192 --> 00:43:16,927
He coated the tart shell with yogurt,

1165
00:43:16,994 --> 00:43:19,096
-filled it with batter bits, then butter.
-In layers.

1166
00:43:19,163 --> 00:43:20,664
Lastly, he topped it with fish.

1167
00:43:20,731 --> 00:43:22,333
He used it as an adhesive.

1168
00:43:22,399 --> 00:43:24,401
A minute and 30 seconds left.

1169
00:43:24,935 --> 00:43:25,769
ICE CREAM CONE

1170
00:43:25,836 --> 00:43:28,105
He's doing something with ice cream.

1171
00:43:28,172 --> 00:43:29,673
My ice cream.

1172
00:43:30,074 --> 00:43:31,542
HE TAKES THE ICE CREAM

1173
00:43:32,142 --> 00:43:35,145
AND BEGINS TO PLATE THE DISH!

1174
00:43:35,579 --> 00:43:36,413
GETTING ARANCINI

1175
00:43:39,550 --> 00:43:41,085
PUTS IT ON THE PLATE

1176
00:43:41,685 --> 00:43:43,654
AND TOPS IT WITH FISH TARTAR SAUCE

1177
00:43:43,721 --> 00:43:45,189
You have one minute left!

1178
00:43:45,255 --> 00:43:46,557
One minute to go.

1179
00:43:46,624 --> 00:43:47,558
Forty-three seconds.

1180
00:43:47,625 --> 00:43:49,293
-Finish up, Sung-jun.
-Finish up.

1181
00:43:49,360 --> 00:43:50,461
GREEK YOGURT, CHESTNUT JAM

1182
00:43:52,229 --> 00:43:54,098
Why aren't you using the filefish?

1183
00:43:54,164 --> 00:43:56,100
-Dang it, the filefish!
-You have to use it.

1184
00:43:56,166 --> 00:43:57,701
-The filefish is just sitting here.
-Filefish.

1185
00:43:57,768 --> 00:44:00,371
-Thirty seconds!
-Where's the filefish?

1186
00:44:00,437 --> 00:44:02,406
-Where's the fish?
-I can't work with this!

1187
00:44:02,473 --> 00:44:05,042
He can't cut it!

1188
00:44:05,109 --> 00:44:06,844
-Where's the fish?
-I can't work with this!

1189
00:44:06,910 --> 00:44:08,145
QUICKLY GIVES UP

1190
00:44:08,212 --> 00:44:09,880
He's unable to chop it!

1191
00:44:10,447 --> 00:44:12,249
I'll eat it later.

1192
00:44:12,316 --> 00:44:13,917
I don't think he'll use the filefish.

1193
00:44:14,318 --> 00:44:16,020
FINISHING UP THE PRESENTATION!

1194
00:44:17,287 --> 00:44:18,122
EGGPLANT AND CHEESE

1195
00:44:19,790 --> 00:44:20,624
MEATBALL

1196
00:44:21,992 --> 00:44:25,596
FINISHING THE SECOND BITE WITH A SKEWER

1197
00:44:25,663 --> 00:44:27,564
You have ten seconds left!

1198
00:44:27,631 --> 00:44:29,366
-Nine. Eight.
-Nine. Eight.

1199
00:44:29,433 --> 00:44:31,368
-Seven. Six.
-Seven. Six.

1200
00:44:31,935 --> 00:44:33,003
HYUN-SUK ALSO WRAPS UP!

1201
00:44:33,504 --> 00:44:34,338
SPROUTS

1202
00:44:34,772 --> 00:44:35,806
APPLE

1203
00:44:36,874 --> 00:44:39,143
WRAPPING UP WITH JULIENNED APPLE ON TOP

1204
00:44:39,810 --> 00:44:40,644
TOMATO SAUCE

1205
00:44:40,711 --> 00:44:43,013
-Five. Four. Three.
-Five. Four. Three.

1206
00:44:43,080 --> 00:44:44,114
-Hyun-suk finishes.
-Two.

1207
00:44:44,181 --> 00:44:45,382
-And Sung-jun?
-One.

1208
00:44:45,449 --> 00:44:47,785
It's a shame
that he couldn't use the filefish.

1209
00:44:47,851 --> 00:44:49,219
It wasn't an easy round.

1210
00:44:49,553 --> 00:44:50,988
THEY BOTH MADE THREE BITES

1211
00:44:51,055 --> 00:44:51,889
He couldn't cut the fish.

1212
00:44:51,955 --> 00:44:55,259
He's not using that anyway,
so try it and see how tough it is.

1213
00:44:55,325 --> 00:44:56,694
How tough is it?

1214
00:44:57,995 --> 00:44:59,463
WE GET IT…

1215
00:44:59,530 --> 00:45:01,498
-If Nam-no can't eat it, it's inedible.
-As tough as a tire.

1216
00:45:01,565 --> 00:45:03,734
I can eat most things, but not that.

1217
00:45:03,801 --> 00:45:05,402
They both look pretty.

1218
00:45:05,469 --> 00:45:07,204
THE LITTLE BITES TAKE OFF

1219
00:45:07,671 --> 00:45:09,373
That's truly in the Naples style.

1220
00:45:09,440 --> 00:45:10,507
Is it really?

1221
00:45:10,574 --> 00:45:11,842
Wow.

1222
00:45:14,011 --> 00:45:18,716
They finished making both dishes
and filled the order Go Soo's Bite Master.

1223
00:45:18,782 --> 00:45:21,251
Chef Hyun-suk finished first,
so please try

1224
00:45:21,318 --> 00:45:23,787
<i>-Sung-jun's Miss, Nice for Hyun-suk.</i>
<i>-Nice for Hyun-suk.</i>

1225
00:45:23,854 --> 00:45:24,755
BEEF CANAPÉ

1226
00:45:25,022 --> 00:45:27,658
HALIBUT TART

1227
00:45:27,991 --> 00:45:29,927
SHRIMP SANDWICH

1228
00:45:30,728 --> 00:45:34,865
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
SUNG-JUN'S MISS, NICE FOR HYUN-SUK

1229
00:45:35,432 --> 00:45:36,700
Gosh.

1230
00:45:36,767 --> 00:45:37,735
SNIFF

1231
00:45:37,801 --> 00:45:38,902
He smells it first.

1232
00:45:38,969 --> 00:45:40,070
What should he start with?

1233
00:45:40,137 --> 00:45:41,205
It's finger food,

1234
00:45:41,271 --> 00:45:44,808
-so have the bites from the left.
-From the left.

1235
00:45:44,875 --> 00:45:47,978
Is the very bottom a piece of bread?

1236
00:45:48,045 --> 00:45:50,948
<i>I cut some rye bread and grilled it</i>
<i>in the oven to make it crispy,</i>

1237
00:45:51,014 --> 00:45:52,816
<i>put cheese in the middle,</i>

1238
00:45:52,883 --> 00:45:56,754
<i>and topped it with sweet and sour beef</i>
<i>in chestnut jam and lemon juice.</i>

1239
00:45:56,820 --> 00:45:58,789
<i>Lastly, apple pieces for more crispness.</i>

1240
00:45:58,856 --> 00:46:01,191
You can just eat it in one bite.

1241
00:46:01,258 --> 00:46:03,627
-The size is perfect.
-Those were apple pieces?

1242
00:46:03,694 --> 00:46:05,362
GO SOO'S SINGLE BITE

1243
00:46:05,429 --> 00:46:07,531
He ate the apple and all in one bite.

1244
00:46:07,598 --> 00:46:11,135
One bite must include the right flavor,
nutrition, and presentation!

1245
00:46:11,201 --> 00:46:13,704
-The portion isn't important to him.
-Right.

1246
00:46:13,771 --> 00:46:16,039
"There's no difference
between 100 g and 500 g of beef."

1247
00:46:16,106 --> 00:46:18,308
-"They're the same." A big portion…
-"They're the same."

1248
00:46:18,375 --> 00:46:21,245
Wait a second. He just frowned a little.

1249
00:46:21,311 --> 00:46:22,412
He's like, "What is this?"

1250
00:46:22,980 --> 00:46:24,414
He seems puzzled.

1251
00:46:25,082 --> 00:46:26,817
NERVOUS

1252
00:46:26,884 --> 00:46:29,453
I guess he's not 100% happy about it.

1253
00:46:31,455 --> 00:46:32,556
UNSURE

1254
00:46:32,623 --> 00:46:34,424
Why is he tilting his head?

1255
00:46:34,491 --> 00:46:35,459
Is it too big?

1256
00:46:35,959 --> 00:46:37,094
Wow.

1257
00:46:37,861 --> 00:46:39,029
Do you want to know?

1258
00:46:40,197 --> 00:46:41,365
Of course, we do.

1259
00:46:43,567 --> 00:46:44,902
WE'VE BEEN WAITING…

1260
00:46:44,968 --> 00:46:46,570
-Of course.
-Of course, we're curious.

1261
00:46:46,637 --> 00:46:49,006
I almost paid him 500 won to find out.

1262
00:46:49,072 --> 00:46:52,209
There was a touch of lemon
in the strip loin,

1263
00:46:52,276 --> 00:46:57,247
and the bread, the rye bread
mixes so well with everything else.

1264
00:46:57,314 --> 00:47:01,585
Then the cheese wraps everything up.

1265
00:47:01,652 --> 00:47:03,253
It feels quite nutritious.

1266
00:47:03,320 --> 00:47:05,122
-I see.
-It must be.

1267
00:47:05,189 --> 00:47:07,257
It has carbs, protein, and fat.

1268
00:47:07,324 --> 00:47:09,126
Goodness. My mouth keeps watering.

1269
00:47:09,693 --> 00:47:10,761
TRYING NOT TO SMILE

1270
00:47:10,828 --> 00:47:12,396
-Try the next one right away.
-The next one.

1271
00:47:12,462 --> 00:47:14,531
<i>-He goes for the next one.</i>
<i>-Straight to the next one.</i>

1272
00:47:14,598 --> 00:47:16,366
What's this bowl?

1273
00:47:16,433 --> 00:47:19,236
I made a tartlet shell with bread,

1274
00:47:19,303 --> 00:47:21,839
-and on the inside, batter bits…
-You made a bowl with bread?

1275
00:47:21,905 --> 00:47:22,873
…to make it crispy.

1276
00:47:22,940 --> 00:47:25,843
-A bowl.
-"You made a bowl with bread?"

1277
00:47:25,909 --> 00:47:26,977
You might've noticed by now.

1278
00:47:27,544 --> 00:47:30,013
-It's a bowl.
-Soo has a homey way of talking.

1279
00:47:30,347 --> 00:47:31,348
GO SOO'S

1280
00:47:31,415 --> 00:47:33,650
HOMEY TALK

1281
00:47:34,618 --> 00:47:36,653
-It's made with…
-Oh!

1282
00:47:36,720 --> 00:47:38,655
-Mmm.
-I heard the crunch just now.

1283
00:47:38,722 --> 00:47:40,224
Yes, there was a crunch.

1284
00:47:41,358 --> 00:47:42,893
He's savoring the flavor.

1285
00:47:42,960 --> 00:47:45,462
SAVORING…

1286
00:47:46,029 --> 00:47:48,065
If anyone has 500-won coin,
can I borrow it?

1287
00:47:48,131 --> 00:47:51,568
-We're wondering what it's like.
-I'm dying to know.

1288
00:47:51,635 --> 00:47:53,303
Let me wire it to you.

1289
00:47:53,871 --> 00:47:55,639
YOU HAVE RECEIVED 500 WON!

1290
00:47:55,706 --> 00:47:58,175
It's our first time
paying the guest for the review.

1291
00:47:58,242 --> 00:48:00,577
First of all, it's delicious.

1292
00:48:00,644 --> 00:48:04,648
The first bite was meat,
followed by fish, right?

1293
00:48:04,715 --> 00:48:06,183
But why don't they feel

1294
00:48:06,250 --> 00:48:07,117
any different?

1295
00:48:07,684 --> 00:48:08,986
WHAT DO YOU MEAN BY THAT?

1296
00:48:09,052 --> 00:48:10,954
-Do you mean it in a positive way?
-Yes.

1297
00:48:11,021 --> 00:48:13,090
They weren't too different.

1298
00:48:13,156 --> 00:48:14,958
-So it's cohesive?
-Yes.

1299
00:48:15,025 --> 00:48:18,262
Did you use <i>yuja</i>?
I can taste that refreshing note.

1300
00:48:18,328 --> 00:48:20,731
<i>I mixed </i>yuja <i>with oriental dressing</i>

1301
00:48:20,797 --> 00:48:24,201
<i>to let it help refresh your mouth.</i>

1302
00:48:24,268 --> 00:48:27,271
My mouth is still watering a lot.
It's calling for the next bite.

1303
00:48:27,337 --> 00:48:28,939
The last bite

1304
00:48:29,006 --> 00:48:31,541
is made with shrimp and broccoli,
which are good for you.

1305
00:48:31,608 --> 00:48:33,810
But I tried making them rich and heavy.

1306
00:48:33,877 --> 00:48:36,313
I wanted you
to cycle 50 km after eating that.

1307
00:48:36,947 --> 00:48:38,515
But this one is the smallest.

1308
00:48:38,582 --> 00:48:40,684
It'll hit you the heaviest.

1309
00:48:40,751 --> 00:48:41,618
It must taste heavy.

1310
00:48:41,685 --> 00:48:43,787
It's the smallest,
yet it'll be the heaviest.

1311
00:48:43,854 --> 00:48:45,455
But it's made with broccoli.

1312
00:48:45,522 --> 00:48:48,525
-Yes, it's made with broccoli.
-Shrimp and broccoli.

1313
00:48:49,526 --> 00:48:51,628
It may be the heaviest bite
among the three.

1314
00:48:51,695 --> 00:48:53,931
I can hear the crunchy sound
of this one too.

1315
00:48:56,967 --> 00:48:58,568
He enjoys it with a serious face.

1316
00:48:58,635 --> 00:49:01,004
He's trying to stall for time
and take 1,500 won from me.

1317
00:49:01,571 --> 00:49:03,240
THIS MAKES HIM…

1318
00:49:03,807 --> 00:49:05,709
THE MASTER OF TEASING

1319
00:49:05,776 --> 00:49:07,544
Do you want to know?

1320
00:49:07,611 --> 00:49:09,947
I know what this tastes like.

1321
00:49:10,013 --> 00:49:11,081
It's like that old snack.

1322
00:49:12,449 --> 00:49:15,485
-Veggie crackers.
-Right, veggie crackers.

1323
00:49:15,552 --> 00:49:18,989
It tastes a lot like those crackers.

1324
00:49:19,056 --> 00:49:21,558
I see. Then it might be
a better idea to get those.

1325
00:49:22,125 --> 00:49:22,993
OFFENDED

1326
00:49:23,060 --> 00:49:24,594
It's like a stack of veggie crackers.

1327
00:49:24,661 --> 00:49:27,831
-But the filling is different.
-It is.

1328
00:49:27,898 --> 00:49:30,334
It has a totally different
nutritional value.

1329
00:49:30,400 --> 00:49:32,936
Very well.
Next, please try Chef Sung-jun's dish,

1330
00:49:33,003 --> 00:49:34,171
<i>Napoli MatPro</i>.

1331
00:49:34,237 --> 00:49:36,139
ARANCINI WITH FISH TARTAR SAUCE

1332
00:49:36,473 --> 00:49:39,042
DEEP-FRIED MEATBALL & EGGPLANT WITH CHEESE

1333
00:49:39,509 --> 00:49:41,411
CROUTON ICE CREAM

1334
00:49:42,179 --> 00:49:46,316
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S NAPOLI MATPRO

1335
00:49:46,383 --> 00:49:48,785
Chef Sung-jun's bites

1336
00:49:48,852 --> 00:49:51,955
-come in bigger sizes than Hyun-suk's.
-They're big.

1337
00:49:52,022 --> 00:49:55,225
Please cut it in half and try a piece.

1338
00:49:55,292 --> 00:49:56,960
But this is Go Soo's Bite Master.

1339
00:49:57,027 --> 00:49:59,196
Shouldn't he eat everything in one bite?

1340
00:49:59,262 --> 00:50:01,765
-He suddenly begins to attack.
-That's true.

1341
00:50:01,832 --> 00:50:03,533
-No way.
-He's right.

1342
00:50:03,600 --> 00:50:05,302
-He has a point.
-No way.

1343
00:50:05,369 --> 00:50:06,870
All he has to do is take one bite.

1344
00:50:06,937 --> 00:50:08,872
-Just eat one bite?
-Take one bite?

1345
00:50:08,939 --> 00:50:11,742
That's like making finger food this big
and taking only one bite.

1346
00:50:11,808 --> 00:50:13,377
A whole cake isn't considered finger food.

1347
00:50:13,443 --> 00:50:14,711
IT MAKES SENSE

1348
00:50:14,778 --> 00:50:16,313
He has a point.

1349
00:50:16,380 --> 00:50:18,482
Chef Hyun-suk points out
something important.

1350
00:50:18,548 --> 00:50:21,251
Food in Naples
tends to be bigger in portion.

1351
00:50:21,318 --> 00:50:23,086
People there are warm,
so the bread is big.

1352
00:50:23,153 --> 00:50:24,488
Are people here not warm?

1353
00:50:24,554 --> 00:50:26,723
Are we cold?

1354
00:50:26,790 --> 00:50:28,925
Italians have bigger mouths
compared to us.

1355
00:50:28,992 --> 00:50:31,128
Especially in the southern region.

1356
00:50:31,194 --> 00:50:33,196
-It's the Naples style.
-They're warmhearted.

1357
00:50:33,263 --> 00:50:36,366
It's a bit too big to eat it in a bite.

1358
00:50:36,433 --> 00:50:37,701
You can cut it.

1359
00:50:37,768 --> 00:50:39,870
He also served three different bites.

1360
00:50:39,936 --> 00:50:41,038
The first one.

1361
00:50:41,104 --> 00:50:42,539
The first one is a fish bite.

1362
00:50:42,606 --> 00:50:45,208
I topped it with halibut
and snapper tartar sauce,

1363
00:50:45,275 --> 00:50:47,744
seasoned with yogurt,
lemon juice, and olive oil.

1364
00:50:47,811 --> 00:50:49,146
Underneath, it's an arancini.

1365
00:50:49,212 --> 00:50:50,680
It's a simple bite.

1366
00:50:50,747 --> 00:50:52,382
It's like Italian sushi.

1367
00:50:52,449 --> 00:50:53,984
ONLY HALF A BITE

1368
00:50:54,051 --> 00:50:55,285
All right.

1369
00:50:55,852 --> 00:50:58,989
GOVID SAVORS THE FOOD

1370
00:50:59,756 --> 00:51:02,259
I also want my veins to pop out
when I eat something.

1371
00:51:02,325 --> 00:51:03,727
-It's never happened, right?
-Never.

1372
00:51:03,794 --> 00:51:04,861
Do you find that cool?

1373
00:51:04,928 --> 00:51:06,863
NICE VEINS

1374
00:51:07,297 --> 00:51:09,766
MISSING THE VEINS!

1375
00:51:09,833 --> 00:51:10,967
-He takes another bite.
-Hey!

1376
00:51:11,034 --> 00:51:12,502
QUIETLY GOES FOR THE REMAINING HALF

1377
00:51:12,569 --> 00:51:14,037
This means…

1378
00:51:14,104 --> 00:51:16,306
-It means it's good.
-It must be.

1379
00:51:17,441 --> 00:51:19,709
-He's making us very curious.
-He reminds me

1380
00:51:19,776 --> 00:51:21,378
of a Buddhist monk at a temple

1381
00:51:21,445 --> 00:51:25,182
who had gone on a week-long fast,

1382
00:51:25,248 --> 00:51:27,717
then finally breaking the fast.

1383
00:51:27,784 --> 00:51:29,753
He chews everything so carefully.

1384
00:51:29,820 --> 00:51:31,721
He'll make 3,000 won very soon.

1385
00:51:31,788 --> 00:51:33,690
GETTING READY TO PAY HIM

1386
00:51:33,757 --> 00:51:34,991
What's it like?

1387
00:51:35,058 --> 00:51:37,427
Unlike what I expected,
it's not too heavy.

1388
00:51:37,494 --> 00:51:38,795
Even though it's deep-fried?

1389
00:51:38,862 --> 00:51:40,430
-That's the point.
-Despite that.

1390
00:51:40,497 --> 00:51:43,767
Is it because I haven't had
anything deep-fried in a while?

1391
00:51:44,668 --> 00:51:45,569
It's very…

1392
00:51:46,403 --> 00:51:47,237
delicious.

1393
00:51:48,672 --> 00:51:50,907
Anything deep-fried tastes great
if it's been a while.

1394
00:51:50,974 --> 00:51:53,110
-It's been a while for me.
-It must be so good.

1395
00:51:53,176 --> 00:51:54,711
It's crunchy and good.

1396
00:51:54,778 --> 00:51:56,079
The second one…

1397
00:51:56,146 --> 00:51:57,914
It came with some tomato sauce.

1398
00:51:57,981 --> 00:52:01,618
The next one is eggplant with cheese
in the Naples style,

1399
00:52:01,685 --> 00:52:03,520
served with a meatball and tomato sauce.

1400
00:52:03,587 --> 00:52:06,089
Please mix everything with the sauce.

1401
00:52:06,156 --> 00:52:08,358
You don't have to eat it all in one go.
You can cut it up.

1402
00:52:08,425 --> 00:52:11,027
It's made with the dried eggplant
he uses to make tea.

1403
00:52:11,094 --> 00:52:14,030
-I used the dried eggplant for making tea.
-Right?

1404
00:52:14,097 --> 00:52:16,566
-The eggplant is deep-fried too.
-It should be good.

1405
00:52:16,633 --> 00:52:17,634
WHAT'S THE EGGPLANT LIKE?

1406
00:52:19,503 --> 00:52:20,704
DEEP GAZE

1407
00:52:21,271 --> 00:52:22,706
GOVID STARES AT SUNG-JUN

1408
00:52:22,772 --> 00:52:25,308
He didn't look at Hyun-suk like that.

1409
00:52:25,375 --> 00:52:26,543
What's going on?

1410
00:52:26,610 --> 00:52:28,345
He's staring right at Sung-jun.

1411
00:52:28,411 --> 00:52:30,213
That's the face of a guy
who hasn't had a fritter in a while.

1412
00:52:31,148 --> 00:52:32,382
I know that face.

1413
00:52:32,449 --> 00:52:34,451
-It must've been like two years.
-Right?

1414
00:52:34,518 --> 00:52:36,853
-He looks pleased.
-It's because of the grease.

1415
00:52:36,920 --> 00:52:38,421
Is he leaning towards Sung-jun's food?

1416
00:52:38,488 --> 00:52:40,223
-He likes deep-fried food.
-He does.

1417
00:52:40,290 --> 00:52:42,959
-How did he hold himself back?
-How did he resist?

1418
00:52:43,026 --> 00:52:44,661
He loves it so much.

1419
00:52:44,728 --> 00:52:47,264
-Now, the meatball.
-It's not bite-sized, but two-bite-sized.

1420
00:52:47,330 --> 00:52:50,534
-The meatball, right?
-The first one I had tasted like eggplant.

1421
00:52:50,600 --> 00:52:52,435
Yes, it's deep-fried eggplant.

1422
00:52:52,502 --> 00:52:55,739
<i>That's a meatball made with beef</i>
<i>and bread soaked in milk.</i>

1423
00:52:56,306 --> 00:52:57,507
YUM

1424
00:52:57,941 --> 00:52:59,709
-Mmm.
-Mmm?

1425
00:52:59,776 --> 00:53:00,710
The meatball.

1426
00:53:00,777 --> 00:53:02,746
Bread soaked in milk.
Is that Italian style?

1427
00:53:02,812 --> 00:53:06,116
-It is. Naples style.
-It's what people in Naples do.

1428
00:53:06,183 --> 00:53:07,617
That's why it'll feel tender.

1429
00:53:07,684 --> 00:53:08,752
-Yes.
-Yes?

1430
00:53:08,818 --> 00:53:10,187
It doesn't taste like milk.

1431
00:53:10,253 --> 00:53:12,389
The milk just makes it tender.

1432
00:53:12,455 --> 00:53:15,425
-Beef alone can be too dry.
-He's talking a lot. He must be nervous.

1433
00:53:15,492 --> 00:53:16,793
He's talking a lot today.

1434
00:53:16,860 --> 00:53:18,295
Has he always been so talkative?

1435
00:53:18,361 --> 00:53:19,663
He feels like he has to drive it in.

1436
00:53:19,729 --> 00:53:20,764
MORE TALKATIVE WHEN IN TROUBLE

1437
00:53:20,830 --> 00:53:23,099
We're supposed to hear it from the guest,

1438
00:53:23,166 --> 00:53:25,402
but he's the one who's talking.

1439
00:53:25,468 --> 00:53:27,404
All Soo does is, "Yes!"

1440
00:53:27,470 --> 00:53:29,439
"Yes, that's right!"

1441
00:53:29,506 --> 00:53:31,308
He's trying to sway him.

1442
00:53:31,374 --> 00:53:33,843
But the meatball

1443
00:53:33,910 --> 00:53:37,180
doesn't taste anything like
what you'd imagine.

1444
00:53:37,247 --> 00:53:39,583
It looked rather dry.

1445
00:53:40,684 --> 00:53:42,586
-It's not.
-It's not?

1446
00:53:42,652 --> 00:53:44,254
-Is it tender?
-It is.

1447
00:53:44,321 --> 00:53:48,325
It's true that Italian meatballs
are made with soaked bread.

1448
00:53:48,391 --> 00:53:51,061
Perhaps that's why.

1449
00:53:51,127 --> 00:53:54,431
-I knew you'd know.
-It really was authentic Italian.

1450
00:53:54,497 --> 00:53:58,068
Everyone here also watched him make this.

1451
00:53:58,702 --> 00:53:59,970
You must be dying to know.

1452
00:54:00,036 --> 00:54:01,238
PLAYING HIS GAME AGAIN

1453
00:54:01,304 --> 00:54:03,139
That's why we keep asking you.

1454
00:54:03,206 --> 00:54:05,275
Others can't help but talk
when they try these.

1455
00:54:05,342 --> 00:54:06,943
But he's having fun with this.

1456
00:54:07,010 --> 00:54:09,179
I get it. Among all of us,
including our viewers,

1457
00:54:09,246 --> 00:54:13,883
-this is something that only he knows.
-Only he knows.

1458
00:54:13,950 --> 00:54:16,052
-Do you want to know?
-Yes, very much.

1459
00:54:16,119 --> 00:54:17,621
Yes, we do.

1460
00:54:19,389 --> 00:54:22,259
You seem excited
after eating it only by yourself.

1461
00:54:22,325 --> 00:54:24,327
He's a different breed.

1462
00:54:24,394 --> 00:54:26,162
The second one tasted like eggplant

1463
00:54:26,229 --> 00:54:28,999
and the next one tasted like a meatball.

1464
00:54:29,065 --> 00:54:29,933
PROUD

1465
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:34,471
After all, he used dried eggplant pieces.
How were they different?

1466
00:54:34,537 --> 00:54:36,172
It tasted like deep-fried

1467
00:54:36,239 --> 00:54:37,207
dried eggplant.

1468
00:54:37,841 --> 00:54:39,776
THE TASTE REVIEW OF A MASTER

1469
00:54:39,843 --> 00:54:42,145
We all saw him make it too.

1470
00:54:42,212 --> 00:54:45,582
I haven't tried it, so I can't imagine it.

1471
00:54:45,649 --> 00:54:48,752
It's the kind of review
that's hard to refute.

1472
00:54:48,818 --> 00:54:50,186
It's technically correct.

1473
00:54:50,253 --> 00:54:53,556
-What's the third one?
-That's the dessert.

1474
00:54:53,623 --> 00:54:56,893
I put together bread
toasted in the oven with butter,

1475
00:54:56,960 --> 00:54:58,895
with chestnut jam, yogurt, and ice cream.

1476
00:54:58,962 --> 00:55:01,264
-That's his favorite ice cream.
-The ice cream that he loves.

1477
00:55:01,331 --> 00:55:03,533
Sung-jun tries to capture his heart.

1478
00:55:03,600 --> 00:55:05,835
-He has a sweet tooth.
-I had to do it.

1479
00:55:06,636 --> 00:55:08,038
OM NOM NOM

1480
00:55:10,607 --> 00:55:11,841
It looks good.

1481
00:55:11,908 --> 00:55:13,443
I think he'll say this again.

1482
00:55:13,510 --> 00:55:14,678
"It's sweet."

1483
00:55:14,744 --> 00:55:15,578
"And cool."

1484
00:55:15,645 --> 00:55:17,847
"It tastes like bread
soaked in ice cream."

1485
00:55:19,349 --> 00:55:20,283
His facial expression

1486
00:55:20,350 --> 00:55:22,886
is as serious as a judge
on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

1487
00:55:22,952 --> 00:55:26,256
What does it remind you of?
Can you tell us so we can understand?

1488
00:55:26,323 --> 00:55:29,492
I often toast some bread
and have it with Greek yogurt,

1489
00:55:29,559 --> 00:55:31,795
but it's my first time mixing it up,

1490
00:55:31,861 --> 00:55:33,430
and it's sweet and delicious.

1491
00:55:33,997 --> 00:55:35,065
THE END

1492
00:55:35,632 --> 00:55:36,633
HE SAID IT SO SERIOUSLY…

1493
00:55:36,700 --> 00:55:38,902
-"Sweet and delicious."
-He's not wrong.

1494
00:55:38,968 --> 00:55:42,572
I told you that he'd say,
"It's sweet, cold, and delicious."

1495
00:55:42,639 --> 00:55:44,107
It's deliciously sweet.

1496
00:55:44,174 --> 00:55:46,543
There is one thing I'm disappointed about.

1497
00:55:46,609 --> 00:55:48,411
-You're disappointed?
-Disappointed?

1498
00:55:48,978 --> 00:55:49,813
HUH?

1499
00:55:50,380 --> 00:55:51,314
The filefish.

1500
00:55:51,381 --> 00:55:53,016
Oh! The burnt filefish!

1501
00:55:53,083 --> 00:55:56,219
-You should've saved it.
-I thought he'd let it pass.

1502
00:55:56,286 --> 00:55:58,254
-I was staying quiet about it.
-What would that have been like?

1503
00:55:58,321 --> 00:56:00,023
As I tried it,

1504
00:56:00,090 --> 00:56:01,991
I found myself wondering,

1505
00:56:02,058 --> 00:56:03,526
"Is it the filefish that's missing?"

1506
00:56:04,594 --> 00:56:06,830
-You lost three filefish fillets.
-The taste of missing filefish.

1507
00:56:06,896 --> 00:56:09,399
-Please apologize.
-Apologize for wasting three pieces.

1508
00:56:09,466 --> 00:56:11,401
APOLOGIZE TO SOO!

1509
00:56:11,468 --> 00:56:12,969
-What a waste.
-Right?

1510
00:56:13,036 --> 00:56:14,804
A HUGE APOLOGY

1511
00:56:14,871 --> 00:56:17,307
Maybe it's like green onion oil.
He could've made filefish oil?

1512
00:56:17,874 --> 00:56:21,044
THE GUY WHO TAKES IT A STEP FURTHER

1513
00:56:21,111 --> 00:56:23,713
Will the filefish have an impact
on the final decision?

1514
00:56:23,780 --> 00:56:25,582
It's now time to decide.

1515
00:56:25,648 --> 00:56:26,683
Do I have to choose?

1516
00:56:26,750 --> 00:56:29,018
You must. You have to.

1517
00:56:29,085 --> 00:56:32,322
No one else here has tried it
except for you.

1518
00:56:32,389 --> 00:56:35,859
He finishes the leftover dessert.

1519
00:56:35,925 --> 00:56:38,061
<i>Press one to choose Sung-jun</i>

1520
00:56:38,128 --> 00:56:40,130
<i>and two to pick Hyun-suk.</i>

1521
00:56:40,196 --> 00:56:43,233
Please make your decision
and press the button!

1522
00:56:43,299 --> 00:56:45,702
After he pushes it,
he'll go, "Do you want to know?"

1523
00:56:47,237 --> 00:56:48,805
This time, I'll give you 1,000 won.

1524
00:56:49,539 --> 00:56:51,274
I can even pay 10,000 won.

1525
00:56:51,341 --> 00:56:53,476
-Have you decided? He pressed it.
-Yes.

1526
00:56:53,543 --> 00:56:55,078
Let's find out who he chose.

1527
00:56:55,145 --> 00:56:56,079
Show us!

1528
00:56:57,213 --> 00:56:59,482
Who has become Go Soo's Bite Master?

1529
00:56:59,549 --> 00:57:02,485
Will Hyun-suk
win against Sung-jun yet again?

1530
00:57:02,552 --> 00:57:07,190
Or will Sung-jun defeat Hyun-suk
for the very first time?

1531
00:57:07,257 --> 00:57:09,392
Let's find out the result!

1532
00:57:09,459 --> 00:57:10,660
Who won?

1533
00:57:11,227 --> 00:57:12,929
Who's the winner?

1534
00:57:12,996 --> 00:57:15,031
KWON SUNG-JUN WINS

1535
00:57:15,432 --> 00:57:17,066
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S NAPOLI MATPRO WINS

1536
00:57:17,133 --> 00:57:18,501
Sung-jun!

1537
00:57:19,068 --> 00:57:20,804
A TUBBY CELEBRATION

1538
00:57:20,870 --> 00:57:23,339
Sung-jun wins against Hyun-suk
for the very first time!

1539
00:57:23,406 --> 00:57:25,975
-He caught a big fish!
-He did!

1540
00:57:26,042 --> 00:57:28,278
This has never happened
on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> before.

1541
00:57:28,344 --> 00:57:31,114
-Sung-jun had lost three previous rounds…
-It's unpredictable.

1542
00:57:31,181 --> 00:57:33,750
…then finally won against Chef Hyun-suk.

1543
00:57:33,817 --> 00:57:39,322
He did a great job
at fulfilling the need that I had.

1544
00:57:39,389 --> 00:57:40,890
I've been craving
something deep-fried badly.

1545
00:57:40,957 --> 00:57:43,126
AND HE NEVER TOLD ANYONE ABOUT IT

1546
00:57:43,193 --> 00:57:46,529
You should've deep-fried something!

1547
00:57:46,596 --> 00:57:48,965
I had been craving something deep-fried,

1548
00:57:49,032 --> 00:57:52,068
but when I tried his food,
they weren't too heavy either.

1549
00:57:52,135 --> 00:57:54,337
-You're right.
-But despite that,

1550
00:57:54,404 --> 00:57:58,274
I also enjoyed Chef Hyun-suk's dish a lot.

1551
00:57:58,908 --> 00:58:00,143
I ENJOYED IT A LOT

1552
00:58:00,210 --> 00:58:01,177
Honestly, I did.

1553
00:58:01,244 --> 00:58:03,580
You lost
because you didn't deep-fry anything.

1554
00:58:03,646 --> 00:58:05,748
He just wanted something greasy.

1555
00:58:05,815 --> 00:58:09,652
Why didn't you ask for Deep-Fry Master
instead of Bite Master?

1556
00:58:09,719 --> 00:58:11,688
It wasn't a miss, but a nice try.

1557
00:58:11,754 --> 00:58:14,791
He finally beat Chef Hyun-suk
after four tries…

1558
00:58:14,858 --> 00:58:17,393
-Nice.
-…and he also gets his second star.

1559
00:58:17,460 --> 00:58:19,963
Sung-jun takes his victory
after guessing the exact need

1560
00:58:20,029 --> 00:58:21,731
Go Soo had been looking for!

1561
00:58:21,798 --> 00:58:23,867
-Great round.
-Please put the star on him, Soo.

1562
00:58:23,933 --> 00:58:27,103
-He defeats Hyun-suk.
-Congratulations, Sung-jun.

1563
00:58:27,170 --> 00:58:29,239
-The Bite Master.
-Thank you for the dish.

1564
00:58:31,341 --> 00:58:35,011
<i>This is the second cook-off</i>
<i>with ingredients from Soo's fridge.</i>

1565
00:58:35,078 --> 00:58:38,014
The master pasta maker, Chef Sam Kim,

1566
00:58:38,081 --> 00:58:42,685
versus the master pasta eater,
Chef Yoon Nam-no.

1567
00:58:42,752 --> 00:58:43,887
Surprisingly,

1568
00:58:43,953 --> 00:58:45,855
this is their first cook-off.

1569
00:58:45,922 --> 00:58:48,925
-Really?
-It's their first time competing.

1570
00:58:48,992 --> 00:58:51,427
-The first time in history?
-Yes.

1571
00:58:51,494 --> 00:58:54,130
Which one of them
will seize their chance to victory?

1572
00:58:54,197 --> 00:58:56,032
-We received a tip.
-What is it?

1573
00:58:56,099 --> 00:58:57,467
-It's from Chef Nam-no.
-Yes?

1574
00:58:57,534 --> 00:58:59,602
"I'd rather deal with Sam than Poong."

1575
00:59:00,403 --> 00:59:01,971
REALLY NOW?

1576
00:59:03,506 --> 00:59:06,209
-Yes, he's never won against Poong.
-That's true.

1577
00:59:06,276 --> 00:59:07,143
The thing is,

1578
00:59:07,210 --> 00:59:09,379
I've been running from Poong.

1579
00:59:10,046 --> 00:59:11,714
-To avoid fighting him.
-Intentionally?

1580
00:59:11,781 --> 00:59:13,983
It's our first battle,
so there's no history.

1581
00:59:14,551 --> 00:59:17,453
So I chose him
because I thought I'd be able to face him

1582
00:59:17,520 --> 00:59:19,756
-with some peace of mind.
-I see.

1583
00:59:19,822 --> 00:59:22,926
But Chef Sam's well-thought-out plan

1584
00:59:22,992 --> 00:59:25,695
-has been noticed by our production crew.
-What is it?

1585
00:59:25,762 --> 00:59:27,330
In order to win against Nam-no,

1586
00:59:27,397 --> 00:59:29,933
he stuck around right next to Poong

1587
00:59:29,999 --> 00:59:32,569
and begged him for tips.

1588
00:59:33,136 --> 00:59:34,404
Is this true?

1589
00:59:34,470 --> 00:59:38,341
-Poong is invincible against Nam-no.
-Invincible.

1590
00:59:38,408 --> 00:59:40,977
So I did ask him for tips to win.

1591
00:59:41,044 --> 00:59:42,879
The thing with Chef Nam-no is this.

1592
00:59:42,946 --> 00:59:44,881
-He's quite mentally fragile…
-Mentally fragile.

1593
00:59:44,948 --> 00:59:47,750
…and he tends to become anxious.

1594
00:59:47,817 --> 00:59:50,420
Also, his ears are always open.

1595
00:59:50,486 --> 00:59:52,021
He cooks as he listens to everything.

1596
00:59:52,622 --> 00:59:54,157
EVEN THE SLIGHTEST ATTEMPT TO BOTHER HIM

1597
00:59:54,724 --> 00:59:56,826
MAKES HIM ANXIOUS

1598
00:59:56,893 --> 00:59:59,329
-Please don't talk to me.
-He's quite…

1599
00:59:59,395 --> 01:00:01,464
-He can't cook when it's noisy.
-That's right.

1600
01:00:01,531 --> 01:00:04,367
-I told him to get in his head.
-Shake him up in his head.

1601
01:00:04,434 --> 01:00:05,802
Can you do that?

1602
01:00:05,868 --> 01:00:06,703
CAN THE SAINT DO IT?

1603
01:00:06,769 --> 01:00:08,705
-It's not my style.
-No, right?

1604
01:00:08,771 --> 01:00:11,574
Poong gave him a helpful tip…

1605
01:00:11,641 --> 01:00:14,110
-He's on the quiet side too.
-…but it's hard for him to do.

1606
01:00:14,177 --> 01:00:18,047
-But Sam is a master of pasta, isn't he?
-He is.

1607
01:00:18,114 --> 01:00:20,650
Are you confident about
facing the pasta master with noodles?

1608
01:00:20,717 --> 01:00:22,852
Among the noodle dishes made here,

1609
01:00:22,919 --> 01:00:26,389
Chef Sam's tuna pasta
was the best one I've had.

1610
01:00:26,456 --> 01:00:28,124
Among the dishes you've had here?

1611
01:00:28,191 --> 01:00:30,927
So I felt a lot of burden about the idea
of making pasta against him,

1612
01:00:30,994 --> 01:00:34,430
-so I'll make my own noodle dish.
-I see.

1613
01:00:34,497 --> 01:00:37,233
-An intelligent approach.
-That's right.

1614
01:00:37,300 --> 01:00:40,970
Though it's hard to believe that
Nam-no has devised an intelligent plan.

1615
01:00:42,271 --> 01:00:44,540
What happened to your reputation?

1616
01:00:44,607 --> 01:00:47,377
-This time, you might catch Samphobia.
-I can't allow that.

1617
01:00:47,443 --> 01:00:48,711
The first cook-off is important.

1618
01:00:49,612 --> 01:00:51,414
CHEF SAM'S INGREDIENTS:
PASTA, LA-STYLE GALBI, TOMATO SALSA

1619
01:00:51,481 --> 01:00:53,716
CHERRY TOMATO, OLIVE OIL, LEMON JUICE,
BEAN SPROUTS, BONE BROTH, AND MORE

1620
01:00:53,783 --> 01:00:56,352
The dish I'm making today is

1621
01:00:57,220 --> 01:00:58,655
GoVid Pasta.

1622
01:00:58,721 --> 01:01:00,590
-GoVid Pasta.
-GoVid Pasta.

1623
01:01:01,157 --> 01:01:03,860
-GoVid Pasta.
-A handsome pasta.

1624
01:01:03,926 --> 01:01:05,528
How will you make it?

1625
01:01:05,595 --> 01:01:07,997
I'll use the pasta noodles,

1626
01:01:08,064 --> 01:01:10,233
but I'll mix it with <i>chogochujang</i>,
gochujang with vinegar.

1627
01:01:10,299 --> 01:01:12,101
Sam, that's…

1628
01:01:12,168 --> 01:01:13,603
I never would've imagined that.

1629
01:01:13,670 --> 01:01:18,107
Actually, GoVid stands
for gochujang vital dish.

1630
01:01:18,174 --> 01:01:19,709
-That's good.
-That was why.

1631
01:01:19,776 --> 01:01:22,011
WAIT, I KNOW THIS RECIPE

1632
01:01:22,078 --> 01:01:23,980
Poong once made a pasta dish

1633
01:01:24,047 --> 01:01:27,083
by mixing <i>chogochujang </i>and tomato sauce.

1634
01:01:27,150 --> 01:01:29,519
You can use angel hair

1635
01:01:29,585 --> 01:01:33,489
and mix <i>chogochujang</i>
and tomato pasta sauce.

1636
01:01:33,556 --> 01:01:36,125
It's delicious with a drip of sesame oil.

1637
01:01:36,192 --> 01:01:38,261
<i>-It's amazing.</i>
<i>-Really?</i>

1638
01:01:38,327 --> 01:01:39,395
Webtoon Artist Poong.

1639
01:01:39,462 --> 01:01:41,497
I really love this recipe.

1640
01:01:41,564 --> 01:01:42,799
It's famous.

1641
01:01:42,865 --> 01:01:45,968
He's going to use my recipe? Mine?

1642
01:01:46,035 --> 01:01:50,073
I want to make a pasta
that has intense flavors.

1643
01:01:50,139 --> 01:01:52,008
-I see.
-So that's what I'm making.

1644
01:01:52,075 --> 01:01:54,043
Next, I saw some LA-style <i>galbi</i>,

1645
01:01:54,110 --> 01:01:56,579
so I'll grill it on a skewer

1646
01:01:56,646 --> 01:01:58,748
and let you eat the spicy noodles

1647
01:01:58,815 --> 01:02:00,349
with a bite of sweet meat.

1648
01:02:00,416 --> 01:02:02,518
Lastly, I saw some bone broth,

1649
01:02:02,585 --> 01:02:06,055
and you said you liked <i>naengmyeon</i>,
so I'll make a cold soup you can drink.

1650
01:02:06,122 --> 01:02:09,225
-A total of three dishes.
-Three?

1651
01:02:09,292 --> 01:02:11,794
-That's not his usual style.
-I know.

1652
01:02:11,861 --> 01:02:13,963
You got the inspiration from Poong, right?

1653
01:02:14,030 --> 01:02:16,432
It came 100% from him.

1654
01:02:16,499 --> 01:02:20,036
-Will you make it fancy?
-I'll add some of my ideas

1655
01:02:20,103 --> 01:02:22,371
-and upgrade it a little.
-It'll be upgraded

1656
01:02:22,438 --> 01:02:25,441
by the hands of the pasta master.

1657
01:02:26,375 --> 01:02:28,244
CHEF NAM-NO'S INGREDIENTS: THIN NOODLES,
SHRIMP, RAW HALIBUT AND SNAPPER

1658
01:02:28,311 --> 01:02:30,446
BELL PEPPER, CHERRY TOMATO, YUJA CHEONG,
LEMON JUICE, APPLE JUICE, FILEFISH FILLET

1659
01:02:30,513 --> 01:02:32,048
The name of my dish is

1660
01:02:32,782 --> 01:02:34,817
You're Go Soo, I'm Guksu.

1661
01:02:34,884 --> 01:02:35,852
PFFT

1662
01:02:36,352 --> 01:02:37,920
You're Go Soo, I'm Guksu.

1663
01:02:37,987 --> 01:02:41,023
SUCH A CATCHY NAME

1664
01:02:41,090 --> 01:02:44,193
Are you making <i>guksu</i>,
Korean-style noodles?

1665
01:02:44,260 --> 01:02:46,329
I'll use thin wheat noodles,

1666
01:02:46,395 --> 01:02:48,431
and I'm also making <i>chogochujang</i> today.

1667
01:02:48,998 --> 01:02:49,999
-Wait.
-However,

1668
01:02:50,066 --> 01:02:52,335
you probably have never had
<i>chogochujang</i> like this.

1669
01:02:52,401 --> 01:02:54,637
-I'm using <i>yuja</i>.
-<i>Yuja chogochujang</i>?

1670
01:02:54,704 --> 01:02:57,140
-You're using <i>yuja</i>?
-Yes, it's <i>yuja chogochujang</i>.

1671
01:02:57,206 --> 01:03:00,042
And I'll use cherry tomatoes
and bell peppers

1672
01:03:00,109 --> 01:03:02,378
to make some broth

1673
01:03:02,445 --> 01:03:04,814
-and serve it on the side.
-Broth?

1674
01:03:04,881 --> 01:03:07,650
-Also, the filefish fillets.
-Filefish fillets?

1675
01:03:07,717 --> 01:03:09,685
The one that Chef Sung-jun failed.

1676
01:03:09,752 --> 01:03:11,320
-He failed.
-Deep-fried filefish?

1677
01:03:11,387 --> 01:03:14,757
I'll try to give them new life.

1678
01:03:14,824 --> 01:03:17,260
-If you fail too, it's over.
-He'll do what Sung-jun can't.

1679
01:03:17,326 --> 01:03:20,329
-Yes.
-I hope your plan goes well.

1680
01:03:20,396 --> 01:03:22,865
His dish is called
You're Go Soo, I'm <i>Guksu</i>.

1681
01:03:22,932 --> 01:03:24,167
That was cute.

1682
01:03:24,233 --> 01:03:26,669
Will Nam-no
finally climb out of last place?

1683
01:03:26,736 --> 01:03:29,639
Let us begin the 15-minute cook-off.

1684
01:03:29,705 --> 01:03:31,240
You have to finish first.

1685
01:03:31,307 --> 01:03:35,378
He's willing to channel Kim Poong today
to destroy Nam-no.

1686
01:03:35,444 --> 01:03:36,813
Chef Poong Kim.

1687
01:03:36,879 --> 01:03:38,014
CHEF SAM KIM
AKA POONG KIM

1688
01:03:38,080 --> 01:03:42,285
But this guy is here to boil some noodles
and make Sam's blood boil too.

1689
01:03:42,351 --> 01:03:44,487
Noodle Nam-no is up for the battle.

1690
01:03:44,554 --> 01:03:48,057
This is their first battle on the show.
Who'll rise as the winner?

1691
01:03:48,124 --> 01:03:50,359
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1692
01:03:52,862 --> 01:03:54,397
WHAT'S SAM DOING?

1693
01:03:54,463 --> 01:03:56,499
STARTING OFF AGGRESSIVELY!

1694
01:03:57,900 --> 01:04:00,937
-This is their first battle.
-Pasta first.

1695
01:04:01,003 --> 01:04:04,006
They haven't even faced each other
on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

1696
01:04:04,073 --> 01:04:05,408
It's their first cook-off.

1697
01:04:05,474 --> 01:04:07,710
-What's that machine?
-I think he'll juice those.

1698
01:04:07,777 --> 01:04:08,611
-A juicer.
-A juicer?

1699
01:04:08,678 --> 01:04:10,446
-He'll juice the bell peppers?
-And tomatoes.

1700
01:04:10,513 --> 01:04:13,683
-And tomatoes? I see.
-And bell peppers too.

1701
01:04:13,749 --> 01:04:15,251
-There's the juice.
-There it is.

1702
01:04:15,318 --> 01:04:17,353
-He's using a juicer.
-It'll taste delicious.

1703
01:04:17,420 --> 01:04:18,688
-It works well.
-Yes.

1704
01:04:18,754 --> 01:04:21,591
-It looks like gazpacho.
-It does.

1705
01:04:21,657 --> 01:04:22,525
KIM POONG'S RECIPE

1706
01:04:22,592 --> 01:04:24,126
MEETS SAM KIM'S SKILLS!

1707
01:04:24,193 --> 01:04:25,661
-Green onion?
-Green onion.

1708
01:04:25,728 --> 01:04:28,164
He threw the pasta in rather early.

1709
01:04:28,231 --> 01:04:31,400
He's making cold noodles,
so it's okay to make it early on.

1710
01:04:31,467 --> 01:04:32,602
-Since he'll cool them?
-Yes.

1711
01:04:32,668 --> 01:04:34,804
-Bean sprouts?
-Bean sprouts.

1712
01:04:34,871 --> 01:04:37,039
Okay. That'll add a nice texture.

1713
01:04:37,106 --> 01:04:38,875
He boils bean sprouts too.

1714
01:04:38,941 --> 01:04:40,009
<i>Yuja cheong</i>, the preserves.

1715
01:04:40,076 --> 01:04:41,878
-<i>Yuja</i>.
-<i>Yuja cheong</i> and garlic.

1716
01:04:41,944 --> 01:04:44,947
-Chef Nam-no makes <i>yuja chogochujang</i>.
-Yes.

1717
01:04:45,014 --> 01:04:47,350
Yes, it's a new kind
of <i>chogochujang </i>with <i>yuja</i>

1718
01:04:47,416 --> 01:04:48,751
that will taste refreshing.

1719
01:04:48,818 --> 01:04:50,519
-It might be too sour.
-Will it taste good?

1720
01:04:50,586 --> 01:04:53,656
I've had <i>chogochujang</i> with green plum,
but never with <i>yuja</i>.

1721
01:04:53,723 --> 01:04:55,057
This is a first.

1722
01:04:55,124 --> 01:04:57,526
What's that sauce for?

1723
01:04:57,593 --> 01:04:59,095
-Me?
-What you're making now.

1724
01:04:59,161 --> 01:04:59,996
Oh.

1725
01:05:00,796 --> 01:05:02,164
-One second.
-"One second."

1726
01:05:02,231 --> 01:05:03,466
He said it was for the noodles.

1727
01:05:03,532 --> 01:05:05,167
-He got distracted.
-He's shaken.

1728
01:05:05,234 --> 01:05:07,136
It's okay. You don't have to answer.

1729
01:05:07,203 --> 01:05:09,105
-Don't distract him.
-I shouldn't.

1730
01:05:09,672 --> 01:05:11,674
Can you give me five minutes? One moment.

1731
01:05:11,741 --> 01:05:13,509
Chef Nam-no!

1732
01:05:13,576 --> 01:05:14,610
Chef Nam-no?

1733
01:05:14,677 --> 01:05:15,645
Chef Yoon!

1734
01:05:15,711 --> 01:05:16,545
Yes?

1735
01:05:17,280 --> 01:05:18,581
Just wanted to say your name.

1736
01:05:19,882 --> 01:05:20,716
Just wanted to say your name.

1737
01:05:20,783 --> 01:05:21,984
GIGGLE

1738
01:05:22,051 --> 01:05:24,186
Stop bothering him.

1739
01:05:24,253 --> 01:05:26,656
That apron is starting to choke him again.

1740
01:05:27,423 --> 01:05:29,058
It keeps choking him.

1741
01:05:29,659 --> 01:05:30,493
SUGAR

1742
01:05:30,826 --> 01:05:33,029
-What did he just add?
-Lemon juice and what?

1743
01:05:33,095 --> 01:05:34,730
-The bone broth?
-It's the bone broth.

1744
01:05:34,797 --> 01:05:36,565
-Bone broth.
-<i>Naengmyeon</i> broth.

1745
01:05:36,632 --> 01:05:38,768
You have to add vinegar to the bone broth.

1746
01:05:38,834 --> 01:05:41,037
What's the vinegar for?

1747
01:05:41,103 --> 01:05:43,806
He mixed bone broth
with lemon juice, vinegar, and salt.

1748
01:05:43,873 --> 01:05:45,408
Into the bone broth?

1749
01:05:45,474 --> 01:05:48,277
-It'll turn into <i>naengmyeon</i> broth.
-Like Pyongyang <i>naengmyeon </i>broth.

1750
01:05:48,344 --> 01:05:49,378
COOLING IN A BOWL OF ICE!

1751
01:05:49,445 --> 01:05:52,581
-It'll become Pyongyang <i>naengmyeon </i>broth.
-It will.

1752
01:05:52,648 --> 01:05:54,083
CHERRY TOMATOES

1753
01:05:54,317 --> 01:05:55,751
BELL PEPPER

1754
01:05:56,018 --> 01:05:57,420
GREEN ONION

1755
01:05:57,787 --> 01:06:00,456
4. ADD CHERRY TOMATOES, BELL PEPPERS,
AND GREEN ONION INTO THE BONE BROTH

1756
01:06:00,523 --> 01:06:03,059
-Gochujang.
-Gochujang.

1757
01:06:03,125 --> 01:06:04,193
-Sugar.
-Sugar.

1758
01:06:04,260 --> 01:06:07,063
-Cooking wine.
-Excellent. You need cooking wine.

1759
01:06:07,129 --> 01:06:08,331
Vinegar.

1760
01:06:08,397 --> 01:06:09,765
Garlic.

1761
01:06:09,832 --> 01:06:11,500
He added tomato salsa.

1762
01:06:11,567 --> 01:06:13,469
Sesame oil.

1763
01:06:13,536 --> 01:06:14,870
Okay. That smells good.

1764
01:06:14,937 --> 01:06:16,839
-Does it?
-Yes, it smells perfect.

1765
01:06:16,906 --> 01:06:20,343
He's done making
the tomato <i>chogochujang </i>sauce.

1766
01:06:20,409 --> 01:06:21,978
-Really?
-He's already done?

1767
01:06:22,945 --> 01:06:24,914
-That's Sam.
-The sauce is quite simple.

1768
01:06:24,981 --> 01:06:28,918
-Your recipes aren't so difficult.
-Not at all. They're so easy.

1769
01:06:28,985 --> 01:06:30,953
-Even easier for the chefs.
-Yes.

1770
01:06:31,654 --> 01:06:33,923
-He's deep-frying the filefish.
-The fried filefish.

1771
01:06:33,990 --> 01:06:35,958
The filefish.

1772
01:06:36,025 --> 01:06:38,594
Huh? The oil isn't hot enough.

1773
01:06:38,661 --> 01:06:39,862
It's an emergency.

1774
01:06:40,429 --> 01:06:42,164
WHY DOES HE NEED MORE COOKING OIL?

1775
01:06:42,231 --> 01:06:43,332
Or is it too hot?

1776
01:06:43,399 --> 01:06:45,901
The oil must've been too hot
for him to deep-fry the fish.

1777
01:06:45,968 --> 01:06:47,403
He quickly pulled it back out.

1778
01:06:47,470 --> 01:06:50,773
-You ruined your fish because of that.
-Right.

1779
01:06:50,840 --> 01:06:52,908
He soaked the fillets in water first.

1780
01:06:52,975 --> 01:06:54,744
-Is he coating it with frying powder?
-Yes.

1781
01:06:54,810 --> 01:06:57,480
-Starch.
-You're coating it with starch?

1782
01:06:57,546 --> 01:06:59,615
But Sung-jun threw them in as is.

1783
01:06:59,682 --> 01:07:01,984
-They went straight in.
-I didn't even soak them.

1784
01:07:02,051 --> 01:07:03,686
That was why he failed.

1785
01:07:03,753 --> 01:07:06,655
He soaked the fillets, coated them
with starch, and then began to fry.

1786
01:07:06,722 --> 01:07:09,592
If the fried filefish turns out nicely,
it might impress Soo.

1787
01:07:10,659 --> 01:07:12,762
WHAT'S THAT?

1788
01:07:12,828 --> 01:07:14,897
-He's using a broccoli stem.
-That's really good.

1789
01:07:14,964 --> 01:07:16,799
-The stem?
-Yes.

1790
01:07:16,866 --> 01:07:19,635
-He's julienning it.
-It looks like noodles.

1791
01:07:19,702 --> 01:07:21,237
It'll add a nice texture.

1792
01:07:21,303 --> 01:07:24,874
-It's crunchy.
-It is. And it's highly nutritious too.

1793
01:07:24,940 --> 01:07:26,242
-I see.
-You're right.

1794
01:07:26,308 --> 01:07:29,912
Poong is in charge of commenting,
while Sam only agrees.

1795
01:07:29,979 --> 01:07:30,880
HOW DID THAT HAPPEN?

1796
01:07:31,447 --> 01:07:33,983
6. JULIENNE A BROCCOLI STEM AND BOIL

1797
01:07:35,184 --> 01:07:37,219
What are you making, Nam-no?

1798
01:07:38,387 --> 01:07:41,190
-Nam-no, what…
-Bell peppers and tomato juice.

1799
01:07:41,257 --> 01:07:43,859
He added sugar and vinegar into the juice.

1800
01:07:43,926 --> 01:07:45,194
No, lemon juice.

1801
01:07:45,261 --> 01:07:48,364
-Is that juice for the broth?
-It's the broth served on the side.

1802
01:07:48,431 --> 01:07:51,100
It's like the side broth you get
with <i>naengmyeon</i>.

1803
01:07:51,167 --> 01:07:53,035
-He can pour it in later.
-To pour it in.

1804
01:07:53,102 --> 01:07:54,670
Did you add crushed garlic?

1805
01:07:54,737 --> 01:07:57,273
-He didn't.
-Add some. That'll be more delicious.

1806
01:07:57,339 --> 01:08:01,811
Poong is sitting here
making suggestions to both sides.

1807
01:08:01,877 --> 01:08:03,746
He's coaching both of them.

1808
01:08:03,813 --> 01:08:05,648
-Garlic will make it better, Nam-no.
-He says add garlic.

1809
01:08:05,714 --> 01:08:08,184
He doesn't even hesitate.

1810
01:08:08,250 --> 01:08:11,587
He tells them to put stuff in,
take stuff out, and whatnot.

1811
01:08:11,654 --> 01:08:13,422
Poong's in control from behind.

1812
01:08:13,489 --> 01:08:15,591
NOODLE NAM-NO MUST COOK THE NOODLES

1813
01:08:16,292 --> 01:08:17,660
That's too much!

1814
01:08:17,726 --> 01:08:19,361
A HANDFUL

1815
01:08:19,428 --> 01:08:21,397
-Hey, that's too much!
-That's a lot.

1816
01:08:21,464 --> 01:08:22,598
He's making a lot.

1817
01:08:22,665 --> 01:08:23,632
It's for me.

1818
01:08:23,699 --> 01:08:25,301
A-HA

1819
01:08:25,367 --> 01:08:28,771
He's cooking
both for the guest and himself.

1820
01:08:29,872 --> 01:08:31,707
He's cooking a huge amount of noodles.

1821
01:08:31,774 --> 01:08:35,177
Soo, you'll get one-ninth
of those noodles.

1822
01:08:35,244 --> 01:08:37,279
The rest is for him.

1823
01:08:37,847 --> 01:08:38,914
FINISHED COOKING THE SHRIMPS

1824
01:08:39,181 --> 01:08:40,082
WASH IN COLD WATER TO COOL

1825
01:08:40,149 --> 01:08:41,150
What is that? Shrimp?

1826
01:08:41,784 --> 01:08:42,718
Shrimp…

1827
01:08:43,686 --> 01:08:46,088
Sam picks up the bean sprouts.

1828
01:08:46,155 --> 01:08:48,023
Are the bean sprouts for your pasta?

1829
01:08:48,090 --> 01:08:49,091
Yes, they are.

1830
01:08:50,459 --> 01:08:53,496
-I really love bean sprouts.
-You do?

1831
01:08:53,562 --> 01:08:56,065
Soo just said he loves bean sprouts.

1832
01:08:56,132 --> 01:08:57,299
COOLING IN ICED WATER

1833
01:08:57,366 --> 01:08:58,534
-Good for Sam!
-Emergency.

1834
01:08:58,601 --> 01:08:59,735
It's an emergency.

1835
01:08:59,802 --> 01:09:01,203
-The meat.
-LA-style <i>galbi</i>.

1836
01:09:01,270 --> 01:09:03,139
-LA-style <i>galbi</i>.
-It's LA-style <i>galbi</i>.

1837
01:09:03,205 --> 01:09:06,075
-He's using a skewer, right?
-In green onion oil. Yes.

1838
01:09:06,142 --> 01:09:07,109
Grilling it in green onion oil.

1839
01:09:07,176 --> 01:09:09,645
Things are smooth sailing for Sam.
You have nine minutes left!

1840
01:09:09,712 --> 01:09:11,714
What's that? Soy sauce.

1841
01:09:11,780 --> 01:09:13,215
-What's that?
-He's making sauce.

1842
01:09:13,282 --> 01:09:14,650
Three spoons of soy sauce.

1843
01:09:14,717 --> 01:09:17,052
-Sugar.
-Sugar. Once, twice.

1844
01:09:17,119 --> 01:09:18,921
-A spoon and a half.
-A spoon and a half.

1845
01:09:18,988 --> 01:09:19,855
What's that?

1846
01:09:19,922 --> 01:09:21,991
-Sesame oil.
-Two spoons of sesame oil.

1847
01:09:22,057 --> 01:09:23,726
What's that sauce for?

1848
01:09:23,792 --> 01:09:24,727
Ah.

1849
01:09:25,794 --> 01:09:26,862
One second.

1850
01:09:27,863 --> 01:09:30,132
You don't have to answer me.

1851
01:09:30,199 --> 01:09:31,734
He's very distracted.

1852
01:09:31,800 --> 01:09:32,968
I feel bad for asking him.

1853
01:09:33,035 --> 01:09:34,703
He's distracted with every response.

1854
01:09:34,770 --> 01:09:36,005
BUT HE BECOMES NAMNORGHINI WITH HIS KNIFE!

1855
01:09:36,071 --> 01:09:37,106
Eight minutes.

1856
01:09:37,173 --> 01:09:38,807
Nice and thin pieces.

1857
01:09:38,874 --> 01:09:40,009
He's so good with a knife.

1858
01:09:40,075 --> 01:09:41,243
He sliced a little too much.

1859
01:09:43,279 --> 01:09:44,313
COOKED BROCCOLI STEM

1860
01:09:44,380 --> 01:09:46,115
-Those look like cucumber strips.
-They do.

1861
01:09:46,182 --> 01:09:50,119
-It's like a cucumber.
-Those will add a crunch like a cucumber.

1862
01:09:50,185 --> 01:09:51,720
The stem is delicious.

1863
01:09:51,787 --> 01:09:54,590
-You can use the stem like that.
-Good idea.

1864
01:09:54,657 --> 01:09:57,293
Seven and a half minutes.
You're halfway done!

1865
01:09:58,127 --> 01:09:59,461
Is the fried filefish doing okay?

1866
01:09:59,528 --> 01:10:00,829
The fried fish looks delicious.

1867
01:10:00,896 --> 01:10:01,830
It looks delicious.

1868
01:10:01,897 --> 01:10:04,233
-The fried filefish looks good.
-Fried filefish.

1869
01:10:04,300 --> 01:10:06,569
-Not bad.
-Those look delicious.

1870
01:10:06,635 --> 01:10:09,038
-Those look like fried fish.
-They do.

1871
01:10:09,104 --> 01:10:12,308
-Or even fish <i>jeon</i>.
-Is that the result of soaking them?

1872
01:10:12,374 --> 01:10:14,710
-It's like filefish <i>jeon</i>.
-He's throwing them in again.

1873
01:10:14,777 --> 01:10:16,679
They're going back in.

1874
01:10:16,745 --> 01:10:17,680
Were they too tough?

1875
01:10:17,746 --> 01:10:19,982
Don't you need some more starch water?

1876
01:10:20,049 --> 01:10:22,151
-You should've put more batter on.
-Nam-no doesn't say a word.

1877
01:10:22,218 --> 01:10:23,886
LA-style <i>galbi</i>.

1878
01:10:25,187 --> 01:10:26,155
GRILLED GREEN ONION

1879
01:10:26,222 --> 01:10:28,090
He just grilled the short ribs.

1880
01:10:28,157 --> 01:10:30,059
-It doesn't seem too special.
-That looks good.

1881
01:10:30,960 --> 01:10:32,861
-<i>Galbi </i>and green onion?
-Yes.

1882
01:10:32,928 --> 01:10:34,129
-G and G.
-Yes.

1883
01:10:34,196 --> 01:10:36,899
-G and G?
-Yes, G and G.

1884
01:10:36,966 --> 01:10:38,801
-A grilled skewer.
-A grilled skewer.

1885
01:10:39,735 --> 01:10:42,271
-With the sauce? That has to be good.
-Over the fire.

1886
01:10:42,338 --> 01:10:44,673
-Six minutes left.
-All right.

1887
01:10:44,740 --> 01:10:48,611
Sam said he'd try to channel Poong today,

1888
01:10:48,677 --> 01:10:51,513
-but he's still not talking much.
-No.

1889
01:10:51,580 --> 01:10:53,882
-Say something, Sam!
-You have to talk a lot.

1890
01:10:53,949 --> 01:10:55,584
You just have to talk to Nam-no.

1891
01:10:55,651 --> 01:10:59,288
-You should be teasing him.
-The skewer is burning!

1892
01:10:59,355 --> 01:11:02,558
-No, it's not burning. It's the edges.
-It's charring at the bottom.

1893
01:11:02,625 --> 01:11:03,926
It's going to burn.

1894
01:11:04,493 --> 01:11:06,095
IT'S AN EMERGENCY

1895
01:11:06,161 --> 01:11:07,296
It's going to burn, Sam!

1896
01:11:07,863 --> 01:11:10,132
-That's good.
-He saves the skewer.

1897
01:11:10,199 --> 01:11:12,034
-It's okay.
-My wife often makes

1898
01:11:12,101 --> 01:11:15,304
-grilled chicken skewers for our kids.
-As a snack?

1899
01:11:15,371 --> 01:11:16,905
A-HA

1900
01:11:16,972 --> 01:11:20,576
-That skewer reminds me of her.
-Are you reminded of her?

1901
01:11:20,643 --> 01:11:22,511
-And my kids.
-I see.

1902
01:11:22,578 --> 01:11:25,914
His wife often makes
grilled skewers for their kids,

1903
01:11:25,981 --> 01:11:27,816
so he's thinking of his wife right now.

1904
01:11:27,883 --> 01:11:29,285
HAHA

1905
01:11:29,852 --> 01:11:31,820
A HEAVY POT OF NOODLES

1906
01:11:32,354 --> 01:11:36,058
-Look at the amount of noodles.
-Look at that.

1907
01:11:36,125 --> 01:11:38,160
-Nam-no's noodles are done.
-You don't have much time.

1908
01:11:38,227 --> 01:11:39,662
FRIED FILEFISH FILLET

1909
01:11:39,728 --> 01:11:41,130
Five minutes and thirty seconds.

1910
01:11:41,196 --> 01:11:42,731
That filefish looks delicious.

1911
01:11:42,798 --> 01:11:45,100
GOLDEN BROWN AND TASTY FILEFISH!

1912
01:11:45,501 --> 01:11:46,735
TOMATO CHOGOCHUJANG

1913
01:11:47,770 --> 01:11:48,837
COOLED PASTA

1914
01:11:48,904 --> 01:11:51,206
-The noodles.
-That looks intense.

1915
01:11:51,273 --> 01:11:55,744
The sauce looks too intense
compared to the pasta.

1916
01:11:56,345 --> 01:11:57,980
The flavors might be a bit too strong.

1917
01:11:58,047 --> 01:11:58,881
DON'T WORRY!

1918
01:12:00,749 --> 01:12:01,917
Five minutes and ten seconds.

1919
01:12:03,218 --> 01:12:04,753
Nam-no strains the noodles.

1920
01:12:05,321 --> 01:12:07,256
He washed them for ages.

1921
01:12:07,323 --> 01:12:08,824
-Why did you make so much?
-It's too much.

1922
01:12:08,891 --> 01:12:10,259
It's as if it's for a cafeteria.

1923
01:12:10,326 --> 01:12:13,028
-He made it for himself.
-Why did you make so much?

1924
01:12:13,095 --> 01:12:14,697
Why do you need so many noodles?

1925
01:12:14,763 --> 01:12:17,299
It's like he's hand-washing laundry.

1926
01:12:17,366 --> 01:12:19,168
Why did you grab so many noodles?

1927
01:12:19,234 --> 01:12:20,936
-Yes, that's too much.
-Come on!

1928
01:12:21,003 --> 01:12:22,204
HAPPY

1929
01:12:22,271 --> 01:12:24,740
-You don't even have time. Cut it out.
-And the noodles will taste bland.

1930
01:12:24,807 --> 01:12:27,142
Jung-hwan, please report from the kitchen!

1931
01:12:27,209 --> 01:12:29,311
-Why did you make so much?
-Is it for <i>japchae </i>or what?

1932
01:12:30,145 --> 01:12:32,214
SWEET AND SALTY
SOY SAUCE NOODLES!

1933
01:12:32,281 --> 01:12:34,083
-That looks good.
-We can all have a bowl each.

1934
01:12:34,149 --> 01:12:35,684
Everyone in the studio can.

1935
01:12:35,751 --> 01:12:38,721
-It's turning into a village feast.
-You don't have enough sauce.

1936
01:12:38,787 --> 01:12:41,390
-He'll take a huge bite to check.
-He needs lots of sauce too.

1937
01:12:41,457 --> 01:12:43,692
-What is this?
-Look at how much he eats.

1938
01:12:43,759 --> 01:12:45,694
He doesn't seem to have enough sauce.

1939
01:12:45,761 --> 01:12:48,330
He ate a bowl's worth of noodles
just to check the taste.

1940
01:12:48,397 --> 01:12:50,599
-Nam-no fills himself up with noodles.
-Sam.

1941
01:12:50,666 --> 01:12:52,368
You need to bother him.

1942
01:12:52,434 --> 01:12:54,169
He's doing well so far.

1943
01:12:54,236 --> 01:12:57,339
-Ask him what he's making.
-This is enough for a sports team.

1944
01:12:58,240 --> 01:12:59,441
FLINCHES

1945
01:12:59,508 --> 01:13:01,343
What are the wheat noodles like?

1946
01:13:01,410 --> 01:13:03,679
-So? What's it like?
-Isn't it bland?

1947
01:13:03,746 --> 01:13:05,814
Can he capture Soo's heart with it?

1948
01:13:06,382 --> 01:13:07,750
Definitely.

1949
01:13:07,816 --> 01:13:08,650
Whoa.

1950
01:13:09,218 --> 01:13:10,519
RISING EXPECTATIONS

1951
01:13:10,586 --> 01:13:11,420
Really?

1952
01:13:11,487 --> 01:13:12,755
Are you serious?

1953
01:13:12,821 --> 01:13:14,656
He didn't add anything too special.

1954
01:13:14,723 --> 01:13:15,758
What's this sauce made of?

1955
01:13:15,824 --> 01:13:17,393
Soy sauce and sesame oil.

1956
01:13:17,459 --> 01:13:20,028
Yes, the sauce he made
with three spoons of sesame oil.

1957
01:13:20,095 --> 01:13:23,232
-It's really nutty.
-A spoon and a half of sugar.

1958
01:13:23,298 --> 01:13:24,466
It's as smooth as Soo.

1959
01:13:24,533 --> 01:13:27,069
-I see. The sauce must be nice.
-It's quite good.

1960
01:13:27,136 --> 01:13:28,771
The skewer. Sam's skewer.

1961
01:13:28,837 --> 01:13:29,972
GRILLED ON THE CORNER OF THE FIRE

1962
01:13:30,606 --> 01:13:31,607
BEAN SPROUTS

1963
01:13:32,374 --> 01:13:34,209
9. COOL PASTA AND BEAN SPROUTS,
MIX WITH SAUCE

1964
01:13:34,276 --> 01:13:35,577
-Jung-hwan.
-Yes?

1965
01:13:35,644 --> 01:13:37,479
Sam's pasta looks very spicy.

1966
01:13:37,546 --> 01:13:38,580
-This one?
-Yes.

1967
01:13:38,647 --> 01:13:40,048
-It's too red.
-This?

1968
01:13:40,115 --> 01:13:41,950
It looks like <i>jjolmyeon</i> to me.

1969
01:13:42,017 --> 01:13:43,318
-Right?
-Yes.

1970
01:13:43,385 --> 01:13:45,354
-It's like <i>jjolmyeon </i>sauce.
-Will you try the sauce?

1971
01:13:45,421 --> 01:13:46,522
Isn't this supposed to be pasta?

1972
01:13:46,588 --> 01:13:47,623
It looks spicy.

1973
01:13:47,689 --> 01:13:49,992
Let me try it and see if it's spicy.

1974
01:13:50,058 --> 01:13:51,193
-The pasta.
-Let me try the sauce.

1975
01:13:51,693 --> 01:13:53,796
Is the sauce spicy or not?

1976
01:13:54,363 --> 01:13:57,032
WHAT'S THE MIX OF TOMATO, CHOGOCHUJANG,
AND PASTA LIKE?

1977
01:13:57,099 --> 01:13:58,367
What do you think?

1978
01:13:58,434 --> 01:14:00,068
-It's not spicy.
-It's not?

1979
01:14:00,135 --> 01:14:02,337
It tastes sweeter than it is spicy.

1980
01:14:03,038 --> 01:14:05,507
-Did you add ginger?
-Garlic.

1981
01:14:05,574 --> 01:14:08,644
Garlic. I see.
It has a strong garlic flavor.

1982
01:14:08,710 --> 01:14:10,779
-A strong garlic flavor.
-Korean-style pasta.

1983
01:14:10,846 --> 01:14:12,080
Do you like garlic?

1984
01:14:12,147 --> 01:14:13,148
OF COURSE

1985
01:14:13,215 --> 01:14:14,950
He's sitting here, gulping.

1986
01:14:15,017 --> 01:14:17,085
-It has a strong garlic flavor.
-It's an emergency.

1987
01:14:17,152 --> 01:14:18,287
That looks good.

1988
01:14:18,353 --> 01:14:20,989
-It suddenly turned red.
-Where's the soy-based sauce?

1989
01:14:21,056 --> 01:14:22,758
-I mixed it in.
-Are you mixing the two?

1990
01:14:22,825 --> 01:14:25,794
You added more sauce to the noodles?
And shrimp?

1991
01:14:25,861 --> 01:14:28,197
-Try some!
-I had some already.

1992
01:14:28,263 --> 01:14:30,999
-You have no time for that.
-He has enough noodles.

1993
01:14:31,066 --> 01:14:33,202
Did the flavor change?

1994
01:14:33,268 --> 01:14:35,070
-You have to finish first.
-What's it like?

1995
01:14:35,137 --> 01:14:36,238
THE SOY SAUCE VERSION WAS ALREADY GOOD

1996
01:14:36,305 --> 01:14:38,774
This is 100 times better.

1997
01:14:38,841 --> 01:14:40,042
HAHAHAHA

1998
01:14:40,108 --> 01:14:41,977
-Is this <i>yuja</i> I smell?
-Yes.

1999
01:14:42,611 --> 01:14:44,680
-It's <i>yuja chogochujang</i>.
-<i>Yuja chogochujang</i>!

2000
01:14:44,746 --> 01:14:48,484
He first seasoned it with soy sauce,
then finished with <i>yuja chogochujang</i>.

2001
01:14:48,550 --> 01:14:49,518
If you finish second, you'll lose.

2002
01:14:49,585 --> 01:14:51,053
It tastes incredible.

2003
01:14:51,119 --> 01:14:51,954
Is it?

2004
01:14:52,020 --> 01:14:53,589
Sam needs to work some more on this.

2005
01:14:53,655 --> 01:14:54,990
Personally,

2006
01:14:55,057 --> 01:14:58,193
-I think the garlic is too strong.
-Did he add too much?

2007
01:14:58,260 --> 01:14:59,228
OH, NO

2008
01:14:59,294 --> 01:15:01,296
Then add some sesame oil.

2009
01:15:01,363 --> 01:15:02,931
-I'll do that.
-Cover up the garlic.

2010
01:15:02,998 --> 01:15:05,501
When I tried it,
I thought the garlic was too strong.

2011
01:15:05,567 --> 01:15:07,169
-Was the garlic strong?
-He seems almost done.

2012
01:15:07,236 --> 01:15:08,737
Add some sesame oil and finish.

2013
01:15:08,804 --> 01:15:09,638
Sesame oil.

2014
01:15:10,072 --> 01:15:11,106
GALBI AND GREEN ONION SKEWER

2015
01:15:11,340 --> 01:15:12,541
PUT THE G AND G SKEWER ON TOP

2016
01:15:12,608 --> 01:15:14,209
AND FINISH WITH A DASH OF SESAME OIL

2017
01:15:14,276 --> 01:15:16,078
-You must finish first.
-They're both noodle dishes,

2018
01:15:16,144 --> 01:15:18,714
so whoever finishes first
has an advantage.

2019
01:15:18,981 --> 01:15:19,882
RAW SNAPPER

2020
01:15:19,948 --> 01:15:20,983
RAW HALIBUT

2021
01:15:21,517 --> 01:15:22,951
8. MIX AND SERVE FISH WITH RED SAUCE

2022
01:15:23,018 --> 01:15:25,487
-Spicy raw fish salad.
-He's making raw fish salad.

2023
01:15:25,554 --> 01:15:27,523
Like that?
Like noodles with raw fish toppings?

2024
01:15:27,589 --> 01:15:29,491
-Raw fish noodles.
-What's the topping?

2025
01:15:29,558 --> 01:15:31,527
-Raw fish.
-Raw fish?

2026
01:15:31,593 --> 01:15:32,694
A-HA

2027
01:15:33,495 --> 01:15:35,364
-Wait, what about this?
-Do you have sesame seeds?

2028
01:15:35,430 --> 01:15:36,565
I couldn't find any.

2029
01:15:36,632 --> 01:15:37,933
-Filefish.
-What are you looking for?

2030
01:15:38,000 --> 01:15:39,635
-Filefish.
-Filefish.

2031
01:15:39,701 --> 01:15:40,536
Serve the filefish.

2032
01:15:40,602 --> 01:15:43,138
They're both almost done,
but Sam finishes his pasta first!

2033
01:15:43,205 --> 01:15:44,973
-The noodles are going to get soggy.
-The filefish.

2034
01:15:45,040 --> 01:15:47,075
-The filefish fillets are ready.
-The filefish.

2035
01:15:47,142 --> 01:15:48,610
We only need Nam-no to finish.

2036
01:15:48,677 --> 01:15:50,913
He fried the fish well
and almost forgot to serve it.

2037
01:15:50,979 --> 01:15:51,813
The fish looks good.

2038
01:15:51,880 --> 01:15:54,283
-He's different from you, Sung-jun.
-He sure is.

2039
01:15:54,349 --> 01:15:56,318
-He's good.
-He is.

2040
01:15:56,385 --> 01:15:57,252
BOILED SHRIMP

2041
01:15:57,319 --> 01:15:58,520
Does anyone have sesame seeds?

2042
01:15:58,587 --> 01:15:59,888
-Sesame.
-There wasn't any.

2043
01:16:00,455 --> 01:16:02,057
50 SECONDS LEFT!

2044
01:16:02,124 --> 01:16:04,359
Why don't we hope he'll find it somewhere?

2045
01:16:04,426 --> 01:16:06,795
-Forty-five seconds.
-Forty-five seconds. You have time.

2046
01:16:06,862 --> 01:16:07,796
You got time.

2047
01:16:07,863 --> 01:16:08,931
He was chopping green onion.

2048
01:16:08,997 --> 01:16:11,133
It's the last touch.

2049
01:16:11,199 --> 01:16:14,136
-It's the broth.
-Twenty seconds.

2050
01:16:14,202 --> 01:16:15,604
-Twenty seconds.
-Twenty seconds.

2051
01:16:15,671 --> 01:16:16,538
THE NOODLES ARE DONE

2052
01:16:16,605 --> 01:16:17,706
AS WELL AS THE FRIED FILEFISH

2053
01:16:17,773 --> 01:16:20,142
-Ring the bell, Nam-no!
-Nam-no!

2054
01:16:20,208 --> 01:16:23,078
-Nine. Eight.
-You served more than enough.

2055
01:16:23,145 --> 01:16:25,213
-Seven. Six.
-Seven. Six.

2056
01:16:25,280 --> 01:16:26,915
-Five.
-Five. Nam-no finishes too.

2057
01:16:26,982 --> 01:16:28,350
-It's over.
-Wow.

2058
01:16:29,918 --> 01:16:31,687
LOOKING FORWARD TO THE DISHES

2059
01:16:32,688 --> 01:16:35,691
A HEARTY AMOUNT OF NOODLE MEALS

2060
01:16:36,191 --> 01:16:39,428
How did they do all this in 15 minutes?

2061
01:16:39,494 --> 01:16:42,631
THAT'S THE CLASS OF CHEF & MY FRIDGE,
AND IT'S ALWAYS A SURPRISE!

2062
01:16:43,098 --> 01:16:44,533
This is insane.

2063
01:16:44,600 --> 01:16:48,270
Both meals were made just for Soo.

2064
01:16:48,937 --> 01:16:51,406
Sam finished first,

2065
01:16:51,473 --> 01:16:53,542
so please try his GoVid Pasta.

2066
01:16:54,109 --> 01:16:55,410
COLD BONE BROTH

2067
01:16:56,712 --> 01:16:59,247
SPICY AND SOUR TOMATO CHOGOCHUJANG PASTA

2068
01:17:00,515 --> 01:17:03,185
TENDER G AND G SKEWER

2069
01:17:04,186 --> 01:17:07,556
CHEF SAM'S GOVID PASTA

2070
01:17:08,423 --> 01:17:10,559
Where should he begin?

2071
01:17:10,626 --> 01:17:13,495
I chopped some granola
and sprinkled it on the pasta.

2072
01:17:13,862 --> 01:17:14,863
COVERED WITH CHOPPED GRANOLA

2073
01:17:14,930 --> 01:17:16,064
Granola.

2074
01:17:16,131 --> 01:17:17,766
He didn't have any sesame seeds.

2075
01:17:17,833 --> 01:17:21,203
-That's why you went with Plan B.
-My gosh.

2076
01:17:21,269 --> 01:17:24,473
Try the noodles with some broccoli pieces.

2077
01:17:24,539 --> 01:17:26,908
As you eat, you can have
a piece of meat too,

2078
01:17:26,975 --> 01:17:29,344
then try the broth.
Just enjoy it as you like.

2079
01:17:29,411 --> 01:17:33,181
-The broccoli…
-I often have boiled broccoli at home,

2080
01:17:33,248 --> 01:17:36,151
and a lot of the stem
gets left over, right?

2081
01:17:36,218 --> 01:17:38,453
So I always throw away the stem.

2082
01:17:38,520 --> 01:17:41,523
-It's much more nutritious. The stem.
-It is?

2083
01:17:41,590 --> 01:17:44,159
Then should I just eat the stem
and throw out the florets?

2084
01:17:44,726 --> 01:17:46,061
GO SOO'S WAY OF THINKING

2085
01:17:46,128 --> 01:17:47,029
Why throw out anything?

2086
01:17:47,095 --> 01:17:49,931
-Well, it depends on your preference.
-That's true.

2087
01:17:50,499 --> 01:17:52,668
SOO'S HUMOR MAKES HIM CRY
FROM LAUGHING TOO HARD

2088
01:17:52,734 --> 01:17:55,671
I finally understand the way he talks.

2089
01:17:55,737 --> 01:17:56,838
UNDERSTANDING SOO'S LANGUAGE

2090
01:17:56,905 --> 01:17:59,374
-Let me try the broth first.
-The broth first.

2091
01:17:59,441 --> 01:18:01,943
-He reaches out for the broth first.
-In reverse order.

2092
01:18:02,511 --> 01:18:04,713
-He must've been curious.
-But most people

2093
01:18:04,780 --> 01:18:07,549
usually eat the dish
the way the chef recommends them to.

2094
01:18:07,616 --> 01:18:10,652
-He has that rebel in him.
-He goes for the broth first.

2095
01:18:10,719 --> 01:18:11,920
He doesn't follow instructions.

2096
01:18:11,987 --> 01:18:14,423
I like to drink the broth
before I work on the main dish.

2097
01:18:14,489 --> 01:18:16,024
Lining the stomach.

2098
01:18:16,091 --> 01:18:18,760
He's going to go in now
after stretching his neck once.

2099
01:18:18,827 --> 01:18:21,296
First things first,
let's all pull out a 500-won coin each.

2100
01:18:23,031 --> 01:18:24,533
All right. And?

2101
01:18:26,568 --> 01:18:28,804
A BIG BITE

2102
01:18:31,273 --> 01:18:32,507
He eats so well.

2103
01:18:32,574 --> 01:18:34,342
Dang it. I'm hungry.

2104
01:18:34,910 --> 01:18:36,011
HIS INNER THOUGHTS CAME OUT

2105
01:18:36,078 --> 01:18:38,413
-This is rough.
-Jong-hyuk seems very hungry.

2106
01:18:38,480 --> 01:18:41,249
-The skewer.
-And a piece of meat.

2107
01:18:41,316 --> 01:18:44,386
That can take away the spiciness.

2108
01:18:44,453 --> 01:18:45,887
WILL IT TASTE AS GOOD AS IT LOOKS?

2109
01:18:46,388 --> 01:18:47,889
SMILING

2110
01:18:47,956 --> 01:18:49,591
This time, you're eating it with a smile.

2111
01:18:49,658 --> 01:18:51,927
Earlier, you ate
with a serious look on your face.

2112
01:18:51,993 --> 01:18:54,296
-You look much happier now.
-He can't hide it.

2113
01:18:54,362 --> 01:18:55,797
He can't hide the smile.

2114
01:18:55,864 --> 01:18:57,599
GoVid eats what
the David of our show made.

2115
01:18:59,568 --> 01:19:01,369
Do I have to tell you now?

2116
01:19:01,436 --> 01:19:03,972
When are you going to tell us, then?

2117
01:19:04,039 --> 01:19:05,407
So? What does it taste like?

2118
01:19:05,474 --> 01:19:06,441
Gosh.

2119
01:19:06,508 --> 01:19:07,709
WHAT'S IT LIKE?

2120
01:19:08,176 --> 01:19:09,344
PICKS UP THE CHOPSTICKS AGAIN?

2121
01:19:09,778 --> 01:19:11,313
SO UNPREDICTABLE

2122
01:19:11,379 --> 01:19:13,248
He does things however he wants to.

2123
01:19:13,315 --> 01:19:15,383
-He's a master at teasing.
-Yes.

2124
01:19:15,450 --> 01:19:17,185
He keeps leaving us curious.

2125
01:19:17,252 --> 01:19:19,654
You've probably never had
anything like this.

2126
01:19:19,721 --> 01:19:21,189
…anything like this.

2127
01:19:21,256 --> 01:19:22,824
Of course not.

2128
01:19:22,891 --> 01:19:23,792
How could we have?

2129
01:19:23,859 --> 01:19:25,560
You're eating that alone right now.

2130
01:19:25,627 --> 01:19:26,995
Stop teasing us.

2131
01:19:27,062 --> 01:19:29,531
How could we have?
You're eating that alone right now.

2132
01:19:29,598 --> 01:19:32,834
GOING BACK TO HIS ALONE TIME

2133
01:19:32,901 --> 01:19:35,203
It looks like he enjoys teasing us.

2134
01:19:35,270 --> 01:19:38,774
-Right? He's mean.
-Yes, he keeps teasing people around him.

2135
01:19:38,840 --> 01:19:40,776
He only looks good on the outside.

2136
01:19:41,910 --> 01:19:43,912
I didn't know he was good at teasing.

2137
01:19:43,979 --> 01:19:45,547
Good grief.

2138
01:19:45,614 --> 01:19:47,649
AND HE SIPS ON THE BROTH TOO

2139
01:19:47,716 --> 01:19:49,484
Can you tell us something?

2140
01:19:50,051 --> 01:19:51,219
Gosh.

2141
01:19:51,286 --> 01:19:54,055
Actually, this is something
I haven't mentioned,

2142
01:19:54,122 --> 01:19:56,424
but my favorite food in the whole world

2143
01:19:56,491 --> 01:19:57,325
is <i>jjolmyeon</i>.

2144
01:19:58,693 --> 01:20:00,862
GOOD ONE, SAM

2145
01:20:00,929 --> 01:20:03,331
And this tastes somewhat similar to it.

2146
01:20:03,398 --> 01:20:06,334
-Was there a hint of it?
-Yes, it was unexpected.

2147
01:20:06,401 --> 01:20:08,670
It's like going somewhere

2148
01:20:08,737 --> 01:20:11,807
and running into an old friend
without expecting it.

2149
01:20:13,341 --> 01:20:14,543
It's such a cinematic analogy.

2150
01:20:14,609 --> 01:20:16,311
Gosh.

2151
01:20:16,378 --> 01:20:19,614
He's finally giving us
a proper food review.

2152
01:20:19,681 --> 01:20:23,218
I've never had
anything like this in my life.

2153
01:20:23,785 --> 01:20:25,687
And I love the taste.

2154
01:20:25,754 --> 01:20:26,822
What about the skewer?

2155
01:20:26,888 --> 01:20:29,524
There's no need to say anything.
It's obviously delicious.

2156
01:20:31,393 --> 01:20:33,428
No need to explain it.

2157
01:20:33,495 --> 01:20:35,530
And with the granola…

2158
01:20:35,597 --> 01:20:36,731
Did you gasp?

2159
01:20:36,798 --> 01:20:39,401
It's many times better than sesame seeds.

2160
01:20:39,968 --> 01:20:41,736
I know sesame seeds are nutty,

2161
01:20:41,803 --> 01:20:43,338
but it's also rather strong.

2162
01:20:43,405 --> 01:20:45,607
Granola isn't that strong though.

2163
01:20:45,674 --> 01:20:46,608
Did you gasp?

2164
01:20:46,675 --> 01:20:48,076
Yes, I really gasped.

2165
01:20:48,143 --> 01:20:49,811
Hence, gasp-all-night.

2166
01:20:50,712 --> 01:20:52,247
Granola, gasp-all-night?

2167
01:20:52,814 --> 01:20:54,382
SMILING AT HIS DAD JOKE

2168
01:20:54,449 --> 01:20:56,651
-Hence, he gasped all night.
-Granola.

2169
01:20:56,718 --> 01:20:59,855
-I figured out what his humor is like.
-Me too.

2170
01:20:59,921 --> 01:21:01,590
I'll throw out some things to humor you.

2171
01:21:01,656 --> 01:21:04,125
-Okay.
-So that's granola for you.

2172
01:21:04,192 --> 01:21:05,894
It's a shame to stop now. May I have more?

2173
01:21:05,961 --> 01:21:07,929
-Of course.
-Feel free to eat more.

2174
01:21:07,996 --> 01:21:10,198
-But he also made noodles.
-There's another dish.

2175
01:21:10,265 --> 01:21:12,200
-My noodles are getting soggy!
-He can eat three packs of <i>ramyeon</i>.

2176
01:21:12,267 --> 01:21:15,337
-It'll be the same when it's soggy.
-Nam-no is sulking and pouting.

2177
01:21:16,004 --> 01:21:17,205
He can't hear anything.

2178
01:21:17,772 --> 01:21:19,207
HE'S ABOUT TO FALL INTO THE BOWL

2179
01:21:19,274 --> 01:21:21,443
He has his nose in the bowl.

2180
01:21:21,509 --> 01:21:22,477
He's finishing it.

2181
01:21:22,544 --> 01:21:26,081
He's holding the skewer tightly
in case someone steals it.

2182
01:21:26,147 --> 01:21:27,916
SO PROUD

2183
01:21:27,983 --> 01:21:29,551
No one will take it from you.

2184
01:21:29,618 --> 01:21:33,588
He doesn't care, even though
Jong-hyuk shouted out that he was hungry.

2185
01:21:34,122 --> 01:21:36,858
This time, he dips the meat in the sauce.

2186
01:21:36,925 --> 01:21:37,759
Mmm.

2187
01:21:37,826 --> 01:21:40,295
He must have a lot to say
with that old pal.

2188
01:21:40,829 --> 01:21:43,064
THAT'S ALL FOR THE TALK WITH HIS OLD PAL

2189
01:21:43,965 --> 01:21:45,500
Look at Nam-no's face.

2190
01:21:46,067 --> 01:21:47,602
MAXIMUM ANXIETY

2191
01:21:47,669 --> 01:21:49,104
These noodles are getting soggy.

2192
01:21:49,170 --> 01:21:51,606
Let's quickly move on to
Chef Nam-no's dish.

2193
01:21:52,173 --> 01:21:53,375
PROPERLY DEEP-FRIED FILEFISH

2194
01:21:54,342 --> 01:21:56,978
RAW FISH OVER LOTS OF NOODLES

2195
01:21:58,179 --> 01:22:01,816
SWEET AND SOUR YUJA CHOGOCHUJANG
WITH LOTS OF FISH AND SHRIMPS

2196
01:22:02,884 --> 01:22:05,186
SERVED WITH FRESH VEGETABLE JUICE

2197
01:22:06,288 --> 01:22:08,890
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S
YOU'RE GO SOO, I'M GUKSU

2198
01:22:08,957 --> 01:22:11,559
NOT A BIB

2199
01:22:11,626 --> 01:22:15,697
Think of this as red kimchi water.

2200
01:22:16,264 --> 01:22:17,699
KIMCHI WATER?

2201
01:22:17,766 --> 01:22:19,367
Let me cut the fish for you.

2202
01:22:19,434 --> 01:22:21,603
Sung-jun had failed at those.

2203
01:22:21,670 --> 01:22:23,838
-These looked different.
-I see.

2204
01:22:23,905 --> 01:22:25,440
So that's how you do it.

2205
01:22:25,507 --> 01:22:28,209
He soaked it in water,
coated it with starch, and deep-fried it.

2206
01:22:28,276 --> 01:22:30,178
HUH?

2207
01:22:30,245 --> 01:22:31,579
I guess it's not that tender.

2208
01:22:32,580 --> 01:22:34,316
-It's getting caught.
-Those scissors…

2209
01:22:34,382 --> 01:22:37,085
Please have a sip of this first, and…

2210
01:22:37,152 --> 01:22:39,120
He probably won't do as you say.

2211
01:22:39,187 --> 01:22:40,588
TAPS

2212
01:22:41,923 --> 01:22:44,225
THE FATHER UNCHOKES THE BABY

2213
01:22:44,292 --> 01:22:45,727
Wait, he's doing as he's instructed.

2214
01:22:45,794 --> 01:22:46,628
-It's like wine.
-Hey.

2215
01:22:46,695 --> 01:22:48,930
CURIOUS

2216
01:22:48,997 --> 01:22:51,800
Lemon juice, salt, and sugar.

2217
01:22:52,767 --> 01:22:54,169
What's it like?

2218
01:22:54,235 --> 01:22:56,037
The vegetable flavor

2219
01:22:56,604 --> 01:22:57,772
hits you nicely.

2220
01:22:57,839 --> 01:23:00,141
It's not overly strong.

2221
01:23:00,208 --> 01:23:03,611
-Does it taste like vegetable juice?
-Yes.

2222
01:23:03,678 --> 01:23:06,047
-It's like an aperitif.
-That's right.

2223
01:23:06,114 --> 01:23:07,649
-A refresher.
-After a few sips,

2224
01:23:07,716 --> 01:23:09,584
-the palate got cleansed.
-It did?

2225
01:23:09,651 --> 01:23:12,087
Sam's dish is slowly being forgotten.

2226
01:23:12,153 --> 01:23:14,456
Everything was intentional.

2227
01:23:14,522 --> 01:23:15,490
"Goodbye, Sam."

2228
01:23:15,557 --> 01:23:18,727
-That's made with <i>yuja chogochujang</i>.
-Yes, the smell of <i>yuja</i>…

2229
01:23:18,793 --> 01:23:21,463
The noodles got a bit soggy
during the wait.

2230
01:23:21,529 --> 01:23:22,931
It looks like a baseball.

2231
01:23:22,998 --> 01:23:24,666
-But it's still easy to separate.
-Yes.

2232
01:23:25,667 --> 01:23:27,469
STRETCH

2233
01:23:28,269 --> 01:23:30,572
STREEETCH

2234
01:23:31,039 --> 01:23:33,108
WILL HE EAT IT NOW?

2235
01:23:33,675 --> 01:23:34,876
NOT YET

2236
01:23:34,943 --> 01:23:35,777
LIFTING

2237
01:23:35,844 --> 01:23:36,678
DROPPING

2238
01:23:37,278 --> 01:23:40,348
PLAYING WITH THEIR HEARTS

2239
01:23:41,116 --> 01:23:43,018
This is something I never do,

2240
01:23:43,084 --> 01:23:45,587
but I want to ask for Soo's number today.

2241
01:23:45,653 --> 01:23:48,423
I want to have a conversation with him.

2242
01:23:48,490 --> 01:23:51,226
I think we'll have lots of fun chatting.

2243
01:23:52,293 --> 01:23:54,529
I don't think it'll taste spicy.

2244
01:23:55,096 --> 01:23:56,898
A BIG BITE

2245
01:23:56,965 --> 01:23:59,934
He said he could eat
three bags of <i>ramyeon </i>at once.

2246
01:24:00,001 --> 01:24:01,436
Can he add more sauce?

2247
01:24:01,503 --> 01:24:03,405
-Yes.
-Make it a bit soupy.

2248
01:24:03,471 --> 01:24:04,305
ADDING THE VEGGIE JUICE

2249
01:24:04,372 --> 01:24:06,608
What will it be like with the sauce?

2250
01:24:06,674 --> 01:24:09,644
-He made it a bit more watery.
-It's juicier now.

2251
01:24:09,711 --> 01:24:11,346
Like adding broth to <i>bibim-naengmyeon</i>.

2252
01:24:11,913 --> 01:24:13,681
A JUICIER BITE THIS TIME

2253
01:24:14,983 --> 01:24:16,484
THE NOODLES KEEP GOING IN

2254
01:24:17,052 --> 01:24:18,119
It looks good.

2255
01:24:18,186 --> 01:24:20,055
-It's like <i>mul-hoe</i> with noodles.
-That's it.

2256
01:24:20,121 --> 01:24:21,623
-Yes.
-It looks good.

2257
01:24:21,689 --> 01:24:24,059
It has the kind of spiciness
that's completely different

2258
01:24:24,125 --> 01:24:25,293
from the previous one.

2259
01:24:25,360 --> 01:24:26,661
-Yes.
-This one

2260
01:24:26,728 --> 01:24:29,931
had the sweet and sour notes
just like <i>jjolmyeon</i>

2261
01:24:29,998 --> 01:24:32,033
with a splash of spiciness.

2262
01:24:32,100 --> 01:24:36,237
But this one has an odd, yet fresh flavor.

2263
01:24:36,304 --> 01:24:38,139
-How?
-It tastes fresh?

2264
01:24:38,206 --> 01:24:40,608
Why don't you try
the fried filefish with it?

2265
01:24:41,242 --> 01:24:43,211
Should he have it with the noodles?

2266
01:24:43,278 --> 01:24:45,480
-Yes, right now would be perfect.
-Right now.

2267
01:24:45,547 --> 01:24:46,614
So?

2268
01:24:46,681 --> 01:24:48,016
I hope it's soft enough.

2269
01:24:48,083 --> 01:24:49,150
It must be so good.

2270
01:24:49,217 --> 01:24:50,452
And?

2271
01:24:50,518 --> 01:24:55,056
That really was the perfect time
to eat the fried filefish.

2272
01:24:55,123 --> 01:24:56,124
Wait.

2273
01:24:56,191 --> 01:24:58,626
-The raw fish…
-How did you make this?

2274
01:24:58,693 --> 01:25:00,161
Do you want to know?

2275
01:25:01,229 --> 01:25:03,098
He really loves noodles.

2276
01:25:03,164 --> 01:25:05,166
Soo, it's now time to decide.

2277
01:25:05,233 --> 01:25:07,035
THE MOMENT OF TRUTH

2278
01:25:07,102 --> 01:25:11,372
-Is it tough?
-It's so tough to choose one or the other.

2279
01:25:11,439 --> 01:25:13,108
<i>Press one for Nam-no</i>

2280
01:25:13,174 --> 01:25:14,442
<i>and two for Sam.</i>

2281
01:25:14,509 --> 01:25:17,879
Whose noodle dish did you like better?

2282
01:25:17,946 --> 01:25:18,947
Make your decision

2283
01:25:19,013 --> 01:25:20,915
and press the button.

2284
01:25:21,416 --> 01:25:22,550
PUSH

2285
01:25:23,118 --> 01:25:24,686
MADE HIS DECISION

2286
01:25:24,752 --> 01:25:25,920
He pushed a button.

2287
01:25:25,987 --> 01:25:28,156
He shook his head as he pushed a button.

2288
01:25:28,223 --> 01:25:30,692
I wonder which one he chose.

2289
01:25:30,758 --> 01:25:32,193
Go Soo's Noodle Master.

2290
01:25:32,260 --> 01:25:34,996
-Let's see the result.
-You never know.

2291
01:25:36,064 --> 01:25:37,265
-You never know.
-Nope.

2292
01:25:37,332 --> 01:25:40,502
-Like the previous round.
-He loves noodles but tries to stay away.

2293
01:25:40,568 --> 01:25:41,769
Is the winner Sam

2294
01:25:41,836 --> 01:25:43,004
or Nam-no?

2295
01:25:43,071 --> 01:25:44,939
This was their first cook-off.

2296
01:25:45,006 --> 01:25:46,741
Go Soo's Noodle Master!

2297
01:25:46,808 --> 01:25:48,076
Who's the winner?

2298
01:25:48,143 --> 01:25:50,378
Show us the winner!

2299
01:25:50,945 --> 01:25:51,846
Who won?

2300
01:25:51,913 --> 01:25:53,248
SAM KIM WINS

2301
01:25:53,314 --> 01:25:54,716
Sam wins!

2302
01:25:54,782 --> 01:25:57,385
CHEF SAM KIM'S GOVID PASTA WINS

2303
01:25:57,452 --> 01:25:58,953
Sam wins!

2304
01:25:59,020 --> 01:26:01,789
THAT'S SAM KIM, THE PASTA MASTER

2305
01:26:01,856 --> 01:26:05,326
I really loved Mr. Nam-no's dish too.

2306
01:26:05,393 --> 01:26:06,728
It was really good.

2307
01:26:08,163 --> 01:26:11,499
<i>But when I had the broccoli stem</i>
<i>with the pasta,</i>

2308
01:26:11,566 --> 01:26:14,435
<i>-I loved the texture so much.</i>
<i>-I see.</i>

2309
01:26:15,069 --> 01:26:16,471
Do you know what's funny?

2310
01:26:16,538 --> 01:26:20,909
Sung-jun won a star even after
he failed to use filefish fillets,

2311
01:26:20,975 --> 01:26:22,143
The filefish wasn't important.

2312
01:26:22,210 --> 01:26:26,014
-But Nam-no lost even after succeeding.
-The fish wasn't important.

2313
01:26:26,080 --> 01:26:27,916
The fish didn't have a big impact.

2314
01:26:27,982 --> 01:26:29,450
-No.
-Not really?

2315
01:26:29,517 --> 01:26:31,252
He just wanted the recipe.

2316
01:26:31,319 --> 01:26:32,587
It wasn't Go Soo's Filefish Master.

2317
01:26:32,654 --> 01:26:35,590
I keep missing the intention of the order.

2318
01:26:35,657 --> 01:26:40,728
I'd like to thank Webtoon Artist Poong
for my victory.

2319
01:26:40,795 --> 01:26:44,165
I have a feeling that
his Poongphobia will last for a while.

2320
01:26:44,232 --> 01:26:45,667
It's an emergency.

2321
01:26:45,733 --> 01:26:50,672
Sam takes the victory on their first
cook-off and wins his fifth star!

2322
01:26:50,738 --> 01:26:52,874
-It was delicious.
-Congratulations!

2323
01:26:52,941 --> 01:26:54,242
Sam Kim wins!

2324
01:26:54,309 --> 01:26:56,377
SAM GETS HIS 5TH STAR,
TYING IN 2ND PLACE WITH POONG

2325
01:26:57,979 --> 01:26:59,714
Jong-hyuk is a veteran actor

2326
01:26:59,781 --> 01:27:01,516
and a dad who's like a friend to his kids.

2327
01:27:01,583 --> 01:27:02,750
Even on <i>Dad! Where Are We Going?</i>,

2328
01:27:02,817 --> 01:27:05,019
he'd just let Joon-su roam around freely.

2329
01:27:05,086 --> 01:27:06,187
I'd ask, "What's Daddy doing?"

2330
01:27:06,254 --> 01:27:07,455
And he'd go, "He's sleeping."

2331
01:27:07,522 --> 01:27:08,756
A FREE-RANGE PARENTING EXPERT

2332
01:27:08,823 --> 01:27:11,192
And now, Joon-su is in college.

2333
01:27:11,259 --> 01:27:13,328
When I ask what he's doing,
he goes, "I'm drinking."

2334
01:27:13,394 --> 01:27:14,629
10 JOON-SU NOW DRINKS

2335
01:27:14,696 --> 01:27:16,297
So I was more flustered.

2336
01:27:16,364 --> 01:27:17,932
-We present his fridge!
-Fridge!

2337
01:27:17,999 --> 01:27:19,100
THAT'S AWESOME

2338
01:27:19,167 --> 01:27:20,935
It's bursting with food!

2339
01:27:21,002 --> 01:27:22,637
This is insane.

2340
01:27:22,704 --> 01:27:23,805
Those are all for my kids.

2341
01:27:23,871 --> 01:27:24,906
Joon-su eats most of those.

2342
01:27:24,973 --> 01:27:26,274
NONE OF THOSE ARE FOR THE DAD

2343
01:27:26,341 --> 01:27:28,209
BUT TODAY, THEY'LL COOK JUST FOR JONG-HYUK

2344
01:27:28,776 --> 01:27:30,545
A FEAST OF IN-SEASON SPRING DISHES

2345
01:27:30,612 --> 01:27:31,646
SPLASH

2346
01:27:31,713 --> 01:27:32,814
Was that cucumber?

2347
01:27:32,880 --> 01:27:34,115
<i>I'll capture the old dude's appetite.</i>

2348
01:27:34,182 --> 01:27:35,183
<i>I love old dude's food.</i>

2349
01:27:35,250 --> 01:27:36,951
-I'm an old dude myself.
-You're an old dude.

2350
01:27:37,018 --> 01:27:38,720
If you look closely,
I have hair on my chin.

2351
01:27:38,786 --> 01:27:39,754
I'm an actual old dude.

2352
01:27:39,821 --> 01:27:41,055
GROWING A BEARD TO WIN?

2353
01:27:41,122 --> 01:27:42,523
Does it feel like spring?

2354
01:27:42,590 --> 01:27:44,759
It's an explosion of spring.

2355
01:27:44,826 --> 01:27:45,793
It's not just spring.

2356
01:27:45,860 --> 01:27:46,928
It's spurting.

2357
01:27:48,429 --> 01:27:49,897
WHO CAPTURED THE FLAVOR OF SPRING?

2358
01:27:53,067 --> 01:27:54,469
It looks like your beard has grown.

2359
01:27:54,535 --> 01:27:56,471
I have to go and shave it off.
It grew out.

2360
01:28:07,749 --> 01:28:12,553
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
